{"title_page": "Clathrate hydrate", "text_new": "[[File:Gashydrat mit Struktur.jpg|thumb|right|Methane clathrate block embedded in the sediment of hydrate ridge, off Oregon, USA]]\n'''Clathrate hydrates''', or '''gas clathrates''', '''gas hydrates''', '''clathrates''', '''hydrates''', etc., are [[crystal]]line water-based [[solid]]s physically resembling [[ice]], in which small [[Chemical polarity|non-polar]] [[molecule]]s (typically [[gas]]es) or [[Chemical polarity|polar]] molecules with large hydrophobic [[Moiety (chemistry)|moieties]] are trapped inside \"cages\" of [[hydrogen bond]]ed, frozen [[water (molecule)|water molecules]].  In other words, clathrate hydrates are [[clathrate compound]]s in which the host molecule is [[water]] and the guest molecule is typically a gas or liquid.  Without the support of the trapped molecules, the [[Crystal structure|lattice]] structure of hydrate clathrates would collapse into conventional ice crystal structure or liquid water. Most low molecular weight gases, including {{oxygen}}<sub>2</sub>, {{hydrogen}}<sub>2</sub>, {{nitrogen}}<sub>2</sub>, [[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]], [[methane|CH<sub>4</sub>]], [[hydrogen sulfide|H<sub>2</sub>S]], {{argon}}, {{krypton}}, and {{xenon}}, as well as some higher [[hydrocarbon]]s and [[freon]]s, will form [[hydrate]]s at suitable temperatures and pressures. Clathrate hydrates are not officially chemical compounds, as the sequestered molecules are never bonded to the lattice. The formation and decomposition of clathrate hydrates are [[Phase transition#Classification of phase transitions|first order phase transitions]], not chemical reactions. Their detailed formation and decomposition mechanisms on a molecular level are still not well understood.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Gao S |author2=House W|author3=Chapman WG | year = 2005 | title = NMR MRI Study of Gas Hydrate Mechanisms | volume = 109 | pages = 19090\u201319093 | doi = 10.1021/jp052071w | url = https://www.scribd.com/doc/9701479/NMR-MRI-Study-of-Gas-Hydrate-Mechanisms | accessdate = August 3, 2009 | pmid = 16853461 | issue = 41 | journal = The Journal of Physical Chemistry B |citeseerx=10.1.1.175.9193}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Gao S |author2=Chapman WG|author3=House W | year = 2005 | title = NMR and Viscosity Investigation of Clathrate Formation and Dissociation | journal = Ind. Eng. Chem. Res. | volume = 44 | pages = 7373\u20137379 | doi = 10.1021/ie050464b | url = https://www.scribd.com/doc/9701466/NMR-and-Viscosity-Investigation-of-Clathrate-Formation-and-Dissociation | accessdate = August 3, 2009 | issue = 19 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choudhary|first=Nilesh|last2=Chakrabarty|first2=Suman|last3=Roy|first3=Sudip|last4=Kumar|first4=Rajnish|date=2019-01-04|title=A comparison of different water models for melting point calculation of methane hydrate using molecular dynamics simulations|journal=Chemical Physics|volume=516|pages=6\u201314|doi=10.1016/j.chemphys.2018.08.036|issn=0301-0104}}</ref>\nClathrate hydrates were first documented in 1810 by [[Humphry Davy]] who found that water was a primary component of what was earlier thought to be solidified chlorine.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/experimentalres02faragoog |title=On Hydrate of Chlorine |year=1859 |accessdate=20 March 2014 |author=Michael Faraday |publisher=Quarterly Journal of Science }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ethomas.web.wesleyan.edu/ees123/clathrate.htm |title=Clathrates: little known components of the global carbon cycle |accessdate=13 December 2007 |date=November 2004 |author=Ellen Thomas |publisher=Wesleyan University }}</ref>\n\nClathrates have been found to occur naturally in large quantities. Around 6.4 trillion (6.4\u00d710<sup>12</sup>) tonnes of [[methane]] is trapped in deposits of [[methane clathrate]] on the deep [[ocean floor]].<ref>{{Cite journal | first = B. | last = Buffett | first2 = D. | last2 = Archer | title = Global inventory of methane clathrate: sensitivity to changes in the deep ocean | year = 2004 | pages = 185\u2013199 | journal = Earth Planet. Sci. Lett. | volume = 227 | issue = 3\u20134 |doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2004.09.005 | bibcode=2004E&PSL.227..185B}}</ref> Such deposits can be found on the [[Norwegian continental shelf]] in the northern headwall flank of the [[Storegga Slide]]. Clathrates can also exist as [[permafrost]], as at the [[Mallik gas hydrate site]] in the [[Mackenzie River|Mackenzie Delta]] of northwestern [[Canadian Arctic]]. These natural gas hydrates are seen as a potentially vast energy resource, but an economical extraction method has so far proven elusive. Clathrate hydrate has also been of great interest to as technology enabler for many applications like seawater desalination<ref>https://www.engineersaustralia.org.au/News/drinkable-water-cold-energy</ref>, gas storage<ref>https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/eco-friendly-ways-to-harness-natural-gas-efficiently</ref>, carbon dioxide capture & storage<ref>https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0360544215004120?via%3Dihub</ref>, cooling medium for data centre<ref>https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/nus-keppel-slng-in-tie-up-to-develop-better-cooling-technology-for-data</ref> and district cooling etc. Hydrocarbon clathrates cause problems for the petroleum industry, because they can form inside [[Pipeline transport|gas pipelines]], often resulting in obstructions. Deep sea deposition of [[carbon dioxide clathrate]] has been proposed as a method to remove this [[greenhouse gas]] from the atmosphere and control [[climate change]].\n\nClathrates are suspected to occur in large quantities on some outer [[planet]]s, [[natural satellite|moons]] and [[trans-Neptunian object]]s, binding gas at fairly high temperatures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pradeep|first=Thalappil|last2=Kumar|first2=Rajnish|last3=Choudhary|first3=Nilesh|last4=Ragupathy|first4=Gopi|last5=Bhuin|first5=Radha Gobinda|last6=Methikkalam|first6=Rabin Rajan J.|last7=Ghosh|first7=Jyotirmoy|date=2019-01-29|title=Clathrate hydrates in interstellar environment|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=116|issue=5|pages=1526\u20131531|doi=10.1073/pnas.1814293116|issn=0027-8424|pmid=30630945|pmc=6358667}}</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\n\n[[Image:HydrateStructures.jpg|thumb|Cages building the different gas hydrate structures.]]\n\nGas hydrates usually form two [[Crystallography|crystallographic]] cubic structures: structure (Type) I (named ''sI'') and structure (Type) II (named ''sII'')<ref>von Stackelberg, M. & M\u00fcller, H. M. (1954) ''Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Elektrochemie'' '''58''', 1, 16, 83</ref> of space groups <math>Pm\\overline{3}n</math>  and <math>Fd\\overline{3}m</math> respectively. Seldom, a third hexagonal structure of space group <math>P6/mmm</math> may be observed (Type H).<ref>Sloan E. D., Jr. (1998) Clathrate hydrates of natural gases. Second edition, Marcel Dekker Inc.:New York.</ref>\n\nThe unit cell of Type I consists of 46 water molecules, forming two types of cages \u2013 small and large. The unit cell contains two small cages and six large ones. The small cage has the shape of a pentagonal [[dodecahedron]] (5<sup>12</sup>) (which is not a regular dodecahedron) and the large one that of a [[tetradecahedron]], specifically a [[hexagonal truncated trapezohedron]] (5<sup>12</sup>6<sup>2</sup>).  Together, they form a version of the [[Weaire\u2013Phelan structure]]. Typical guests forming Type I hydrates are [[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] in [[carbon dioxide clathrate]] and [[methane|CH<sub>4</sub>]] in [[methane clathrate]].\n\nThe unit cell of Type II consists of 136 water molecules, again forming two types of cages \u2013 small and large. In this case there are sixteen small cages and eight large ones in the unit cell.  The small cage again has the shape of a pentagonal dodecahedron (5<sup>12</sup>), but the large one is a [[hexadecahedron]] (5<sup>12</sup>6<sup>4</sup>). Type II hydrates are formed by gases like O<sub>2</sub> and N<sub>2</sub>.\n\nThe unit cell of Type H consists of 34 water molecules, forming three types of cages \u2013 two small ones of different types, and one \"huge\". In this case, the unit cell consists of three small cages of type 5<sup>12</sup>, two small ones of type 4<sup>3</sup>5<sup>6</sup>6<sup>3</sup> and one huge of type 5<sup>12</sup>6<sup>8</sup>. The formation of Type H requires the cooperation of two guest gases (large and small) to be stable. It is the large cavity that allows structure H hydrates to fit in large molecules (e.g. [[butane]], [[hydrocarbon]]s), given the presence of other smaller help gases to fill and support the remaining cavities. Structure H hydrates were suggested to exist in the Gulf of Mexico. Thermogenically-produced supplies of heavy hydrocarbons are common there.\n\n== Hydrates in the universe ==\n\nIro ''et al.'',<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Iro | first1 = N. | last2 = Gautier | first2 = D. | last3 = Hersant | first3 = F. | last4 = Bockel\u00e9e-Morvan | first4 = D. | last5 = Lunine | first5 = J. I. | year = 2003 | title = An interpretation of the Nitrogen deficiency in comets | url = | journal = Icarus | volume = 161 | issue = 2| page = 513 |bibcode=2003Icar..161..511I |doi=10.1016/S0019-1035(02)00038-6 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.487.722 }}</ref> trying to interpret the [[nitrogen]] deficiency in [[comet]]s, stated most of the conditions for hydrate formation in the [[Protoplanetary disk|protoplanetary nebulae]], surrounding the [[Main sequence|pre-main and main sequence]] stars were fulfilled, despite the rapid grain growth to meter scale. The key was to provide enough microscopic ice particles exposed to a gaseous environment. Observations of the [[Radiometry|radiometric]] [[Continuum (theory)|continuum]] of [[Protoplanetary disk|circumstellar discs]] around <math>\\tau</math>[[T Tauri star|-Tauri]] and [[Herbig Ae/Be stars]] suggest massive dust disks consisting of millimeter-sized grains, which disappear after several million years (e.g.,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Beckwith | first1 = S. V. W. | last2 = Henning | first2 = T. | last3 = Nakagawa | first3 = Y. | year = 2000 | title = Dust properties and assembly of large particles in protoplanetary disks | url = | journal = Protostars and Planets | volume = IV | issue = | page = 533 | arxiv=astro-ph/9902241 |bibcode = 2000prpl.conf..533B }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Natta | first1 = A. | last2 = Grinin | first2 = V. | last3 = Mannings | first3 = V. | year = 2000 | title = Properties and Evolution of Disks around Pre-Main-Sequence Stars of Intermediate Mass | url = | journal = Protostars and Planets | volume = IV | issue = | page = 559 |hdl=2014/17884 | bibcode = 2000prpl.conf..559N }}</ref>). A lot of work on detecting water ices in the Universe was done on the [[Infrared Space Observatory]] (ISO). For instance, broad [[Spectral bands|emission bands]] of water ice at 43 and 60 \u03bcm were found in the disk of the isolated [[Herbig Ae/Be stars|Herbig Ae/Be star]] HD 100546 in [[Musca]]. The one at 43 \u03bcm is much weaker than the one at 60 \u03bcm, which means the water ice, is located in the outer parts of the disk at temperatures below 50 K.<ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 1998A&A...332L..25M | author=Malfait, K., Waelkens, C., Waters, L. B. F. M., Vandenbussche, B., Huygen, E. & de Graauw, M. S. |year=1998 |title= The spectrum of the young star HD 100546 observed with the Infrared Space Observatory |journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=332 |pages= L25\u2013L28 | last2 = Waelkens | last3 = Waters | last4 = Vandenbussche | last5 = Huygen | last6 = De Graauw}}</ref> There is also another broad ice feature between 87 and 90 \u03bcm, which is very similar to the one in [[NGC 6302]] <ref>Barlow, M.J., In the proceedings of \u2018ISO\u2019s view on stellar evolution\u2019, Noordwijkerhout, July 1\u20134, 1997</ref> (the Bug or Butterfly nebula in [[Scorpius]]). Crystalline ices were also detected in the proto-planetary disks of [[Epsilon Eridani|\u03b5-Eridani]] and the isolated Fe star HD 142527<ref>{{cite journal | title= Modeling the infrared emission from the \u03b5-Eridani disk| doi = 10.1086/380495 | year= 2003 | last1= Li | first1= Aigen | last2= Lunine | first2= J. I. | last3= Bendo | first3= G. J. | journal= The Astrophysical Journal | volume= 598 | issue = 1 | pages= L51\u2013L54 | bibcode=2003ApJ...598L..51L|arxiv = astro-ph/0311069 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Malfait | first1 = K. | last2 = Waelkens | first2 = C. | last3 = Bouwman | first3 = J. | last4 = De Koter | first4 = A. | last5 = Waters | first5 = L. B. F. M. | year = 1999 | title = The ISO spectrum of the young star HD 142527 | url = | journal = Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume = 345 | issue = | page = 181 |bibcode=1999A&A...345..181M}}</ref> in [[Lupus (constellation)|Lupus]]. 90% of the ice in the latter was found crystalline at temperature around 50 K. [[Hubble Space Telescope|HST]] demonstrated that relatively old [[Protoplanetary disk|circumstellar disks]], as the one around the 5-million-year-old B9.5Ve<ref>Jaschek, C. & Jaschek, M. (1992) ''Astronomy and Astrophysics'', '''95''', p. 535</ref> [[Herbig Ae/Be stars|Herbig Ae/Be star]] HD 141569A, are dusty.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Clampin | first1 = M. | last2 = Krist | first2 = J. E. | last3 = Ardila | first3 = D. R. | last4 = Golimowski | first4 = D. A. | last5 = Hartig | first5 = G. F. | last6 = Ford | first6 = H. C. | last7 = Illingworth | first7 = G. D. | last8 = Bartko | first8 = F. | last9 = Bentez | first9 = N. | last10 = Blakeslee | first10 = J. P. | last11 = Bouwens | first11 = R. J. | last12 = Broadhurst | first12 = T. J. | last13 = Brown | first13 = R. A. | last14 = Burrows | first14 = C. J. | last15 = Cheng | first15 = E. S. | last16 = Cross | first16 = N. J. G. | last17 = Feldman | first17 = P. D. | last18 = Franx | first18 = M. | last19 = Gronwall | first19 = C. | last20 = Infante | first20 = L. | last21 = Kimble | first21 = R. A. | last22 = Lesser | first22 = M. P. | last23 = Martel | first23 = A. R. | last24 = Menanteau | first24 = F. | last25 = Meurer | first25 = G. R. | last26 = Miley | first26 = G. K. | last27 = Postman | last29 = Sirianni | first29 = M. | last30 = Sparks | first30 = W. B. | last28 = Rosati | first28 = P. | doi = 10.1086/375460 | title = Hubble Space TelescopeACS Coronagraphic Imaging of the Circumstellar Disk around HD 141569A | first27 = M. | journal = The Astronomical Journal | volume = 126 | issue = 1 | pages = 385\u2013392 | year = 2003 | pmid =  | pmc = | displayauthors = 29|arxiv = astro-ph/0303605 |bibcode = 2003AJ....126..385C }}</ref> Li & Lunine<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Li | first1 = A. | last2 = Lunine | first2 = J. I. | year = 2003 | title = Modeling the infrared emission from the HD 141569A disk | url = | journal = Astrophysical Journal | volume = 594 | issue = 2| pages = 987\u20131010 | doi = 10.1086/376939 | bibcode=2003ApJ...594..987L|arxiv = astro-ph/0311070 }}</ref> found water ice there. Knowing the ices usually exist at the outer parts of the [[Protoplanetary disk|proto-planetary nebulae]], Hersant ''et al.''<ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 2004P&SS...52..623H | doi=10.1016/j.pss.2003.12.011 | title = Enrichment in volatiles in the giant planets of the Solar System | year = 2004 | last1 = Hersant | first1 = F | journal = Planetary and Space Science | volume = 52 | issue = 7 | pages = 623\u2013641 }}</ref> proposed an interpretation of the [[Volatility (physics)|volatile]] enrichment, observed in the four [[Gas giant|giant planets]] of the [[Solar System]], with respect to the Solar [[Abundance of the chemical elements|abundances]]. They assumed the [[Volatility (physics)|volatiles]] had been trapped in the form of hydrates and incorporated in the [[planetesimal]]s flying in the [[Protoplanet|protoplanets\u2019]] feeding zones.\n\nKieffer ''et al.'' (2006) hypothesized that the geyser activity in the south polar region of [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]] originates from clathrate hydrates, where carbon dioxide, methane, and nitrogen are released when exposed to the vacuum of space through the \"[[Tiger Stripes (Enceladus)|Tiger Stripe]]\" fractures found in that area.<ref name=Kieffer2006>{{cite journal| first=Susan W.| last= Kieffer|author2=Xinli Lu |author3=Craig M. Bethke |author4=John R. Spencer |author5=Stephen Marshak |author6=Alexandra Navrotsky | year=2006| doi=10.1126/science.1133519| title=A Clathrate Reservoir Hypothesis for Enceladus' South Polar Plume| journal=Science| volume=314| issue=5806| pages=1764\u20131766| pmid=17170301| bibcode=2006Sci...314.1764K| url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/d23f6cd66b2089fcb3a9e7c4622a8fd4bc078c4a}}</ref> However, subsequent analysis of plume material makes it more likely that the geysers on Enceladus derive from a salty subsurface ocean.<ref name=\"SCI-20140404\">{{cite journal |last1=Iess |first1=L. |last2=Stevenson |first2=D.J. |last3=Parisi |first3=M. |last4=Hemingway |first4=D. |last5=Jacobson |first5=R.A. |last6=Lunine |first6=J.I. |last7=Nimmo |first7=F. |last8=Armstrong |first8=J.w. |last9=Asmar |first9=S.w. |last10=Ducci |first10=M. |last11=Tortora |first11=P. |title=The Gravity Field and Interior Structure of Enceladus |date=April 4, 2014 |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=344 |number=6179 |pages=78\u201380 |doi=10.1126/science.1250551 |bibcode=2014Sci...344...78I |pmid=24700854|url=https://authors.library.caltech.edu/45462/7/Iess-SM.pdf }}</ref>\n\n[[Carbon dioxide clathrate]] is believed to play a major role in different processes on Mars.  [[Hydrogen clathrate]] is likely to form in condensation nebulae for gas giants.\n\n== Hydrates on Earth==\n\n===Natural gas hydrates===\n{{main|Methane clathrate}}\nNaturally on [[Earth]] gas hydrates can be found on the [[seabed]], in ocean sediments,<ref>{{cite journal |year=1980 |author1=Kvenvolden, K. A. |author2=McMenamin, M. A. |title=Hydrates of Natural Gas: Their Geologic Occurrence |journal=U. S. Geological Survey Circular |volume=825 }}</ref> in deep lake sediments (e.g. [[Lake Baikal]]), as well as in the [[permafrost]] regions. The amount of [[methane]] potentially trapped in natural [[Methane clathrate|methane hydrate]] deposits may be significant (10<sup>15</sup> to 10<sup>17</sup> cubic metres),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn16848-ice-that-burns-could-be-a-green-fossil-fuel|title=Ice that burns could be a green fossil fuel|last=Marshall|first=Michael|date=March 26, 2009|work=New Scientist|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref> which makes them of major interest as a potential energy resource. Catastrophic release of methane from the decomposition of such deposits may lead to a global climate change, because [[methane|CH]]<sub>4</sub> is a more potent greenhouse gas than [[carbon dioxide|CO]]<sub>2</sub> (see [[Atmospheric methane]]). The fast decomposition of such deposits is considered a [[geohazard]], due to its potential to trigger [[landslide]]s, [[earthquake]]s  and [[tsunami]]s. However, natural gas hydrates do not contain only methane but also other [[hydrocarbon]] gases, as well as [[Hydrogen sulfide|H<sub>2</sub>S]] and [[Carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]]. [[Air hydrates]] are frequently observed in polar ice samples.\n\n[[Pingo]]s are common structures in permafrost regions.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Methane Leakage from Pingo-like Features on the Arctic Shelf, Beaufort Sea, NWT, Canada  |date=December 2005 | bibcode = 2005AGUFM.C11A1069U | author1 = Ussler, W. | author2 = Paull, C. K. | author3 = Lorenson, T. | author4 = Dallimore, S. | author5 = Medioli, B. | author6 = Blasco, S. | author7 = McLaughlin, F. | author8 = Nixon, F. M. | volume = 11 | pages = C11A\u20131069 | journal =  AGU Fall Meeting Abstracts}}</ref> Similar structures are found in deep water related to methane leakages. Significantly, gas hydrates can even be formed in the absence of a liquid phase. Under that situation, water is dissolved in gas or in liquid hydrocarbon phase.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Youssef | first1 = Z. | last2 = Barreau | first2 = A. | last3 = Mougin | first3 = P. | last4 = Jose | first4 = J. | last5 = Mokbel | first5 = I | year = 2009 | title =  | url = | journal = Ind. Eng. Chem. Res. | volume = 48 | issue = | pages = 4045\u20134050 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, both Japan and China announced that attempts at large-scale [[resource extraction]] of methane hydrates from under the seafloor were successful.  However, commercial-scale production remains years away. <ref>{{Cite web | url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-39971667 | title= China claims breakthrough in mining 'flammable ice' &#124; BBC News| date=2017-05-19}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/world/china-japan-extracts-combustible-ice-from-seafloor-a-step-towards-harnessing-a-legendary-frozen-fossil-fuel | title=China and Japan find way to extract 'combustible ice' from seafloor, harnessing a legendary frozen fossil fuel &#124; National Post| date=2017-05-19}}</ref>\n\n===Gas hydrates in pipelines===\nThermodynamic conditions favouring hydrate formation are often found in [[Pipeline transport|pipelines]]. This is highly undesirable, because the clathrate crystals might agglomerate and plug the line<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1021/ef800189k | title = Investigation of Interactions between Gas Hydrates and Several Other Flow Assurance Elements | year = 2008 | last1 = Gao | first1 = Shuqiang | journal = Energy & Fuels | volume = 22 | issue = 5 | pages = 3150\u20133153 }}</ref> and cause [[flow assurance]] failure and damage valves and instrumentation. The results can range from flow reduction to equipment damage.\n\n====Hydrate formation, prevention and mitigation philosophy====\nHydrates have a strong tendency to [[agglomerate]] and to adhere to the pipe wall and thereby plug the pipeline. Once formed, they can be decomposed by increasing the temperature and/or decreasing the pressure. Even under these conditions, the clathrate dissociation is a slow process.\n\nTherefore, preventing hydrate formation appears to be the key to the problem. A hydrate prevention philosophy could typically be based on three levels of security, listed in order of priority:\n# Avoid operational conditions that might cause formation of hydrates by depressing the hydrate formation temperature using [[glycol dehydration]];\n# Temporarily change [[operating conditions]] in order to avoid hydrate formation;\n# Prevent formation of hydrates by addition of chemicals that (a) shift the hydrate equilibrium conditions towards lower temperatures and higher pressures or (b) increase hydrate formation time ([[Reaction inhibitor|inhibitor]]s)\n\nThe actual philosophy would depend on operational circumstances such as pressure, temperature, type of flow (gas, liquid, presences of water etc.)\n\n====Hydrate inhibitors====\nWhen operating within a set of parameters where hydrates could be formed, there are still ways to avoid their formation. Altering the gas composition by adding chemicals can lower the hydrate formation temperature and/or delay their formation. Two options generally exist:\n* Thermodynamic inhibitors\n* [[Kinetic Inhibitor|Kinetic inhibitors/anti-agglomerants]]<ref>{{Cite journal|title= Synergetic effects of polyacrylamide and nonionic surfactants on preventing gas hydrate formation|pages=343\u2013349|journal=Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering|volume=30|doi=10.1016/j.jngse.2016.02.027|date=March 2016|last1=Khodaverdiloo|first1=Khadijeh Rostami|last2=Erfani|first2=Amir|last3=Peyvandi|first3=Kiana|last4=Varaminian|first4=Farshad}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Erfani|first=Amir|date=|title=Gas hydrate formation inhibition using low dosage hydrate inhibitors|url=http://www.semnan.ac.ir/uploads/nicgh1392/articles/7252.pdf|journal=2nd National Iranian Conference on Gas Hydrat|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe most common thermodynamic inhibitors are [[methanol]], [[ethylene glycol|monoethylene glycol]] (MEG), and [[diethylene glycol]] (DEG), commonly referred to as [[glycol]]. All may be recovered and recirculated, but the economics of methanol recovery is not favourable in most cases. MEG is preferred over DEG for applications where the temperature is expected to be \u221210&nbsp;\u00b0C or lower due to high viscosity at low temperatures. [[Triethylene glycol]] (TEG) has too low vapour pressure to be suited as an inhibitor injected into a gas stream. More methanol is lost in the gas phase when compared to MEG or DEG.\n\nThe use of [[Kinetic Inhibitor|kinetic inhibitors]] and anti-agglomerants in actual field operations is a new and evolving technology. It requires extensive tests and optimisation to the actual system. While kinetic inhibitors work by slowing down the kinetics of the nucleation, anti-agglomerants do not stop the nucleation, but stop the agglomeration (sticking together) of gas hydrate crystals.  These two kinds of inhibitors are also known as [[LDHI|low dosage hydrate inhibitors]], because they require much smaller concentrations than the conventional thermodynamic inhibitors.  Kinetic inhibitors, which do not require water and hydrocarbon mixture to be effective, are usually polymers or copolymers and anti-agglomerants (requires water and hydrocarbon mixture) are polymers or [[zwitterion]]ic&nbsp;\u2014 usually ammonium and COOH&nbsp;\u2014 surfactants being both attracted to hydrates and hydrocarbons.\n\n== Empty clathrate hydrates ==\nEmpty clathrate hydrates<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/acsearthspacechem.9b00009 | bibcode=2019ECS.....3..789C | volume=3 | title=Low-Temperature Thermodynamic Study of the Metastable Empty Clathrate Hydrates Using Molecular Simulations | year=2019 | journal=ACS Earth and Space Chemistry | pages=789\u2013799 | last1 = Cruz | first1 = Fernando J. A. L. | last2 = Alavi | first2 = Saman | last3 = Mota | first3 = Jos\u00e9 P. B.}}</ref> are thermodynamically unstable (guest molecules are of paramount importance to stabilize these structures) with respect to ice, and as such their study using experimental techniques is greatly limited to very specific formation conditions; however, their mechanical stability renders theoretical and computer simulation methods the ideal choice to address their thermodynamic properties. Starting from very cold samples (110\u2013145 K), Falenty et al.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Falenty A. |author2=Hansen T.C.|author3=Kuhs .F. | year = 2014 | title = Formation and Properties of Ice XVI Obtained by Emptying a Type sII Clathrate Hydrate | volume = 516 |issue=7530| pages = 231\u2013234 | doi = 10.1038/nature14014 |pmid=25503235| journal = Nature|bibcode=2014Natur.516..231F}}</ref> degassed Ne-sII clathrates for several hours using vacuum pumping to obtain a so-called ice XVI, while employing neutron diffraction to observe that (i) the empty sII hydrate structure decomposes at T \u2265 145 K and, furthermore, (ii) the empty hydrate shows a negative thermal expansion at T < 55 K, and it is mechanically more stable and has a larger lattice constant at low temperatures than the Ne-filled analogue. The existence of such a porous ice had been theoretically predicted before.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Kosyakov V.I. | year = 2009 | title = Structure Formation Under Negative Pressures | volume = 50 | pages = 60\u201365 | doi = 10.1007/s10947-009-0190-0 | journal = J. Struct. Chem}}</ref> From a theoretical perspective, empty hydrates can be probed using Molecular Dynamics or Monte Carlo techniques. Conde et al. used empty hydrates and a fully atomic description of the solid lattice to estimate the phase diagram of H<sub>2</sub>O at negative pressures and T \u2264 300 K,<ref>{{cite journal | author = Conde M.M. |author2=Vega C.|author3=Tribello G.A. |author4=Slater B.| year = 2009 | title = The Phase Diagram of Water at Negative Pressures: Virtual Ices | volume = 131 |issue=3| pages = 034510 | doi = 10.1063/1.3182727 |pmid=19624212| journal = J. Chem. Phys.|bibcode=2009JChPh.131c4510C}}</ref> and obtain the differences in chemical potentials between ice Ih and the empty hydrates, central to the van der Waals\u2212Platteeuw theory. Jacobson et al. performed<ref>{{cite journal | author = Jacobson L.C. |author2=Hujo W.|author3=Molinero V. | year = 2009 | title = Thermodynamic Stability and Growth of Guest-Free Clathrate Hydrates: A Low-Density Crystal Phase of Water | volume = 113 |issue=30| pages = 10298\u201310307 | doi = 10.1021/jp903439a |pmid=19585976| journal = J. Phys. Chem. B| doi-access = free }}</ref> simulations using a monoatomic (coarse-grained) model developed for H<sub>2</sub>O that is capable of capturing the tetrahedral symmetry of hydrates. Their calculations revealed that, under 1 atm pressure, sI and sII empty hydrates are metastable regarding the ice phases up to their melting temperatures, T = 245 \u00b1 2 K and T = 252 \u00b1 2 K, respectively. Matsui et al. employed<ref>{{cite journal | author = Matsui T.|author2=Hirata M.|author3=Yagasaki T. |author4=Matsumoto M. |author5=Tanaka H.| year = 2017 | title = Hypothetical Ultralow-density Ice Polymorphs | volume = 147 |issue=9| pages = 091101 | doi = 10.1063/1.4994757 |pmid=28886658| journal = J. Chem. Phys.}}</ref> molecular dynamics to perform a thorough and systematic study of several ice polymorphs, namely space fullerene ices, zeolitic ices, and aeroices, and interpreted their relative stability in terms of geometrical considerations.\n\nThe thermodynamics of metastable empty sI clathrate hydrates have been probed over broad temperature and pressure ranges, 100 \u2264 T (K) \u2264 220 and 1 \u2264 p (bar) \u2264 5000, by Cruz et al.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Cruz F.J.A.L. |author2=Alavi S.|author3=Mota J.P.B. | year = 2019 | title = Low-Temperature Thermodynamic Study of the Metastable Empty Clathrate Hydrates Using Molecular Simulations | doi = 10.1021/acsearthspacechem.9b00009 | journal = ACS Earth Space Chem.|volume=3|issue=5|pages=789\u2013799|bibcode=2019ECS.....3..789C}}</ref> using large-scale simulations and compared with experimental data at 1 bar. The whole p\u2212V\u2212T surface obtained was fitted by the universal form of the Parsafar and Mason equation of state with an accuracy of 99.7\u201399.9%. Framework deformation caused by applied temperature followed a parabolic law, and there is a critical temperature above which the isobaric thermal expansion becomes negative, ranging from 194.7 K at 1 bar to 166.2 K at 5000 bar. Response to the applied (p, T) field was analyzed in terms of angle and distance descriptors of a classical tetrahedral structure and observed to occur essentially by means of angular alteration for (p, T) > (2000 bar, 200 K). The length of the hydrogen bonds responsible for framework integrity was insensitive to the thermodynamic conditions and its average value is r(\u0305O H) = 0.25&nbsp;nm.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Clathrate]]\n* [[Star#Formation and evolution|Star formation and evolution]]\n* [[Clathrate gun hypothesis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Gao | first1 = Shuqiang | last2 = House | first2 = Waylon | last3 = Chapman | first3 = Walter | year = 2005 | title = NMR/MRI Study of Clathrate Hydrate Mechanisms | url = | journal = J. Phys. Chem. B | volume = 109 | issue = 41| pages = 19090\u201319093 | doi=10.1021/jp052071w}}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.margeo.2004.10.015 |title=Effect of gas hydrates melting on seafloor slope instability |journal=Marine Geology |volume=213 |issue=1\u20134 |pages=379\u2013401 |year=2004 |last1=Sultan |first1=N |last2=Cochonat |first2=P |last3=Foucher |first3=J.-P |last4=Mienert |first4=J |bibcode=2004MGeol.213..379S |url=https://archimer.ifremer.fr/doc/2004/publication-699.pdf }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Gas hydrates}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080411201908/http://www.ifm-geomar.de/index.php?id=1201&L=1 Gas hydrates], from [https://web.archive.org/web/20081105232040/http://www.ifm-geomar.de/index.php?id=1&L=1 Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences], Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110611035202/http://www.ifm-geomar.de/index.php?id=3563&L=1 The SUGAR Project (Submarine Gas Hydrate Reservoirs)], from [https://web.archive.org/web/20081105232040/http://www.ifm-geomar.de/index.php?id=1&L=1 Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences], Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR)\n* [http://www.psl-systemtechnik.de/gas_hydrate_autoclave.html?&L=1 Gas hydrates in video] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20151121100842/http://www.psl-systemtechnik.de/gas_hydrate_autoclave_knowledge.html?&L=1 \u2013 Background knowledge about gas hydrates, their prevention and removal] (by manufacturer of hydrate autoclaves)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clathrate Hydrate}}\n[[Category:Clathrate hydrates| ]]\n[[Category:Ice]]\n[[Category:Gases]]\n[[Category:Industrial gases]]\n[[Category:Natural gas]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Gashydrat mit Struktur.jpg|thumb|right|Methane clathrate block embedded in the sediment of hydrate ridge, off Oregon, USA]]\n'''Clathrate hydrates''', or '''gas clathrates''', '''gas hydrates''', '''clathrates''', '''hydrates''', etc., are [[crystal]]line water-based [[solid]]s physically resembling [[ice]], in which small [[Chemical polarity|non-polar]] [[molecule]]s (typically [[gas]]es) or [[Chemical polarity|polar]] molecules with large hydrophobic [[Moiety (chemistry)|moieties]] are trapped inside \"cages\" of [[hydrogen bond]]ed, frozen [[water (molecule)|water molecules]].  In other words, clathrate hydrates are [[clathrate compound]]s in which the host molecule is [[water]] and the guest molecule is typically a gas or liquid.  Without the support of the trapped molecules, the [[Crystal structure|lattice]] structure of hydrate clathrates would collapse into conventional ice crystal structure or liquid water. Most low molecular weight gases, including {{oxygen}}<sub>2</sub>, {{hydrogen}}<sub>2</sub>, {{nitrogen}}<sub>2</sub>, [[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]], [[methane|CH<sub>4</sub>]], [[hydrogen sulfide|H<sub>2</sub>S]], {{argon}}, {{krypton}}, and {{xenon}}, as well as some higher [[hydrocarbon]]s and [[freon]]s, will form [[hydrate]]s at suitable temperatures and pressures. Clathrate hydrates are not officially chemical compounds, as the sequestered molecules are never bonded to the lattice. The formation and decomposition of clathrate hydrates are [[Phase transition#Classification of phase transitions|first order phase transitions]], not chemical reactions. Their detailed formation and decomposition mechanisms on a molecular level are still not well understood.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Gao S |author2=House W|author3=Chapman WG | year = 2005 | title = NMR MRI Study of Gas Hydrate Mechanisms | volume = 109 | pages = 19090\u201319093 | doi = 10.1021/jp052071w | url = https://www.scribd.com/doc/9701479/NMR-MRI-Study-of-Gas-Hydrate-Mechanisms | accessdate = August 3, 2009 | pmid = 16853461 | issue = 41 | journal = The Journal of Physical Chemistry B |citeseerx=10.1.1.175.9193}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | author = Gao S |author2=Chapman WG|author3=House W | year = 2005 | title = NMR and Viscosity Investigation of Clathrate Formation and Dissociation | journal = Ind. Eng. Chem. Res. | volume = 44 | pages = 7373\u20137379 | doi = 10.1021/ie050464b | url = https://www.scribd.com/doc/9701466/NMR-and-Viscosity-Investigation-of-Clathrate-Formation-and-Dissociation | accessdate = August 3, 2009 | issue = 19 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Choudhary|first=Nilesh|last2=Chakrabarty|first2=Suman|last3=Roy|first3=Sudip|last4=Kumar|first4=Rajnish|date=2019-01-04|title=A comparison of different water models for melting point calculation of methane hydrate using molecular dynamics simulations|journal=Chemical Physics|volume=516|pages=6\u201314|doi=10.1016/j.chemphys.2018.08.036|issn=0301-0104}}</ref>\nClathrate hydrates were first documented in 1810 by [[Humphry Davy]] who found that water was a primary component of what was earlier thought to be solidified chlorine.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/experimentalres02faragoog |title=On Hydrate of Chlorine |year=1859 |accessdate=20 March 2014 |author=Michael Faraday |publisher=Quarterly Journal of Science }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ethomas.web.wesleyan.edu/ees123/clathrate.htm |title=Clathrates: little known components of the global carbon cycle |accessdate=13 December 2007 |date=November 2004 |author=Ellen Thomas |publisher=Wesleyan University }}</ref>\n\nClathrates have been found to occur naturally in large quantities. Around 6.4 trillion (6.4\u00d710<sup>12</sup>) tonnes of [[methane]] is trapped in deposits of [[methane clathrate]] on the deep [[ocean floor]].<ref>{{Cite journal | first = B. | last = Buffett | first2 = D. | last2 = Archer | title = Global inventory of methane clathrate: sensitivity to changes in the deep ocean | year = 2004 | pages = 185\u2013199 | journal = Earth Planet. Sci. Lett. | volume = 227 | issue = 3\u20134 |doi=10.1016/j.epsl.2004.09.005 | bibcode=2004E&PSL.227..185B}}</ref> Such deposits can be found on the [[Norwegian continental shelf]] in the northern headwall flank of the [[Storegga Slide]]. Clathrates can also exist as [[permafrost]], as at the [[Mallik gas hydrate site]] in the [[Mackenzie River|Mackenzie Delta]] of northwestern [[Canadian Arctic]]. These natural gas hydrates are seen as a potentially vast energy resource, but an economical extraction method has so far proven elusive. Hydrocarbon clathrates cause problems for the petroleum industry, because they can form inside [[Pipeline transport|gas pipelines]], often resulting in obstructions. Deep sea deposition of [[carbon dioxide clathrate]] has been proposed as a method to remove this [[greenhouse gas]] from the atmosphere and control [[climate change]].\n\nClathrates are suspected to occur in large quantities on some outer [[planet]]s, [[natural satellite|moons]] and [[trans-Neptunian object]]s, binding gas at fairly high temperatures.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pradeep|first=Thalappil|last2=Kumar|first2=Rajnish|last3=Choudhary|first3=Nilesh|last4=Ragupathy|first4=Gopi|last5=Bhuin|first5=Radha Gobinda|last6=Methikkalam|first6=Rabin Rajan J.|last7=Ghosh|first7=Jyotirmoy|date=2019-01-29|title=Clathrate hydrates in interstellar environment|journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|language=en|volume=116|issue=5|pages=1526\u20131531|doi=10.1073/pnas.1814293116|issn=0027-8424|pmid=30630945|pmc=6358667}}</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\n\n[[Image:HydrateStructures.jpg|thumb|Cages building the different gas hydrate structures.]]\n\nGas hydrates usually form two [[Crystallography|crystallographic]] cubic structures: structure (Type) I (named ''sI'') and structure (Type) II (named ''sII'')<ref>von Stackelberg, M. & M\u00fcller, H. M. (1954) ''Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Elektrochemie'' '''58''', 1, 16, 83</ref> of space groups <math>Pm\\overline{3}n</math>  and <math>Fd\\overline{3}m</math> respectively. Seldom, a third hexagonal structure of space group <math>P6/mmm</math> may be observed (Type H).<ref>Sloan E. D., Jr. (1998) Clathrate hydrates of natural gases. Second edition, Marcel Dekker Inc.:New York.</ref>\n\nThe unit cell of Type I consists of 46 water molecules, forming two types of cages \u2013 small and large. The unit cell contains two small cages and six large ones. The small cage has the shape of a pentagonal [[dodecahedron]] (5<sup>12</sup>) (which is not a regular dodecahedron) and the large one that of a [[tetradecahedron]], specifically a [[hexagonal truncated trapezohedron]] (5<sup>12</sup>6<sup>2</sup>).  Together, they form a version of the [[Weaire\u2013Phelan structure]]. Typical guests forming Type I hydrates are [[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]] in [[carbon dioxide clathrate]] and [[methane|CH<sub>4</sub>]] in [[methane clathrate]].\n\nThe unit cell of Type II consists of 136 water molecules, again forming two types of cages \u2013 small and large. In this case there are sixteen small cages and eight large ones in the unit cell.  The small cage again has the shape of a pentagonal dodecahedron (5<sup>12</sup>), but the large one is a [[hexadecahedron]] (5<sup>12</sup>6<sup>4</sup>). Type II hydrates are formed by gases like O<sub>2</sub> and N<sub>2</sub>.\n\nThe unit cell of Type H consists of 34 water molecules, forming three types of cages \u2013 two small ones of different types, and one \"huge\". In this case, the unit cell consists of three small cages of type 5<sup>12</sup>, two small ones of type 4<sup>3</sup>5<sup>6</sup>6<sup>3</sup> and one huge of type 5<sup>12</sup>6<sup>8</sup>. The formation of Type H requires the cooperation of two guest gases (large and small) to be stable. It is the large cavity that allows structure H hydrates to fit in large molecules (e.g. [[butane]], [[hydrocarbon]]s), given the presence of other smaller help gases to fill and support the remaining cavities. Structure H hydrates were suggested to exist in the Gulf of Mexico. Thermogenically-produced supplies of heavy hydrocarbons are common there.\n\n== Hydrates in the universe ==\n\nIro ''et al.'',<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Iro | first1 = N. | last2 = Gautier | first2 = D. | last3 = Hersant | first3 = F. | last4 = Bockel\u00e9e-Morvan | first4 = D. | last5 = Lunine | first5 = J. I. | year = 2003 | title = An interpretation of the Nitrogen deficiency in comets | url = | journal = Icarus | volume = 161 | issue = 2| page = 513 |bibcode=2003Icar..161..511I |doi=10.1016/S0019-1035(02)00038-6 | citeseerx = 10.1.1.487.722 }}</ref> trying to interpret the [[nitrogen]] deficiency in [[comet]]s, stated most of the conditions for hydrate formation in the [[Protoplanetary disk|protoplanetary nebulae]], surrounding the [[Main sequence|pre-main and main sequence]] stars were fulfilled, despite the rapid grain growth to meter scale. The key was to provide enough microscopic ice particles exposed to a gaseous environment. Observations of the [[Radiometry|radiometric]] [[Continuum (theory)|continuum]] of [[Protoplanetary disk|circumstellar discs]] around <math>\\tau</math>[[T Tauri star|-Tauri]] and [[Herbig Ae/Be stars]] suggest massive dust disks consisting of millimeter-sized grains, which disappear after several million years (e.g.,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Beckwith | first1 = S. V. W. | last2 = Henning | first2 = T. | last3 = Nakagawa | first3 = Y. | year = 2000 | title = Dust properties and assembly of large particles in protoplanetary disks | url = | journal = Protostars and Planets | volume = IV | issue = | page = 533 | arxiv=astro-ph/9902241 |bibcode = 2000prpl.conf..533B }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Natta | first1 = A. | last2 = Grinin | first2 = V. | last3 = Mannings | first3 = V. | year = 2000 | title = Properties and Evolution of Disks around Pre-Main-Sequence Stars of Intermediate Mass | url = | journal = Protostars and Planets | volume = IV | issue = | page = 559 |hdl=2014/17884 | bibcode = 2000prpl.conf..559N }}</ref>). A lot of work on detecting water ices in the Universe was done on the [[Infrared Space Observatory]] (ISO). For instance, broad [[Spectral bands|emission bands]] of water ice at 43 and 60 \u03bcm were found in the disk of the isolated [[Herbig Ae/Be stars|Herbig Ae/Be star]] HD 100546 in [[Musca]]. The one at 43 \u03bcm is much weaker than the one at 60 \u03bcm, which means the water ice, is located in the outer parts of the disk at temperatures below 50 K.<ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 1998A&A...332L..25M | author=Malfait, K., Waelkens, C., Waters, L. B. F. M., Vandenbussche, B., Huygen, E. & de Graauw, M. S. |year=1998 |title= The spectrum of the young star HD 100546 observed with the Infrared Space Observatory |journal=Astronomy and Astrophysics|volume=332 |pages= L25\u2013L28 | last2 = Waelkens | last3 = Waters | last4 = Vandenbussche | last5 = Huygen | last6 = De Graauw}}</ref> There is also another broad ice feature between 87 and 90 \u03bcm, which is very similar to the one in [[NGC 6302]] <ref>Barlow, M.J., In the proceedings of \u2018ISO\u2019s view on stellar evolution\u2019, Noordwijkerhout, July 1\u20134, 1997</ref> (the Bug or Butterfly nebula in [[Scorpius]]). Crystalline ices were also detected in the proto-planetary disks of [[Epsilon Eridani|\u03b5-Eridani]] and the isolated Fe star HD 142527<ref>{{cite journal | title= Modeling the infrared emission from the \u03b5-Eridani disk| doi = 10.1086/380495 | year= 2003 | last1= Li | first1= Aigen | last2= Lunine | first2= J. I. | last3= Bendo | first3= G. J. | journal= The Astrophysical Journal | volume= 598 | issue = 1 | pages= L51\u2013L54 | bibcode=2003ApJ...598L..51L|arxiv = astro-ph/0311069 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Malfait | first1 = K. | last2 = Waelkens | first2 = C. | last3 = Bouwman | first3 = J. | last4 = De Koter | first4 = A. | last5 = Waters | first5 = L. B. F. M. | year = 1999 | title = The ISO spectrum of the young star HD 142527 | url = | journal = Astronomy and Astrophysics | volume = 345 | issue = | page = 181 |bibcode=1999A&A...345..181M}}</ref> in [[Lupus (constellation)|Lupus]]. 90% of the ice in the latter was found crystalline at temperature around 50 K. [[Hubble Space Telescope|HST]] demonstrated that relatively old [[Protoplanetary disk|circumstellar disks]], as the one around the 5-million-year-old B9.5Ve<ref>Jaschek, C. & Jaschek, M. (1992) ''Astronomy and Astrophysics'', '''95''', p. 535</ref> [[Herbig Ae/Be stars|Herbig Ae/Be star]] HD 141569A, are dusty.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Clampin | first1 = M. | last2 = Krist | first2 = J. E. | last3 = Ardila | first3 = D. R. | last4 = Golimowski | first4 = D. A. | last5 = Hartig | first5 = G. F. | last6 = Ford | first6 = H. C. | last7 = Illingworth | first7 = G. D. | last8 = Bartko | first8 = F. | last9 = Bentez | first9 = N. | last10 = Blakeslee | first10 = J. P. | last11 = Bouwens | first11 = R. J. | last12 = Broadhurst | first12 = T. J. | last13 = Brown | first13 = R. A. | last14 = Burrows | first14 = C. J. | last15 = Cheng | first15 = E. S. | last16 = Cross | first16 = N. J. G. | last17 = Feldman | first17 = P. D. | last18 = Franx | first18 = M. | last19 = Gronwall | first19 = C. | last20 = Infante | first20 = L. | last21 = Kimble | first21 = R. A. | last22 = Lesser | first22 = M. P. | last23 = Martel | first23 = A. R. | last24 = Menanteau | first24 = F. | last25 = Meurer | first25 = G. R. | last26 = Miley | first26 = G. K. | last27 = Postman | last29 = Sirianni | first29 = M. | last30 = Sparks | first30 = W. B. | last28 = Rosati | first28 = P. | doi = 10.1086/375460 | title = Hubble Space TelescopeACS Coronagraphic Imaging of the Circumstellar Disk around HD 141569A | first27 = M. | journal = The Astronomical Journal | volume = 126 | issue = 1 | pages = 385\u2013392 | year = 2003 | pmid =  | pmc = | displayauthors = 29|arxiv = astro-ph/0303605 |bibcode = 2003AJ....126..385C }}</ref> Li & Lunine<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Li | first1 = A. | last2 = Lunine | first2 = J. I. | year = 2003 | title = Modeling the infrared emission from the HD 141569A disk | url = | journal = Astrophysical Journal | volume = 594 | issue = 2| pages = 987\u20131010 | doi = 10.1086/376939 | bibcode=2003ApJ...594..987L|arxiv = astro-ph/0311070 }}</ref> found water ice there. Knowing the ices usually exist at the outer parts of the [[Protoplanetary disk|proto-planetary nebulae]], Hersant ''et al.''<ref>{{cite journal | bibcode = 2004P&SS...52..623H | doi=10.1016/j.pss.2003.12.011 | title = Enrichment in volatiles in the giant planets of the Solar System | year = 2004 | last1 = Hersant | first1 = F | journal = Planetary and Space Science | volume = 52 | issue = 7 | pages = 623\u2013641 }}</ref> proposed an interpretation of the [[Volatility (physics)|volatile]] enrichment, observed in the four [[Gas giant|giant planets]] of the [[Solar System]], with respect to the Solar [[Abundance of the chemical elements|abundances]]. They assumed the [[Volatility (physics)|volatiles]] had been trapped in the form of hydrates and incorporated in the [[planetesimal]]s flying in the [[Protoplanet|protoplanets\u2019]] feeding zones.\n\nKieffer ''et al.'' (2006) hypothesized that the geyser activity in the south polar region of [[Saturn]]'s moon [[Enceladus (moon)|Enceladus]] originates from clathrate hydrates, where carbon dioxide, methane, and nitrogen are released when exposed to the vacuum of space through the \"[[Tiger Stripes (Enceladus)|Tiger Stripe]]\" fractures found in that area.<ref name=Kieffer2006>{{cite journal| first=Susan W.| last= Kieffer|author2=Xinli Lu |author3=Craig M. Bethke |author4=John R. Spencer |author5=Stephen Marshak |author6=Alexandra Navrotsky | year=2006| doi=10.1126/science.1133519| title=A Clathrate Reservoir Hypothesis for Enceladus' South Polar Plume| journal=Science| volume=314| issue=5806| pages=1764\u20131766| pmid=17170301| bibcode=2006Sci...314.1764K| url= https://semanticscholar.org/paper/d23f6cd66b2089fcb3a9e7c4622a8fd4bc078c4a}}</ref> However, subsequent analysis of plume material makes it more likely that the geysers on Enceladus derive from a salty subsurface ocean.<ref name=\"SCI-20140404\">{{cite journal |last1=Iess |first1=L. |last2=Stevenson |first2=D.J. |last3=Parisi |first3=M. |last4=Hemingway |first4=D. |last5=Jacobson |first5=R.A. |last6=Lunine |first6=J.I. |last7=Nimmo |first7=F. |last8=Armstrong |first8=J.w. |last9=Asmar |first9=S.w. |last10=Ducci |first10=M. |last11=Tortora |first11=P. |title=The Gravity Field and Interior Structure of Enceladus |date=April 4, 2014 |journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]] |volume=344 |number=6179 |pages=78\u201380 |doi=10.1126/science.1250551 |bibcode=2014Sci...344...78I |pmid=24700854|url=https://authors.library.caltech.edu/45462/7/Iess-SM.pdf }}</ref>\n\n[[Carbon dioxide clathrate]] is believed to play a major role in different processes on Mars.  [[Hydrogen clathrate]] is likely to form in condensation nebulae for gas giants.\n\n== Hydrates on Earth==\n\n===Natural gas hydrates===\n{{main|Methane clathrate}}\nNaturally on [[Earth]] gas hydrates can be found on the [[seabed]], in ocean sediments,<ref>{{cite journal |year=1980 |author1=Kvenvolden, K. A. |author2=McMenamin, M. A. |title=Hydrates of Natural Gas: Their Geologic Occurrence |journal=U. S. Geological Survey Circular |volume=825 }}</ref> in deep lake sediments (e.g. [[Lake Baikal]]), as well as in the [[permafrost]] regions. The amount of [[methane]] potentially trapped in natural [[Methane clathrate|methane hydrate]] deposits may be significant (10<sup>15</sup> to 10<sup>17</sup> cubic metres),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn16848-ice-that-burns-could-be-a-green-fossil-fuel|title=Ice that burns could be a green fossil fuel|last=Marshall|first=Michael|date=March 26, 2009|work=New Scientist|access-date=2018-03-26|language=en-US}}</ref> which makes them of major interest as a potential energy resource. Catastrophic release of methane from the decomposition of such deposits may lead to a global climate change, because [[methane|CH]]<sub>4</sub> is a more potent greenhouse gas than [[carbon dioxide|CO]]<sub>2</sub> (see [[Atmospheric methane]]). The fast decomposition of such deposits is considered a [[geohazard]], due to its potential to trigger [[landslide]]s, [[earthquake]]s  and [[tsunami]]s. However, natural gas hydrates do not contain only methane but also other [[hydrocarbon]] gases, as well as [[Hydrogen sulfide|H<sub>2</sub>S]] and [[Carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]]. [[Air hydrates]] are frequently observed in polar ice samples.\n\n[[Pingo]]s are common structures in permafrost regions.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Methane Leakage from Pingo-like Features on the Arctic Shelf, Beaufort Sea, NWT, Canada  |date=December 2005 | bibcode = 2005AGUFM.C11A1069U | author1 = Ussler, W. | author2 = Paull, C. K. | author3 = Lorenson, T. | author4 = Dallimore, S. | author5 = Medioli, B. | author6 = Blasco, S. | author7 = McLaughlin, F. | author8 = Nixon, F. M. | volume = 11 | pages = C11A\u20131069 | journal =  AGU Fall Meeting Abstracts}}</ref> Similar structures are found in deep water related to methane leakages. Significantly, gas hydrates can even be formed in the absence of a liquid phase. Under that situation, water is dissolved in gas or in liquid hydrocarbon phase.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Youssef | first1 = Z. | last2 = Barreau | first2 = A. | last3 = Mougin | first3 = P. | last4 = Jose | first4 = J. | last5 = Mokbel | first5 = I | year = 2009 | title =  | url = | journal = Ind. Eng. Chem. Res. | volume = 48 | issue = | pages = 4045\u20134050 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, both Japan and China announced that attempts at large-scale [[resource extraction]] of methane hydrates from under the seafloor were successful.  However, commercial-scale production remains years away. <ref>{{Cite web | url= https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-39971667 | title= China claims breakthrough in mining 'flammable ice' &#124; BBC News| date=2017-05-19}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web | url=http://news.nationalpost.com/news/world/china-japan-extracts-combustible-ice-from-seafloor-a-step-towards-harnessing-a-legendary-frozen-fossil-fuel | title=China and Japan find way to extract 'combustible ice' from seafloor, harnessing a legendary frozen fossil fuel &#124; National Post| date=2017-05-19}}</ref>\n\n===Gas hydrates in pipelines===\nThermodynamic conditions favouring hydrate formation are often found in [[Pipeline transport|pipelines]]. This is highly undesirable, because the clathrate crystals might agglomerate and plug the line<ref>{{cite journal | doi = 10.1021/ef800189k | title = Investigation of Interactions between Gas Hydrates and Several Other Flow Assurance Elements | year = 2008 | last1 = Gao | first1 = Shuqiang | journal = Energy & Fuels | volume = 22 | issue = 5 | pages = 3150\u20133153 }}</ref> and cause [[flow assurance]] failure and damage valves and instrumentation. The results can range from flow reduction to equipment damage.\n\n====Hydrate formation, prevention and mitigation philosophy====\nHydrates have a strong tendency to [[agglomerate]] and to adhere to the pipe wall and thereby plug the pipeline. Once formed, they can be decomposed by increasing the temperature and/or decreasing the pressure. Even under these conditions, the clathrate dissociation is a slow process.\n\nTherefore, preventing hydrate formation appears to be the key to the problem. A hydrate prevention philosophy could typically be based on three levels of security, listed in order of priority:\n# Avoid operational conditions that might cause formation of hydrates by depressing the hydrate formation temperature using [[glycol dehydration]];\n# Temporarily change [[operating conditions]] in order to avoid hydrate formation;\n# Prevent formation of hydrates by addition of chemicals that (a) shift the hydrate equilibrium conditions towards lower temperatures and higher pressures or (b) increase hydrate formation time ([[Reaction inhibitor|inhibitor]]s)\n\nThe actual philosophy would depend on operational circumstances such as pressure, temperature, type of flow (gas, liquid, presences of water etc.)\n\n====Hydrate inhibitors====\nWhen operating within a set of parameters where hydrates could be formed, there are still ways to avoid their formation. Altering the gas composition by adding chemicals can lower the hydrate formation temperature and/or delay their formation. Two options generally exist:\n* Thermodynamic inhibitors\n* [[Kinetic Inhibitor|Kinetic inhibitors/anti-agglomerants]]<ref>{{Cite journal|title= Synergetic effects of polyacrylamide and nonionic surfactants on preventing gas hydrate formation|pages=343\u2013349|journal=Journal of Natural Gas Science and Engineering|volume=30|doi=10.1016/j.jngse.2016.02.027|date=March 2016|last1=Khodaverdiloo|first1=Khadijeh Rostami|last2=Erfani|first2=Amir|last3=Peyvandi|first3=Kiana|last4=Varaminian|first4=Farshad}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Erfani|first=Amir|date=|title=Gas hydrate formation inhibition using low dosage hydrate inhibitors|url=http://www.semnan.ac.ir/uploads/nicgh1392/articles/7252.pdf|journal=2nd National Iranian Conference on Gas Hydrat|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nThe most common thermodynamic inhibitors are [[methanol]], [[ethylene glycol|monoethylene glycol]] (MEG), and [[diethylene glycol]] (DEG), commonly referred to as [[glycol]]. All may be recovered and recirculated, but the economics of methanol recovery is not favourable in most cases. MEG is preferred over DEG for applications where the temperature is expected to be \u221210&nbsp;\u00b0C or lower due to high viscosity at low temperatures. [[Triethylene glycol]] (TEG) has too low vapour pressure to be suited as an inhibitor injected into a gas stream. More methanol is lost in the gas phase when compared to MEG or DEG.\n\nThe use of [[Kinetic Inhibitor|kinetic inhibitors]] and anti-agglomerants in actual field operations is a new and evolving technology. It requires extensive tests and optimisation to the actual system. While kinetic inhibitors work by slowing down the kinetics of the nucleation, anti-agglomerants do not stop the nucleation, but stop the agglomeration (sticking together) of gas hydrate crystals.  These two kinds of inhibitors are also known as [[LDHI|low dosage hydrate inhibitors]], because they require much smaller concentrations than the conventional thermodynamic inhibitors.  Kinetic inhibitors, which do not require water and hydrocarbon mixture to be effective, are usually polymers or copolymers and anti-agglomerants (requires water and hydrocarbon mixture) are polymers or [[zwitterion]]ic&nbsp;\u2014 usually ammonium and COOH&nbsp;\u2014 surfactants being both attracted to hydrates and hydrocarbons.\n\n== Empty clathrate hydrates ==\nEmpty clathrate hydrates<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1021/acsearthspacechem.9b00009 | bibcode=2019ECS.....3..789C | volume=3 | title=Low-Temperature Thermodynamic Study of the Metastable Empty Clathrate Hydrates Using Molecular Simulations | year=2019 | journal=ACS Earth and Space Chemistry | pages=789\u2013799 | last1 = Cruz | first1 = Fernando J. A. L. | last2 = Alavi | first2 = Saman | last3 = Mota | first3 = Jos\u00e9 P. B.}}</ref> are thermodynamically unstable (guest molecules are of paramount importance to stabilize these structures) with respect to ice, and as such their study using experimental techniques is greatly limited to very specific formation conditions; however, their mechanical stability renders theoretical and computer simulation methods the ideal choice to address their thermodynamic properties. Starting from very cold samples (110\u2013145 K), Falenty et al.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Falenty A. |author2=Hansen T.C.|author3=Kuhs .F. | year = 2014 | title = Formation and Properties of Ice XVI Obtained by Emptying a Type sII Clathrate Hydrate | volume = 516 |issue=7530| pages = 231\u2013234 | doi = 10.1038/nature14014 |pmid=25503235| journal = Nature|bibcode=2014Natur.516..231F}}</ref> degassed Ne-sII clathrates for several hours using vacuum pumping to obtain a so-called ice XVI, while employing neutron diffraction to observe that (i) the empty sII hydrate structure decomposes at T \u2265 145 K and, furthermore, (ii) the empty hydrate shows a negative thermal expansion at T < 55 K, and it is mechanically more stable and has a larger lattice constant at low temperatures than the Ne-filled analogue. The existence of such a porous ice had been theoretically predicted before.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Kosyakov V.I. | year = 2009 | title = Structure Formation Under Negative Pressures | volume = 50 | pages = 60\u201365 | doi = 10.1007/s10947-009-0190-0 | journal = J. Struct. Chem}}</ref> From a theoretical perspective, empty hydrates can be probed using Molecular Dynamics or Monte Carlo techniques. Conde et al. used empty hydrates and a fully atomic description of the solid lattice to estimate the phase diagram of H<sub>2</sub>O at negative pressures and T \u2264 300 K,<ref>{{cite journal | author = Conde M.M. |author2=Vega C.|author3=Tribello G.A. |author4=Slater B.| year = 2009 | title = The Phase Diagram of Water at Negative Pressures: Virtual Ices | volume = 131 |issue=3| pages = 034510 | doi = 10.1063/1.3182727 |pmid=19624212| journal = J. Chem. Phys.|bibcode=2009JChPh.131c4510C}}</ref> and obtain the differences in chemical potentials between ice Ih and the empty hydrates, central to the van der Waals\u2212Platteeuw theory. Jacobson et al. performed<ref>{{cite journal | author = Jacobson L.C. |author2=Hujo W.|author3=Molinero V. | year = 2009 | title = Thermodynamic Stability and Growth of Guest-Free Clathrate Hydrates: A Low-Density Crystal Phase of Water | volume = 113 |issue=30| pages = 10298\u201310307 | doi = 10.1021/jp903439a |pmid=19585976| journal = J. Phys. Chem. B| doi-access = free }}</ref> simulations using a monoatomic (coarse-grained) model developed for H<sub>2</sub>O that is capable of capturing the tetrahedral symmetry of hydrates. Their calculations revealed that, under 1 atm pressure, sI and sII empty hydrates are metastable regarding the ice phases up to their melting temperatures, T = 245 \u00b1 2 K and T = 252 \u00b1 2 K, respectively. Matsui et al. employed<ref>{{cite journal | author = Matsui T.|author2=Hirata M.|author3=Yagasaki T. |author4=Matsumoto M. |author5=Tanaka H.| year = 2017 | title = Hypothetical Ultralow-density Ice Polymorphs | volume = 147 |issue=9| pages = 091101 | doi = 10.1063/1.4994757 |pmid=28886658| journal = J. Chem. Phys.}}</ref> molecular dynamics to perform a thorough and systematic study of several ice polymorphs, namely space fullerene ices, zeolitic ices, and aeroices, and interpreted their relative stability in terms of geometrical considerations.\n\nThe thermodynamics of metastable empty sI clathrate hydrates have been probed over broad temperature and pressure ranges, 100 \u2264 T (K) \u2264 220 and 1 \u2264 p (bar) \u2264 5000, by Cruz et al.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Cruz F.J.A.L. |author2=Alavi S.|author3=Mota J.P.B. | year = 2019 | title = Low-Temperature Thermodynamic Study of the Metastable Empty Clathrate Hydrates Using Molecular Simulations | doi = 10.1021/acsearthspacechem.9b00009 | journal = ACS Earth Space Chem.|volume=3|issue=5|pages=789\u2013799|bibcode=2019ECS.....3..789C}}</ref> using large-scale simulations and compared with experimental data at 1 bar. The whole p\u2212V\u2212T surface obtained was fitted by the universal form of the Parsafar and Mason equation of state with an accuracy of 99.7\u201399.9%. Framework deformation caused by applied temperature followed a parabolic law, and there is a critical temperature above which the isobaric thermal expansion becomes negative, ranging from 194.7 K at 1 bar to 166.2 K at 5000 bar. Response to the applied (p, T) field was analyzed in terms of angle and distance descriptors of a classical tetrahedral structure and observed to occur essentially by means of angular alteration for (p, T) > (2000 bar, 200 K). The length of the hydrogen bonds responsible for framework integrity was insensitive to the thermodynamic conditions and its average value is r(\u0305O H) = 0.25&nbsp;nm.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Clathrate]]\n* [[Star#Formation and evolution|Star formation and evolution]]\n* [[Clathrate gun hypothesis]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Gao | first1 = Shuqiang | last2 = House | first2 = Waylon | last3 = Chapman | first3 = Walter | year = 2005 | title = NMR/MRI Study of Clathrate Hydrate Mechanisms | url = | journal = J. Phys. Chem. B | volume = 109 | issue = 41| pages = 19090\u201319093 | doi=10.1021/jp052071w}}\n*{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.margeo.2004.10.015 |title=Effect of gas hydrates melting on seafloor slope instability |journal=Marine Geology |volume=213 |issue=1\u20134 |pages=379\u2013401 |year=2004 |last1=Sultan |first1=N |last2=Cochonat |first2=P |last3=Foucher |first3=J.-P |last4=Mienert |first4=J |bibcode=2004MGeol.213..379S |url=https://archimer.ifremer.fr/doc/2004/publication-699.pdf }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Gas hydrates}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080411201908/http://www.ifm-geomar.de/index.php?id=1201&L=1 Gas hydrates], from [https://web.archive.org/web/20081105232040/http://www.ifm-geomar.de/index.php?id=1&L=1 Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences], Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110611035202/http://www.ifm-geomar.de/index.php?id=3563&L=1 The SUGAR Project (Submarine Gas Hydrate Reservoirs)], from [https://web.archive.org/web/20081105232040/http://www.ifm-geomar.de/index.php?id=1&L=1 Leibniz Institute of Marine Sciences], Kiel (IFM-GEOMAR)\n* [http://www.psl-systemtechnik.de/gas_hydrate_autoclave.html?&L=1 Gas hydrates in video] and [https://web.archive.org/web/20151121100842/http://www.psl-systemtechnik.de/gas_hydrate_autoclave_knowledge.html?&L=1 \u2013 Background knowledge about gas hydrates, their prevention and removal] (by manufacturer of hydrate autoclaves)\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Clathrate Hydrate}}\n[[Category:Clathrate hydrates| ]]\n[[Category:Ice]]\n[[Category:Gases]]\n[[Category:Industrial gases]]\n[[Category:Natural gas]]\n", "name_user": "Sandpidu2", "label": "safe", "comment": "added links and applications", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clathrate_hydrate"}
{"title_page": "Anne Couppier de Romans", "text_new": "[[File:Anne Couppier de Romans.jpg|thumb|Anne Couppier de Romans]]\n'''Anne Couppier de Romans''' (1737-1808), was the [[Ma\u00eetresse-en-titre|mistress]] of [[Louis XV of France]] from 1760 to 1765.<ref>Lever, Maurice, Louis XV: libertin malgr\u00e8 lui, Payot, Paris, 2001</ref> \n\n==Life==\nAnne Couppier de Romans was the daughter of an office clerk in Grenoble, Jean Joseph Roman Coppier, and Marie-Madeleine Armand. In 1760, she became aquited with [[Giacomo Casanova]], who made her a [[horoscope]] claiming that she would be the lover of the king. Her sister Marie-Madeleine Couppier-Varnier was a courtesan in Paris and connected to [[Dominique Guillaume Lebel]], who provided the king with lovers for his [[Parc-aux-Cerfs]]. \n\n===Royal mistress===\n\nShe became the ''petite ma\u00eetresse'' (inofficiall mistress) of the king in 1760, but she refused to become one of the lovers of the \u200eParc-aux-Cerfs, were at the time [[Marguerite-Catherine Haynault]] and [[Lucie Madeleine d'Estaing]] were housed. Instead, she successfully demanded to be given her own house in Passy, close to the [[Ch\u00e2teau de la Muette]], where the king visited her. Her house was called ''Hotel de la Folie''. The King gave her the title baronesse de Meilly-Coulonge. \n\nShe had a son with the king: [[Louis Aim\u00e9 de Bourbon]] (1761-1787), who became a priest. The king registered himself as the father of the child, and while he did take responsibility for many of his illegitimate children, he normally did not acknowledge them.  Anne Couppier de Romans called her son 'Monseigneur', a title for a Prince, and displayed him in public in the [[Bois de Boulogne]]. \n\nThe special treatment given by the king to Anne Couppier de Romans, so unlike anything to any of the lovers of the Parc-aux-Cerfs, reportedly worried Madame de Pompadour, and on one occasion, she visited the Bois de Boulogne to observe Anne Couppier de Romans and her son.\n\n===Later life===\nIn 1765, Anne Couppier de Romans was implicated in the affair of [[Louis-Ren\u00e9 de Caradeuc de La Chalotais]]. The same year, the king discontinued their affair. She was separated from her son. She was given an allowance of 500.000 ''[[livres]]'', more than any of the lovers of the Parc-aux-Cerfs. \n\nIn 1772, she married Gabriel Guillaume de Siran, marquis de Cavanac (d. 1784). In contrast to most of the marriages of the lovers of the Parc-aux-Cerfs, hers was not arranged by the king. She had two children in her marriage prior to [[S\u00e9paration de corps et d'habitation| her separation]]. She left France during the [[French revolution]] and lived in Spain during the [[Reign of Terror]]. After the fall of [[Robespierre]], she returned to France and reclaimed her property. She died a millionarie\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n* Michel Garcin, Mademoiselle de Romans, la \u00ab grande \u00bb, Atlantica, 1 mars 2006, {{ISBN|978-2843949029}}.\n\n{{Expand Swedish|Anne Couppier de Romans|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Romans, Anne Couppier de}}\n[[Category:1737 births]]\n[[Category:1808 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century French people]]\n[[Category:Mistresses of Louis XV of France]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Anne Couppier de Romans.jpg|thumb|Anne Couppier de Romans]]\n'''Anne Couppier de Romans''' (1737-1808), was the [[Ma\u00eetresse-en-titre|mistress]] of [[Louis XV of France]] from 1760 to 1765.<ref>Lever, Maurice, Louis XV: libertin malgr\u00e8 lui, Payot, Paris, 2001</ref> \n\n==Life==\nAnne Couppier de Romans was the daughter of an office clerk in Grenoble, Jean Joseph Roman Coppier, and Marie-Madeleine Armand. In 1760, she became aquited with [[Giacomo Casanova]], who made her a [[horoscope]] claiming that she would be the lover of the king. Her sister Marie-Madeleine Couppier-Varnier was a courtesan in Paris and connected to [[Dominique Guillaume Lebel]], who provided the king with lovers for his [[Parc-aux-Cerfs]]. \n\n===Royal mistress===\n\nShe became the ''petite ma\u00eetresse'' (inofficiall mistress) of the king in 1760, but she refused to become one of the lovers of the \u200eParc-aux-Cerfs, were at the time [[Marguerite-Catherine Haynault]] and [[Lucie Madeleine d'Estaing]] were housed. Instead, she successfully demanded to be given her own house in Passy, close to the [[Ch\u00e2teau de la Muette]], where the king visited her. Her house was called ''Hotel de la Folie''. The King gave her the title baronesse de Meilly-Coulonge. \n\nShe had a son with the king: [[Louis Aim\u00e9 de Bourbon]] (1761-1787), who became a priest. The king registered himself as the father of the child, and while he did take responsiblity for many of his illegitimate children, he normally did not acknowledge them.  Anne Couppier de Romans called her son 'Monseigneur', a title for a Prince, and displayed him in public in the [[Bois de Boulogne]]. \n\nThe special treatment given by the king to Anne Couppier de Romans, so unlike anything to any of the lovers of the Parc-aux-Cerfs, reportedly worried Madame de Pompadour, and on one occasion, she visited the Bois de Boulogne to observe Anne Couppier de Romans and her son.\n\n===Later life===\nIn 1765, Anne Couppier de Romans was implicated in the affair of [[Louis-Ren\u00e9 de Caradeuc de La Chalotais]]. The same year, the king discontinued their affair. She was separated from her son. She was given an allowance of 500.000 ''[[livres]]'', more than any of the lovers of the Parc-aux-Cerfs. \n\nIn 1772, she married Gabriel Guillaume de Siran, marquis de Cavanac (d. 1784). In contrast to most of the marriages of the lovers of the Parc-aux-Cerfs, hers was not arranged by the king. She had two children in her marriage prior to [[S\u00e9paration de corps et d'habitation| her separation]]. She left France during the [[French revolution]] and lived in Spain during the [[Reign of Terror]]. After the fall of [[Robespierre]], she returned to France and reclaimed her property. She died a millionarie\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n* Michel Garcin, Mademoiselle de Romans, la \u00ab grande \u00bb, Atlantica, 1 mars 2006, {{ISBN|978-2843949029}}.\n\n{{Expand Swedish|Anne Couppier de Romans|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Romans, Anne Couppier de}}\n[[Category:1737 births]]\n[[Category:1808 deaths]]\n[[Category:18th-century French people]]\n[[Category:Mistresses of Louis XV of France]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_Couppier_de_Romans"}
{"title_page": "Sudigali Sudheer", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{infobox person\n| nationality        = Indian\n| name               = Sudigali Sudheer\n| image              = File:Sudigali_Sudheer.jpg\n| caption            = Sudigali Sudheer in 50th episode of ''[[Pove Pora]]'' photoshoot\n| birth_name         = '''Sudheer Anand Bayana'''\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=y|1987|5|19}}\n| birth_place        = [[Vijayawada]],<br /> [[Andhra Pradesh]],<br /> [[India]]\n| occupation         = {{bulleted list|Actor|Comedian|Dancer|[[Magician (illusionist)|Magician]]|Singer|Television Presenter}}\n| module             = {{Listen|embed=yes|pos=center|filename=Sudigali Sudheer Interview.flac|title=Sudigali Sudheer Voice|type=speech|description= from an Interview in March 2017<ref>{{cite web|title= Sudigali Sudheer Interview |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F-IH-kH5Cho|work=Telugu Film Nagar|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>}}\n\n| family             = ''Dev Anand Bayana'' (Father),<br />  ''Nagarani Bayana'' (Mother),<br /> ''Rohan Bayana'' (Brother),<br />  ''Ramya Bayana'' (Sister in Law), <br> ''Swetha Anand Pilla'' (Sister), <br> ''Venkat Pilla'' (Brother in Law), <br> ''Yoshita (Yoshi)'' (Niece)\n| years_active       = 2010\u2013present\n| known_for          = ''[[Extra Jabardasth]]'', ''[[Dhee Ultimate Dance Show]]'', ''[[Pove Pora]]''\n| awards             = See [[#Awards and recognition|awards]]\n}}\n\n'''Sudigali Sudheer''' (born '''Sudheer Anand ''' on 19 May 1987) is a [[Telugu language]] actor and a comedian, who is known for his performance in the [[List of Telugu-language television channels|Telugu-language television channel]] comedy shows ''[[Jabardasth (comedy show)|Jabardasth]]'' and ''[[Extra Jabardasth]]''. He is also a team leader on ''[[Dhee Ultimate Dance Show]]'' for season 9, season 10, season 11 and season 12.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/telugu/Guess-who-made-Sudigali-Sudheer-day-unforgettable/articleshow/51311466.cms|title=Sudigali Sudheer: Guess who made Sudigali Sudheer day unforgettable|work=The Times of India|access-date=8 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/telugu/Anchors-Rashmi-and-Sudigali-Sudheer-swaps-roles/articleshow/54763176.cms|title=Rashmi sudigali sudheer: Anchors Rashmi and Sudigali Sudheer swaps roles|work=The Times of India|access-date=9 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/telugu/sudigali-sudheer-is-the-new-host-of-jackpot-2/articleshow/63693210.cms|title=Jackpot 2: Sudigali Sudheer is the new host of 'Jackpot 2'|work=The Times of India|access-date=10 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/telugu/Sudigali-Sudheer-spotted-at-Niagara-falls/articleshow/49871303.cms|title=Sudigali Sudheer: Sudigali Sudheer spotted at Niagara falls|work=The Times of India|access-date=21 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tollywood.net/rashmi-gautham-and-sudigali-sudheer-impressed-from-their-first-night-room/|title=Rashmi Gautam and Sudigali Sudheer impressed from their first night room|work=tollywood.net|access-date=21 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/telugu/Sudigali-Sudheer-spotted-at-tower-bridge/articleshow/49538800.cms|title=Sudigali Sudheer spotted at tower bridge|work=tollywoodnet|access-date=26 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/telugu/Comedian-Sudheers-unforgettable-moment/articleshow/49674058.cms|title=Sudigali Sudheer: Comedian Sudigali Sudheer's unforggettable moment|date=5 November 2015|newspaper=The Times of India|access-date=6 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/telugu/blaming-the-entire-industry-for-mistakes-done-by-few-is-completely-unfair-sudigali-sudheer/articleshow/63877786.cms|title=Sudigali Sudheer: Blaming the entire industry for mistakes done by few is completely unfair|work=The Times of India|access-date=24 April 2018}}</ref> He is raised as youth icon with hosting ''[[Pove Pora]]'' , a youth game show. Before joining the Jabardasth show, he has worked as a [[Magician (illusionist)|Magician]] at [[Ramoji Film City]], [[Hyderabad]], India.\n\nMost of his skits in Jabardasth and Extra Jabardasth are hits and won the prize of the day. All his works, have good ratings on television and good views on YouTube. He has also appeared in Telugu cinemas as a supporting actor and has also hosted [[American Telugu Association|American Telugu Convention \u2013 2018]] alongside [[Suma Kanakala]]. He has secured 13th place in ''Hyderabad's Most Desirable Men on TV \u2013 for the year 2018''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/telugu/heres-to-tvs-hottest-hunks/articleshow/68024326.cms|title=Here's to TV's hottest hunks|work=The Times of India|access-date=17 February 2019}}</ref> In December 2019 he made his debut as hero in the movie Software Sudheer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tollywood.net/software-sudheer-movie-review/|title=Software Sudheer Movie Review|work=Tollywood.Net|access-date=28 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.123telugu.com/reviews/software-sudheer-telugu-movie-review.html|title=Software Sudheer Telugu Movie Review|work=123Telugu.Com|access-date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and family ==\nSudheer Anand Bayana was born on 19<sup><sup>th</sup></sup> May 1987 in [[Vijayawada]], [[Krishna District]], Andhra Pradesh to Dev Anand Bayana and Nagarani Bayana into a Telugu speaking family. His mother Nagarani Bayana, a Housewife and father Dev Anand Bayana, worked as Manager in a Cinema theater in Vijayawada. He is one of three siblings in a family consisting of younger brother (Rohan Bayana) and elder sister (Swetha Anand Pilla). Ramya Bayana is his Sister in law(Rohan's wife).\n\nSudheer finished his schooling at ''Sri Telaprolu Bapanaiah English Medium High School'' Vijayawada.During his schooling, he was very good at dancing, singing and other extra curricular activities. He also learnt [[Bharatanatyam]], [[Folk music|Folk]], Western for two years and a good dancer during his schooldays. He participated in many competitions at various levels and had won many prizes. Magic, another area of his interest which was guided by his Maternal Uncle since childhood. Later he joined college to pursue Intermediate and opted for M.P.C.(Mathematics, Physics and Chemistry) as those were his favourite subjects. During this time he moved to Hyderabad to pursue acting career and was not able to attend final exams. After Six years,he completed the intermediate. Later he continued to work for various shows.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\n== Acting career ==\n\n===Early Career and Struggle (2004\u20132008)===\n\nSudheer made his first Television appearance for a talent show telecasted on Citi Cable Vijayawada. During his Intermediate, he appeared for a show ''\u2018Star Hunt One Chance\u2019'' which was aired on [[Maa TV]]. His talents were highly appreciated by Judges. He skipped his intermediate exams to appear in the Finale. He was one of the finalist of ''\u2018Star Hunt One Chance\u2019''. His efforts went in vain as he did not succeed both in Exams and Show. He returned to Vijayawada where he started to teach Folk, Western and Classic form of dance.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nIn sudden turn of events, his father met with an accident and seriously injured. At the same time they faced financial difficulties. Being the eldest son, he took family responsibilities and moved to Hyderabad. In 2006, he joined [[Ramoji Film City]] as a Magician. Daily he used to perform three Magic shows round the year. He was greatly inspired by works of [[David Blaine]] and [[Criss Angel]].<ref name=\":1\"/> \n{{quote box\n| width = 100%\n| border = 2px\n| fontsize = 100%\n| bgcolor = #E6FBFF\n| align = center\n| quote = '' \" Film city days were the best part of my life. Those were the days of Happiness, Sadness, Hard work and Earnings. That transformed me a lot and encouraged to achieve more\"''\n| salign = right\n| source = \u2014 Sudigali Sudheer in one of his interviews in March 2017<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|title= Sudigali Sudheer Interview |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F-IH-kH5Cho|work=Telugu Film Nagar|accessdate=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n}}\n\n=== Comeback, Resurgence and Introduction to Small Screen (2009\u20132012)===\n\nAfter two and half years of work in Film city, he left the job to achieve acting career goals. But this decision yielded no results. With no options left, he joined and worked with ''Ali'', his Magic Guru, one of the finest Magician in Hyderabad. During those days, his earnings dried up and there were times he used to drink sink water and had no money to afford a meal. Things changed slowly, he started to conduct magic shows and game shows. He conducted magic shows for Local TV where he met Getup Srinu and Pradeep Machiraju. Later he started an event management firm and organised many shows and Events. In 2011, his Magic Talent got him an opportunity to conduct Magic show for Maa TV in a big way. Magic Mantra, Street Magic Sweet Magic, Abrakadabra shows were the first Feathers in his TV Career.<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\n=== Breakthrough and Acclaim (2013\u20132014)===\n\n'''Jabardasth'''\n\nSudheer got his career break through ''Jabardasth'', Telugu comedy television series produced by [[Mallemala]] Entertainments and telecast on [[ETV Network]]. He was one of the team members in ''\u2018Venu Wonders\u2019'' led by Venu. His first episode aired on 7 February 2013. His performance was highly appreciated by Judges Nagendra Babu and Roja. Every time he used to impress the judges and audiences with outstanding performance. He got opportunity to lead his own team, teamed up with his best friends Getup Srinu, Auto Ramprasad and Sunny to form '''''Sudigali Sudheer & Team'''''. That's when he got stage name Sudigali Sudheer. His first skit as Team leader telecasted on 15 August 2013. His team became instant hit due to his timings, expressions, Srinu's Get-ups, Ramprasad's auto punches. His team won \"Performers of the day\" many times. In an interview, he revealed that it's because of Getup Srinu he got chance to perform in ''Venu Wonders Team''.\n\n=== Rise to Stardom and Prominence (2015\u2013present)===\n\n'''Extra Jabardasth'''\n[[File:Sudigaali sudheer performing a skit from Jabardasth.png|thumbnail|right|upright=1.15|alt=|'''Sudigali Sudheer performing a skit in ''[[Extra Jabardasth]]''''' ]]\n\nSudheer's team later moved into [[Extra Jabardasth]], spin off of ''Jabardasth'' Comedy TV Series. The first episode of this show telecasted on [[ETV Network]] on 10 October 2014. The series garnered very good response from the audience. His team has won \"Performers of the day\" many times here as well. Currently all his skits are performed in Extra Jabardasth. He has also made guest appearance for other team leader's skits in ''Jabardasth'' and ''Extra Jabardasth'' on multiple occasions.\n\n'''Dhee Ultimate Dance Show (Season 9,10,11 and 12)'''\n\nSudheer got his career second best through [[Dhee Ultimate Dance Show]], south India's biggest dance reality show produced by [[Mallemala]] Entertainments and telecast on [[ETV Network]]. He made his first entry through 9<sup><sup>th</sup></sup> Season of Dhee Ultimate Dance Show as Team Leader. His comedy timings, dance, style, expressions, spontaneity received very good appreciation from the audience. He is also the Title Winner of Dhee Ultimate Dance Show Season 9 and 10 ; Runner up of Dhee Ultimate Dance Show Season 11. Currently, he is the Team Leader for the 12<sup><sup>th</sup></sup> Season of the show.\n\n'''Pove Pora'''\n\nIn 2017, Sudheer started his anchoring career with a new show ''\u2018[[Pove Pora]]\u2019'', an youth game show, co-hosted with anchor Vishnupriya, produced by [[Mallemala]] Entertainments and telecast on [[ETV Plus]]. It received good response from students who were the center theme of the show. The show completed its 100<sup><sup>th</sup></sup> episode on 15 June 2019.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\nAll the films are in Telugu language.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n\n!  Year \n!  Movie \n!  Role \n!  Note\n|-\n\n| 2013 || ''[[Adda (film)|Adda]]'' || Karthik ||\n|-\n\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2014 || ''Arya Chitra''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/telugu/movie-details/arya-chitra/movieshow/62508519.cms|title=Arya Chitra Movie: Showtimes, Review, Trailer, Posters, News & Videos \u2013 eTimes|work=The Times of India}}</ref> || Hari ||\n|-\n| ''[[Race Gurram]]'' || Spandana's driver ||\n|-\n|[[Chakkiligintha]] || Pub Waiter ||\n|-\n| ''[[Brother of Bommali]]'' || Ramakrishna's friend ||\n|-\n\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2015 || ''[[Tiger (2015 film)|Tiger]]'' || Tiger's friend ||\n|-\n| [[Supreme (film)|Supreme]]||Movie Director|| \n|-\n| ''[[Where Is Vidya Balan]]'' ||Vasu's gangmate ||\n|-\n| ''[[Sher (film)|Sher]]'' || ||\n|-\n| ''[[Cinema Choopistha Mava]]'' || College Student ||\n|-\n\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2016|| ''[[Nenu Sailaja]]'' || Hari's friend ||\n|-\n| ''Drishya Kavyam''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.123telugu.com/reviews/drushya-kavyam-telugu-movie-review.html|title=Drusya kavyam Telugu Movie Review \u2013 Drusya kavyam Movie Review \u2013 Drusya kavyam Review and Rating \u2013 Drusya kavyam Cinema Review \u2013 Drusya kavyam Film Review \u2013 Drusya kavyam Telugu Review \u2013 Drusya kavyam Twitter Updates \u2013 Drusya kavyam First Day Talk \u2013 Drusya kavyam Review|date=18 March 2016}}</ref> || College Student ||\n|-\n| ''[[Sardaar Gabbar Singh]]'' || Police Constable ||\n|-\n| ''[[Banthi Poola Janaki]]'' || Akash ||\n|-\n| ''[[Selfie Raja (film)|Selfie Raja]]'' || Police Constable ||\n|-\n\n| rowspan=\"5\"|2017|| ''[[Middle Class Abbayi]]'' || Nani's friend ||\n