 He has also made guest appearance on many shows such as Naa Show Naa Ishtam, WOW 2, Star Mahila, Bhale Chancele, Tell Me The Answer Genes, Cash, Patas, Sixth Sense etc.,\n[[File:Sudigali Sudheer Performing a skit.png|thumbnail|right|upright=1.15|alt=|'''Sudigali Sudheer performing in ''[[Extra Jabardasth]] as team leader''''' ]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n\n!  Years Active In\n!  Shows\n!  Channels\n!  Note\n|-\n \n| rowspan=\"3\"|2010\u20132011|| ''Street Magic Sweet Magic'' || Local TV || Magician & Host\n|-\n\n| ''Abrakadabra'' ||[[Star Maa Music]] || Magician & Host\n|-\n\n| ''Magic Mantra'' || [[Star Maa Music]] || Magician & Host\n|-\n\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2013\u2013present || ''[[Jabardasth (comedy show)|Jabardasth]]''  || rowspan=\"7\"|''[[ETV Network]]'' || Team Leader\n|-\n|''[[Extra Jabardasth]]''|| Team Leader\n|-\n\n| 2016 || Naa Show Naa Ishtam ||  Host for 1 episode\n|-\n| 2016\u20132017 || ''[[Dhee Ultimate Dance Show|Dhee Jodi \u2013 Season 09]]''|| Team Leader & Winner\n|-\n| 2017\u20132018 || ''[[Dhee Ultimate Dance Show|Dhee \u2013 Season 10]]''|| Team Leader & Winner\n|-\n|2018\u20132019 || ''[[Dhee Ultimate Dance Show|Dhee Jodi \u2013 Season 11]]'' || Team Leader & Runner-up\n|-\n| 2017\u2013present || ''[[Pove Pora]]''|| Host\n|-\n|2018 || ''Jackpot \u2013 2'' || ''[[Sun TV Network]]''|| Host for only 4 episodes\n|-\n|2019 || Drama Juniors Blockbuster Special || ''[[Zee Telugu]]''|| Host \n|-\n|2019\u2013present|| ''[[Dhee Ultimate Dance Show|Dhee Champions \u2013 Season 12]]''||''[[ETV Network]]'' || Team Leader\n|-\n|2019 || Ali Tho Saradhaga || ''[[ETV Network]]''|| Guest \n|-\n|}\n\n== Television films ==\n\n[[ETV Network]] Festival shows are huge hit among the audience. They have excelled in bringing festivity, tradition, celebration to the show. The shows comprises members of Jabardasth, Extra Jabardasth, Dhee Ultimate Dance Show, Pataas, Pove Pora and Star Mahila along with Celebrity guests for the events, which is successful in making and telecasting of Festival celebrations till date in reference to the Culture.\n[[File:Sudigali Sudheer.png|thumbnail|right|upright=1.15|alt=|Sudigali Sudheer in [[ETV Network|ETV]] Sankranthi Special Event'''''\" Sarada Sankranthi \"''''' ]]\n\nThis is the list of Television film of this team, which is also available on YouTube.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n\n! S.No\n! Year\n! Event\n! Note\n|-\n\n|01\n|2014\n|''New Year Special 2015'' \n|\n|-\n\n|02\n| 2015\n|''New Year Special 2016'' \n|\n|-\n\n|03\n|  rowspan=\"5\" | 2016\n|''Ugadi Ullasam''\n|\n|-\n\n|04\n|''Hai Hai Vinayaka'' \n|\n|-\n\n|05 \n|''Dasara Mahotsavam''\n|\n|-\n\n|06\n|''Sambaram''\n|\n|-\n\n|07 \n|''Welcome to the Party 2017''\n|\n|-\n\n|08 \n| rowspan=\"6\" | 2017\n|''Sankranthi Pandem Kollu'' \n|\n|-\n\n|09\n|''Ugadi 369'' \n|\n|-\n\n|10\n|''Ganapati Bappa Moriya''\n| Co-Hosted with [[Pradeep Machiraju]]\n|-\n\n|11\n|''Dasara Mahotsavam'' \n|\n|-\n\n|12 \n|''Pandaga Chesko'' \n| Host\n|-\n\n|13\n|''It's Time to Party 2018'' \n| Host\n|-\n\n|14 \n| rowspan=\"6\" | 2018\n|''Saradaga Sankranti'' \n|\n|-\n\n|15 \n|''Aha Naa Pellanta'' \n|\n|-\n\n|16 \n|''Vachadayyo Swamy''\n|\n|-\n\n|17\n|''Sarrainollu''\n|\n|-\n\n|18\n|''Tarajuvvalu''\n|\n|-\n\n|19\n|''Evadi Gola Vadidi''\n| Host\n|-\n\n|20 \n| rowspan=\"8\" | 2019\n|''Sakutumba Saparivara Sametamga'' \n|Introduced his family as part of show.\n|-\n\n|21\n|''Sudheer Gadi Pelli Gola''\n| Co-Hosted with [[Pradeep Machiraju]]\n|-\n\n|22\n|''Ugadi Allulu''\n| Co-Hosted with [[Pradeep Machiraju]] in [[Zee Telugu]]\n|-\n\n|23\n|''Avunu Valliddaru Godavapaddaru''\n|\n|-\n\n|24\n|''Sudheer Gadi Intlo Deyyam''\n| Host\n|-\n\n|25\n|''Uttama Purushulu''\n|\n|-\n\n|26\n|''Zee Telugu Kutumbam Awards''\n| Co-Hosted with Anchor Ravi and Shyamala in [[Zee Telugu]]\n|-\n\n|27\n|''Aadavari Partylaki Ardhale Verule''\n|\n|-\n\n|28\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2020\n|''Amma Nanna O Sankranti''\n| \n|-\n\n|29\n|''Pandaga Sir Pandaga Anthe''\n|\n|-\n\n|}\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" align=center cellspacing=\"1\" cellpadding=\"1\" style=\"background:#f7f8ff; text-align=center; border: 1px solid #88a; padding: 5px; font-size: 100%; width: 88%;\"\n|+ style=\"background : #ccf\" colspan=\"3\"  | Awards\n! Year \n! Awards\n! Category\n! Nominee / Nominated Work\n! Result\n|-style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| 2018\n| [[Zee Telugu| Zee Telugu TV]] <br> Comedy Awards\n| Best Comedy Gang on Television\n| Sudigali Sudheer and Team\n|{{won}}\n|-style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| 2019\n| [[TV9 (Telugu)|TV9 Telugu]] <br> TV Awards\n| Best Male Anchor \n| Sudigali Sudheer\n|{{won}}\n|-style=\"text-align: center;\"\n| 2019\n| Padma Mohana <br> TV Awards 2019\n| Best Entertainer Award \n| Sudigali Sudheer\n|{{won}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n[[Annapurna Studios]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{Facebook|SudigaliSudheerOfficial}}\n*{{Twitter|sudheeranand}}\n*{{Instagram|sudheeranandbayana}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sudheer, Sudigali}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Telugu cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Telugu television]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Vijayawada]]\n[[Category:Indian male television actors]]\n", "name_user": "Sanali0997", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sudigali_Sudheer"}
{"title_page": "Blaze Foley", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Blaze Foley\n| image            = Blaze Foley.jpg\n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Michael David Fuller\n| alias            = Deputy Dawg\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1949|12|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[Malvern, Arkansas|Malvern]], Arkansas, United States\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1989|2|1|1949|12|18}}\n| death_place      = [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], Texas, United States\n| genre            = [[Country music|Country]], [[Folk music|folk]]\n| years_active     = 1975-1989\n| website          = https://www.blazefoley.com/\n}}\n\n'''Michael David Fuller''' (December 18, 1949 \u2013 February 1, 1989), better known by his stage name '''Blaze Foley''', was an American [[country music]] singer-songwriter, poet, and artist active in Austin, Texas.\n\n==Background==\nFoley was born Michael David Fuller in Malvern, Arkansas on December 18, 1949.<ref name=\":0\" /> He grew up in San Antonio, Texas and performed in a [[gospel music|gospel]] band called ''The Singing Fuller Family'' with his mother, brother and sisters.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CE8xiT3pV6QC&pg=PT566 | title=Handbook of Texas Music | publisher=Texas A&M University Press | author=Jasinski, Laurie E. | year=2012 | pages=566}}</ref> As a child Blaze contracted polio and as a consequence one of his legs was shorter than the other, causing him to drag his foot while walking.<ref name=\"Cocoran\">{{cite web |last1=Cocoran |first1=Michael |title=Blaze Foley: Killing of a Songwriter |url=http://www.michaelcorcoran.net/archives/4496 |website=MichaelCorcoran.net |accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> He was nicknamed \"[[Deputy Dawg]]\" early in his career.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2008-10-31/696273/|title=Faded Love|last=Freeman|first=Doug|date=2008-10-31|work=Austin Chronicle|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref> In the spring of 1975, he was living in a small artists' community just outside Whitesburg, Georgia when he met Sybil Rosen.<ref name=\":1\" /> Rosen and Foley were in a relationship and decided to leave the artist community together to support his music. He went on the road and performed in Atlanta, Chicago, Houston and, finally, Austin, Texas.<ref name=\":1\" /> Together, they ended up in Austin. Foley tried to get into songwriting, but after the move he experienced a lot of career pressure.<ref name=\":1\" /> Foley started drinking more and the bar scene complicated his relationship with Rosen, which eventually ended.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFoley was close friends with [[Townes Van Zandt]] and was greatly influenced by him.<ref name=\"chronicle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/1999-12-24/75224/|title=A Walking Contradiction|author=Nichols|first=Lee|date=24 December 1999|work=Austin Chronicle|accessdate=2018-06-06}}</ref> Foley's stage name was inspired by his admiration of musician [[Red Foley]].<ref name=\"chronicle\" /> Foley placed duct tape on the tips of his cowboy boots to mock the \"Urban Cowboy\"-crazed folks with their silver-tipped cowboy boots. He later made a suit out of duct tape that he wore walking around.\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nThe master tapes from his first studio album were confiscated by the [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] when the executive producer was caught in a drug bust.<ref name=\"rosen\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZBPnxt0oKPgC|title=Living in the Woods in a Tree: Remembering Blaze Foley|author=Rosen, Sybil|first=|publisher=University of North Texas Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=180, 190}}</ref>{{rp|190}} Another studio album disappeared when the master copies were stolen with his belongings from a station wagon that Foley had been given and lived in.<ref name=\"rosen\" />{{rp|180}} A third studio album, ''Wanted More Dead Than Alive'', was thought to have disappeared until, many years after Blaze died, a friend who was cleaning out his car discovered what sounded like the Bee Creek recording sessions on which he and other musicians had performed. This was Foley's last studio album, and he was scheduled to tour the UK with Townes Van Zandt in support of the album. When Foley died, his attorney immediately nullified the recording contract and the master tapes subsequently disappeared (reportedly lost in a flood).\n\nFoley worked with [[Gurf Morlix]], Townes Van Zandt, [[Guy Schwartz]], [[Billy Block]], [[Calvin Russell (musician)|Calvin Russell]], and others.\n\n== Death and legacy ==\nOn February 1, 1989, Foley was at a house in the [[Bouldin Creek, Austin, Texas|Bouldin Creek]] neighborhood of Austin, Texas<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2017-05-05/blaze-foleys-lost-muscle-shoals-recordings/|title=Blaze Foley's Lost Muscle Shoals Recordings|last=Freeman|first=Doug|date=2017-05-05|work=Austin Chronicle|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref> when he was shot in the chest and killed by Carey January, the son of Foley's friend Concho January. Blaze had confronted Carey January accusing him of stealing his father's veteran pension and welfare checks.<ref name=\"Dansby\">{{cite news |last1=Dansby |first1=Andrew |title=Film takes a peek into Blaze Foley's peculiar life |url=https://www.chron.com/entertainment/music/article/Film-takes-a-peek-into-Blaze-Foley-s-peculiar-life-1726372.php#photo-1286570 |accessdate=31 August 2018 |work=The Houston Chronicle |date=24 May 2009}}</ref> Carey January was acquitted of first-degree murder by reason of self-defense. He and his father presented completely different versions of the shooting at trial.<ref>Delgato, Berta, \"Self-defense claimed in singer's death\", ''[[Austin American Statesman]]'', September 28, 1989, p. B1.</ref> Concho January, who has since died, liked to drink and proved an unreliable witness even though he tried to testify against his son.<ref name=\"Dansby\"/>\n\nAt his funeral, Foley's casket was coated with duct tape by his friends.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/deeperbluelifemu00hard|url-access=registration|title=A Deeper Blue: The Life and Music of Townes Van Zandt|publisher=University of North Texas Press|author=Hardy, Robert Earl|year=2008|pages=[https://archive.org/details/deeperbluelifemu00hard/page/208 208]}}</ref> [[Townes Van Zandt]] told a story where he and his musicians went to Foley's grave to dig up his body because they wanted the pawn ticket that Foley had for Townes's guitar.<ref name=\"chronicle\" />\n\n=== Film and television  ===\nFoley's music is featured prominently in a feature-length documentary film about him entitled ''Blaze Foley: Duct Tape Messiah'', released in 2011 by filmmaker Kevin Triplett.\n\nFoley's song \"Let Me Ride in Your Big Cadillac\" featured prominently at the end of Episode 8 (July 2016) of the first season of the television show [[Preacher (TV series)|''Preacher'']].\n\n\"Cold, Cold World\" is featured in Episode 4, Season 5 of ''The Mentalist''.\n\nIn 2016 his song \"Clay Pigeons\" featured on the soundtrack of the movie \"Homestate\"\n\nIn January 2018, [[Blaze (2018 film)|''Blaze'']], a biographical drama directed by [[Ethan Hawke]],<ref name=\":2\" /> premiered at the [[2018 Sundance Film Festival|Sundance Film Festival]]. The screenplay was adapted by Hawke from the novel ''Living in the Woods in a Tree: Remembering Blaze'' by Sybil Rosen. The film stars musician [[Ben Dickey]] as Foley, [[Alia Shawkat]] as Sybil Rosen, and [[Charlie Sexton]] as Townes Van Zandt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/blaze-review-ethan-hawke-sundance-1202671659|title=Film Review: \u2018BLAZE\u2019|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|date=2018-01-22|work=Variety|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nTownes Van Zandt wrote the 1990 song \"Blaze's Blues\" about his friend <ref>https://www.austinchronicle.com/features/2018-08-17/the-ballad-of-townes-and-blaze/</ref> and first released it on his 1991 live album ''Rain on a Conga Drum - Live in Berlin''. He re-released it multiple times, notably on his two-disc album ''Live at Union Chapel, London, England''.\n\n[[Lucinda Williams]] wrote a Foley tribute song titled \"Drunken Angel\" for her 1998 album ''[[Car Wheels on a Gravel Road]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2000/06/05/delta-nights|title=Delta Nights - A singer\u2019s love affair with loss|last1=Buford|first1=Bill|date=5 June 2000|work=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Gurf Morlix]] wrote a Foley tribute song titled \"Music You Mighta Made\" for his 2009 album ''Last Exit to Happyland''. On February 1, 2011, Morlix released a 15-song collection of Foley cover songs titled ''[[Blaze Foley's 113th Wet Dream]]''.\n\n[[Kings of Leon]] recorded a Foley tribute song titled \"[[Reverend (song)|Reverend]]\" on their 2016 album ''[[Walls (Kings of Leon album)|Walls]]''.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/kings-of-leon-reveal-the-story-behind-reverend-1.3953608</ref>\n\nIn 1998, a various artist Foley digital tribute album was released titled ''Blaze Foley: In Tribute and Loving Memory...Volume One'', which includes Foley's work by 15 artists (Deep State Production).<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Various-Blaze-Foley-In-Tribute-And-Loving-Memory--Volume-One-BFI-Volume-One/release/3778228</ref>\n\nHis 1979 song \"If I Could Only Fly\" was covered on [[Merle Haggard]] and [[Willie Nelson]]'s 1987 duet album ''[[Seashores of Old Mexico]]'', with the song reaching Number 58 on the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Hot Country Songs]] singles chart. It was covered again by Haggard on his 2000 album ''[[If I Could Only Fly]]''. [[Joe Nichols]] recorded it as a duet with [[Lee Ann Womack]] on his 2007 album ''[[Real Things (Joe Nichols album)|Real Things]]''. [[Nanci Griffith]] recorded it on her 2012 album ''[[Intersection (album)|Intersection]]''. [[Kimmie Rhodes]] recorded it on the aforementioned 1998 Foley tribute album ''Blaze Foley: In Tribute and Loving Memory...Volume One''.\n\nHis song \"Election Day\" was covered by [[Lyle Lovett]] on his 2003 album ''[[My Baby Don't Tolerate]]''.\n\nHis song \"Clay Pigeons\" was covered by [[John Prine]] on his Grammy Award-winning 2005 album ''[[Fair & Square]]'' and by [[Michael Cera]] on his 2014 album ''[[True That]]''.\n\nIn 2009, at the request of Foley's estate, Texas singer-songwriter and old-time music historian Jon Hogan was tasked with adding music to three unearthed songs from lyrics found in Foley's handwriting after his death. The three \"new\" songs \"Every Now and Then\", \"Safe in the Arms of Love\", and \"Can't Always Cry\" were recorded by Hogan on his 2010 tribute album ''Every Now and Then: Songs of Townes Van Zandt & Blaze Foley''.<ref>https://store.cdbaby.com/cd/jonhogan</ref> In 2017, Hogan and musical partner Maria Moss re-recorded \"Can't Always Cry\" for their album ''In Dreams I Go Back Home''.\n\n==Quotes==\n\n===About Foley===\n* \"He's only gone crazy once. Decided to stay.\" \u2013 [[Townes Van Zandt]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wideopencountry.com/blaze-foley-outlaw-legend/|title=Blaze Foley: The Outlaw Legend You May Not Know About But Should|date=2017-12-19|work=Wide Open Country|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* \"Blaze Foley was a genius and a beautiful loser.\" \u2013 [[Lucinda Williams]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/01/blaze-review-ethan-hawke-benjamin-dickey-sundance-2018-1201922356/|title=\u2018Blaze\u2019 Review: Ethan Hawke Directs a Gonzo Indie Country-Western Opera About an Unsung Legend \u2014 Sundance 2018|last=Ehrlich|first=David|date=2018-01-28|work=IndieWire|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Album name\n!Year released\n!Publisher\n!Notes\n|-\n|''If I Could Only Fly/Let Me Ride in Your Big Cadillac''\n|1979\n|Zephyr Records\n|7\" 45-only release; 1000\n|-\n|''Blaze Foley''\n|1984\n|Vital Records\n|LP-only release; 7497-33\n|-\n|''Girl Scout Cookies/Oval Room'' \n|1984\n|Vital Records\n|7\" 45-only release; 7077\n|-\n|''Live at the Austin Outhouse (...And Not There)''\n|1989\n|Outhouse Records\n|cassette-only release\n|-\n|''Live at the Austin Outhouse''\n|1999\n|Lost Art Records\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|''Oval Room'' \n|2004\n|Lost Art Records\n|<ref name=\":3\" />(Munic/Indigo)\n|-\n|''Wanted More Dead Than Alive''\n|2005\n|Waddell Hollow Records\n|\n|-\n|''Cold, Cold World''\n|2006\n|Lost Art Records\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|''Sittin' by the Road''\n|2010\n|Lost Art Records\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|''The Dawg Years''\n|2010\n|[[Fat Possum Records]]\n|\n|-\n|''Duct Tape Messiah Documentary Soundtrack''\n|2011\n|Lost Art Records\n|\n|-\n|''Blaze Foley'' (reissue)\n|2012\n|Big Pink\n|(Big Pink re-issue of Vital Records LP)\n|-\n|''Blaze Foley The Lost Muscle Shoals Recordings''\n|2017\n|Lost Art Records\n|featuring the [[Muscle Shoals Horns]], Foley's first recorded album from a 1984 session recorded at [[Broadway Sound Studio]].<ref name=\":3\" /> This album was missing for many years due to the DEA drug bust of the executive producer.<ref name=\":3\" /> \n|}\n\n== Literature ==\n*Carmen und Kai Nees: ''Blaze Foley - Ein Aussenseiter, der zur Legende wurde'' - Self-published in 2018; {{ISBN|978-3-00-058564-7}} - Book in German.\n*Carmen und Kai Nees: ''Blaze Foley - From Misfit To Legend'' - Self-published in 2018; {{ISBN|978-3-00-060018-0}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20180125160711/http://www.sybilrosen.com/blaze.htm Living In The Woods In A Tree: Remembering Blaze Foley\" by Sybil Rosen (memoir, available at Amazon.com)]\n*[http://www.blazefoley.com/ Official Site]\n*[http://www.blazefoleymovie.com Documentary movie website]\n*{{IMDb title|1414820|Blaze Foley: Duct Tape Messiah}}\n*[http://www.blazefoleybuch.de Website of the book publication (Blaze Foley - From Misfit To Legend)]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Foley, Blaze}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:1989 deaths]]\n[[Category:American alternative country singers]]\n[[Category:People from Malvern, Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:20th-century American singers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Texas]]\n[[Category:Country musicians from Arkansas]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2011}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name             = Blaze Foley\n| image            = Blaze Foley.jpg\n| caption          = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Michael David Fuller\n| alias            = Deputy Dawg\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|1949|12|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[Malvern, Arkansas|Malvern]], Arkansas, United States\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1989|2|1|1949|12|18}}\n| death_place      = [[Austin, Texas|Austin]], Texas, United States\n| genre            = [[Country music|Country]], [[Folk music|folk]]\n| years_active     = 1975-1989\n| website          = https://www.blazefoley.com/\n}}\n\n'''Michael David Fuller''' (December 18, 1949 \u2013 February 1, 1989), better known by his stage name '''Blaze Foley''', was an American [[country music]] singer-songwriter, poet, and artist active in Austin, Texas.\n\n==Background==\nFoley was born Michael David Fuller in Malvern, Arkansas on December 18, 1949.<ref name=\":0\" /> He grew up in San Antonio, Texas and performed in a [[gospel music|gospel]] band called ''The Singing Fuller Family'' with his mother, brother and sisters.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CE8xiT3pV6QC&pg=PT566 | title=Handbook of Texas Music | publisher=Texas A&M University Press | author=Jasinski, Laurie E. | year=2012 | pages=566}}</ref> As a child Blaze contracted polio and as a consequence one of his legs was shorter than the other, causing him to drag his foot while walking.<ref name=\"Cocoran\">{{cite web |last1=Cocoran |first1=Michael |title=Blaze Foley: Killing of a Songwriter |url=http://www.michaelcorcoran.net/archives/4496 |website=MichaelCorcoran.net |accessdate=31 August 2018}}</ref> He was nicknamed \"Deputy Dawg\" early in his career.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2008-10-31/696273/|title=Faded Love|last=Freeman|first=Doug|date=2008-10-31|work=Austin Chronicle|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref> In the spring of 1975, he was living in a small artists' community just outside Whitesburg, Georgia when he met Sybil Rosen.<ref name=\":1\" /> Rosen and Foley were in a relationship and decided to leave the artist community together to support his music. He went on the road and performed in Atlanta, Chicago, Houston and, finally, Austin, Texas.<ref name=\":1\" /> Together, they ended up in Austin. Foley tried to get into songwriting, but after the move he experienced a lot of career pressure.<ref name=\":1\" /> Foley started drinking more and the bar scene complicated his relationship with Rosen, which eventually ended.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFoley was close friends with [[Townes Van Zandt]] and was greatly influenced by him.<ref name=\"chronicle\">{{cite web|url=http://www.austinchronicle.com/music/1999-12-24/75224/|title=A Walking Contradiction|author=Nichols|first=Lee|date=24 December 1999|work=Austin Chronicle|accessdate=2018-06-06}}</ref> Foley's stage name was inspired by his admiration of musician [[Red Foley]].<ref name=\"chronicle\" /> Foley placed duct tape on the tips of his cowboy boots to mock the \"Urban Cowboy\"-crazed folks with their silver-tipped cowboy boots. He later made a suit out of duct tape that he wore walking around.\n\n==Music and lyrics==\nThe master tapes from his first studio album were confiscated by the [[Drug Enforcement Administration|DEA]] when the executive producer was caught in a drug bust.<ref name=\"rosen\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZBPnxt0oKPgC|title=Living in the Woods in a Tree: Remembering Blaze Foley|author=Rosen, Sybil|first=|publisher=University of North Texas Press|year=2008|isbn=|location=|pages=180, 190}}</ref>{{rp|190}} Another studio album disappeared when the master copies were stolen with his belongings from a station wagon that Foley had been given and lived in.<ref name=\"rosen\" />{{rp|180}} A third studio album, ''Wanted More Dead Than Alive'', was thought to have disappeared until, many years after Blaze died, a friend who was cleaning out his car discovered what sounded like the Bee Creek recording sessions on which he and other musicians had performed. This was Foley's last studio album, and he was scheduled to tour the UK with Townes Van Zandt in support of the album. When Foley died, his attorney immediately nullified the recording contract and the master tapes subsequently disappeared (reportedly lost in a flood).\n\nFoley worked with [[Gurf Morlix]], Townes Van Zandt, [[Guy Schwartz]], [[Billy Block]], [[Calvin Russell (musician)|Calvin Russell]], and others.\n\n== Death and legacy ==\nOn February 1, 1989, Foley was at a house in the [[Bouldin Creek, Austin, Texas|Bouldin Creek]] neighborhood of Austin, Texas<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/music/2017-05-05/blaze-foleys-lost-muscle-shoals-recordings/|title=Blaze Foley's Lost Muscle Shoals Recordings|last=Freeman|first=Doug|date=2017-05-05|work=Austin Chronicle|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref> when he was shot in the chest and killed by Carey January, the son of Foley's friend Concho January. Blaze had confronted Carey January accusing him of stealing his father's veteran pension and welfare checks.<ref name=\"Dansby\">{{cite news |last1=Dansby |first1=Andrew |title=Film takes a peek into Blaze Foley's peculiar life |url=https://www.chron.com/entertainment/music/article/Film-takes-a-peek-into-Blaze-Foley-s-peculiar-life-1726372.php#photo-1286570 |accessdate=31 August 2018 |work=The Houston Chronicle |date=24 May 2009}}</ref> Carey January was acquitted of first-degree murder by reason of self-defense. He and his father presented completely different versions of the shooting at trial.<ref>Delgato, Berta, \"Self-defense claimed in singer's death\", ''[[Austin American Statesman]]'', September 28, 1989, p. B1.</ref> Concho January, who has since died, liked to drink and proved an unreliable witness even though he tried to testify against his son.<ref name=\"Dansby\"/>\n\nAt his funeral, Foley's casket was coated with duct tape by his friends.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/deeperbluelifemu00hard|url-access=registration|title=A Deeper Blue: The Life and Music of Townes Van Zandt|publisher=University of North Texas Press|author=Hardy, Robert Earl|year=2008|pages=[https://archive.org/details/deeperbluelifemu00hard/page/208 208]}}</ref> [[Townes Van Zandt]] told a story where he and his musicians went to Foley's grave to dig up his body because they wanted the pawn ticket that Foley had for Townes's guitar.<ref name=\"chronicle\" />\n\n=== Film and television  ===\nFoley's music is featured prominently in a feature-length documentary film about him entitled ''Blaze Foley: Duct Tape Messiah'', released in 2011 by filmmaker Kevin Triplett.\n\nFoley's song \"Let Me Ride in Your Big Cadillac\" featured prominently at the end of Episode 8 (July 2016) of the first season of the television show [[Preacher (TV series)|''Preacher'']].\n\n\"Cold, Cold World\" is featured in Episode 4, Season 5 of ''The Mentalist''.\n\nIn 2016 his song \"Clay Pigeons\" featured on the soundtrack of the movie \"Homestate\"\n\nIn January 2018, [[Blaze (2018 film)|''Blaze'']], a biographical drama directed by [[Ethan Hawke]],<ref name=\":2\" /> premiered at the [[2018 Sundance Film Festival|Sundance Film Festival]]. The screenplay was adapted by Hawke from the novel ''Living in the Woods in a Tree: Remembering Blaze'' by Sybil Rosen. The film stars musician [[Ben Dickey]] as Foley, [[Alia Shawkat]] as Sybil Rosen, and [[Charlie Sexton]] as Townes Van Zandt.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/blaze-review-ethan-hawke-sundance-1202671659|title=Film Review: \u2018BLAZE\u2019|last=Gleiberman|first=Owen|date=2018-01-22|work=Variety|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n=== Music ===\nTownes Van Zandt wrote the 1990 song \"Blaze's Blues\" about his friend <ref>https://www.austinchronicle.com/features/2018-08-17/the-ballad-of-townes-and-blaze/</ref> and first released it on his 1991 live album ''Rain on a Conga Drum - Live in Berlin''. He re-released it multiple times, notably on his two-disc album ''Live at Union Chapel, London, England''.\n\n[[Lucinda Williams]] wrote a Foley tribute song titled \"Drunken Angel\" for her 1998 album ''[[Car Wheels on a Gravel Road]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2000/06/05/delta-nights|title=Delta Nights - A singer\u2019s love affair with loss|last1=Buford|first1=Bill|date=5 June 2000|work=[[The New Yorker]]|accessdate=23 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Gurf Morlix]] wrote a Foley tribute song titled \"Music You Mighta Made\" for his 2009 album ''Last Exit to Happyland''. On February 1, 2011, Morlix released a 15-song collection of Foley cover songs titled ''[[Blaze Foley's 113th Wet Dream]]''.\n\n[[Kings of Leon]] recorded a Foley tribute song titled \"[[Reverend (song)|Reverend]]\" on their 2016 album ''[[Walls (Kings of Leon album)|Walls]]''.<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/radio/q/kings-of-leon-reveal-the-story-behind-reverend-1.3953608</ref>\n\nIn 1998, a various artist Foley digital tribute album was released titled ''Blaze Foley: In Tribute and Loving Memory...Volume One'', which includes Foley's work by 15 artists (Deep State Production).<ref>https://www.discogs.com/Various-Blaze-Foley-In-Tribute-And-Loving-Memory--Volume-One-BFI-Volume-One/release/3778228</ref>\n\nHis 1979 song \"If I Could Only Fly\" was covered on [[Merle Haggard]] and [[Willie Nelson]]'s 1987 duet album ''[[Seashores of Old Mexico]]'', with the song reaching Number 58 on the [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] [[Hot Country Songs]] singles chart. It was covered again by Haggard on his 2000 album ''[[If I Could Only Fly]]''. [[Joe Nichols]] recorded it as a duet with [[Lee Ann Womack]] on his 2007 album ''[[Real Things (Joe Nichols album)|Real Things]]''. [[Nanci Griffith]] recorded it on her 2012 album ''[[Intersection (album)|Intersection]]''. [[Kimmie Rhodes]] recorded it on the aforementioned 1998 Foley tribute album ''Blaze Foley: In Tribute and Loving Memory...Volume One''.\n\nHis song \"Election Day\" was covered by [[Lyle Lovett]] on his 2003 album ''[[My Baby Don't Tolerate]]''.\n\nHis song \"Clay Pigeons\" was covered by [[John Prine]] on his Grammy Award-winning 2005 album ''[[Fair & Square]]'' and by [[Michael Cera]] on his 2014 album ''[[True That]]''.\n\nIn 2009, at the request of Foley's estate, Texas singer-songwriter and old-time music historian Jon Hogan was tasked with adding music to three unearthed songs from lyrics found in Foley's handwriting after his death. The three \"new\" songs \"Every Now and Then\", \"Safe in the Arms of Love\", and \"Can't Always Cry\" were recorded by Hogan on his 2010 tribute album ''Every Now and Then: Songs of Townes Van Zandt & Blaze Foley''.<ref>https://store.cdbaby.com/cd/jonhogan</ref> In 2017, Hogan and musical partner Maria Moss re-recorded \"Can't Always Cry\" for their album ''In Dreams I Go Back Home''.\n\n==Quotes==\n\n===About Foley===\n* \"He's only gone crazy once. Decided to stay.\" \u2013 [[Townes Van Zandt]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wideopencountry.com/blaze-foley-outlaw-legend/|title=Blaze Foley: The Outlaw Legend You May Not Know About But Should|date=2017-12-19|work=Wide Open Country|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n* \"Blaze Foley was a genius and a beautiful loser.\" \u2013 [[Lucinda Williams]]<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.indiewire.com/2018/01/blaze-review-ethan-hawke-benjamin-dickey-sundance-2018-1201922356/|title=\u2018Blaze\u2019 Review: Ethan Hawke Directs a Gonzo Indie Country-Western Opera About an Unsung Legend \u2014 Sundance 2018|last=Ehrlich|first=David|date=2018-01-28|work=IndieWire|access-date=2018-06-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n!Album name\n!Year released\n!Publisher\n!Notes\n|-\n|''If I Could Only Fly/Let Me Ride in Your Big Cadillac''\n|1979\n|Zephyr Records\n|7\" 45-only release; 1000\n|-\n|''Blaze Foley''\n|1984\n|Vital Records\n|LP-only release; 7497-33\n|-\n|''Girl Scout Cookies/Oval Room'' \n|1984\n|Vital Records\n|7\" 45-only release; 7077\n|-\n|''Live at the Austin Outhouse (...And Not There)''\n|1989\n|Outhouse Records\n|cassette-only release\n|-\n|''Live at the Austin Outhouse''\n|1999\n|Lost Art Records\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|''Oval Room'' \n|2004\n|Lost Art Records\n|<ref name=\":3\" />(Munic/Indigo)\n|-\n|''Wanted More Dead Than Alive''\n|2005\n|Waddell Hollow Records\n|\n|-\n|''Cold, Cold World''\n|2006\n|Lost Art Records\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|''Sittin' by the Road''\n|2010\n|Lost Art Records\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|''The Dawg Years''\n|2010\n|[[Fat Possum Records]]\n|\n|-\n|''Duct Tape Messiah Documentary Soundtrack''\n|2011\n|Lost Art Records\n|\n|-\n|''Blaze Foley'' (reissue)\n|2012\n|Big Pink\n|(Big Pink re-issue of Vital Records LP)\n|-\n|''Blaze Foley The Lost Muscle Shoals Recordings''\n|2017\n|Lost Art Records\n|featuring the [[Muscle Shoals Horns]], Foley's first recorded album fro