{"title_page": "John N. Brandenburg", "text_new": "{{short description|American lieutenant general}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= John N. Brandenburg\n|image= JohnBrandenburg.jpg\n|image_size= 250\n|alt= \n|caption= \n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1929|4|29}}\n|birth_place= [[Enid, Oklahoma]]\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2020|1|14|1929|4|29}}\n|death_place= [[Canton, Georgia]]\n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1951\u20131984\n|rank= [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]]<br/>[[101st Airborne Division]]\n|battles= [[Korean War]]<br/>[[Vietnam War]]\n|awards= [[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Silver Star]] (2)<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (3)<br/>[[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (2)<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (2)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''John Nelson Brandenburg''' (April 29, 1929 \u2013 January 14, 2020) was a [[Lieutenant general (United States)|lieutenant general]] in the [[United States Army]]. He was commander of [[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]] at [[Fort Lewis]] from 1981 to 1984. He was also a commander of the [[101st Airborne Division]] (1978\u20131980).<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Delta|author=Sigma Nu|date=1990|issue=v. 107\u2013109|publisher=Sigma Nu Fraternity|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Wc5KAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=Army executive biographies|author=United States. Dept. of the Army|date=1985|publisher=Headquarters, Dept. of the Army|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=zqRPfg2-KCEC|accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\nBrandenburg died at his home in [[Canton, Georgia]], on January 14, 2020. He was 90.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.darbyfuneralhome.com/obituaries/Lieutenant-General-John-Brandenburg/#!/Obituary|title=Lieutenant General John Nelson Brandenburg|publisher=Darby Funeral Home|date=January 2020|accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brandenburg, John N.}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Enid, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Star]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n\n{{US-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American lieutenant general}}\n{{Infobox military person\n|name= John N. Brandenburg\n|image= JohnBrandenburg.jpg\n|image_size= 250\n|alt= \n|caption= \n|nickname= \n|birth_date= {{Birth date|1929|4|29}}\n|birth_place= [[Enid, Oklahoma]]\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2020|1|14|1929|4|29}}\n|death_place= [[Canton, Georgia]]\n|placeofburial= \n|allegiance= United States\n|branch= [[United States Army]]\n|serviceyears= 1951\u20131984\n|rank= [[Lieutenant general (United States)|Lieutenant General]]\n|servicenumber= \n|unit= \n|commands= [[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]]<br/>[[101st Airborne Division]]\n|battles= [[Korean War]]<br/>[[Vietnam War]]\n|awards= [[Army Distinguished Service Medal]]<br/>[[Silver Star]] (2)<br/>[[Legion of Merit]] (3)<br/>[[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] (2)<br/>[[Bronze Star Medal]] (2)\n|relations= \n|laterwork= \n}}\n'''John Nelson Brandenburg''' (April 29, 1929 \u2013 January 14, 2020) was a [[Lieutenant general (United States)|lieutenant general]] in the [[United States Army]]. He was commander of [[I Corps (United States)|I Corps]] at [[Fort Lewis]] from 1981 to 1984. He was also a commander of the [[101st Airborne Division]] (1978\u20131980).<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=Delta|author=Sigma Nu|date=1990|issue=v. 107-109|publisher=Sigma Nu Fraternity|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Wc5KAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref><ref name=\"google2\">{{cite book|title=Army executive biographies|author=United States. Dept. of the Army|date=1985|publisher=Headquarters, Dept. of the Army|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=zqRPfg2-KCEC|accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\nBrandenburg died at his home in [[Canton, Georgia]], on January 14, 2020. He was 90.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.darbyfuneralhome.com/obituaries/Lieutenant-General-John-Brandenburg/#!/Obituary|title=Lieutenant General John Nelson Brandenburg|publisher=Darby Funeral Home|date=January 2020|accessdate=January 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brandenburg, John N.}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Vietnam War]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Enid, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Service Medal (US Army)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Legion of Merit]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Silver Star]]\n[[Category:United States Army generals]]\n\n{{US-mil-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Abraham, B.S.", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_N._Brandenburg"}
{"title_page": "Vishnupriya (actress)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vishnupriya\n| image              = \n| imagesize          = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1987|02|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bahrain]]\n| other_names   =\n| occupation         = Actress, Model\n| height             = 5 ft 7 inches\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Vinay Vijayan|2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/malayalam/actress-vishnupriya-pillai-ties-the-knot-with-vinay-vijayan/articleshow/69890545.cms|title=Actress Vishnupriya Pillai ties the knot with Vinay Vijayan|publisher=indiatimes.com|date=21 June 2019}}</ref>\n| years_active       = 2007-present\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Vishnupriya Ramchandran''' (born 22 February 1987 in Bahrain), better known as '''Vishnupriya''', is an Indian film actress,<ref>http://www.truthplaza.xyz</ref> dancer and model. She started off her career participating in the dance reality show Vodafone Thakadimi which was aired on [[Asianet (TV channel)|Asianet]]. She made her acting debut in 2007 with ''Speed Track'', playing a supporting character. Later, she played the lead character in ''[[Keralotsavam 2009]]'' and got noticed for her character in ''[[Penpattanam]]'' (2010). Since then, she has played supporting roles in various films. She made her [[Tamil cinema]] debut in ''[[Naanga]]'' (2011).<ref>http://www.kollyinsider.com/2012/03/vishnupriyas-double-dhamaka.html?m=0</ref> She had performed for AMMA show in 2013. She has also participated in a reality show ''Star Challenge'' on Flowers TV.\n\n==Early life==\nVishnupriya was born and brought up at Bahrain.<ref>http://cinetrooth.in/2016/02/07/vishnu-priya-actress-profile-and-biography/</ref> She had done her schooling from The Indian School, Bahrain and completed her BBA degree from The Birla Institute of Technology International Centre. She had participated in various competitions and won the Inter-school championship for [[Bharata Natyam]] during her school days. Apart from dance, she has done few theater works too.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n;Acting\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n! Year !! Film   !!Role!!   Language !! Notes\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Speed Track]]''<ref>http://www.filmibeat.com/celebs/vishnu-priya/filmography.html</ref> || Smitha || Malayalam || \n|-\n|2007|| ''[[Rathri Mazha]]'' || Meera's friend || Malayalam ||\n|-\n| 2009|| ''[[Keralotsavam 2009]]'' || Ganga ||  Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2010 || '' [[Penpattanam]] ''|| Raji || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Makaramanju]]'' || Singer (cameo in song) || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Naanga]]'' || Devi || Tamil || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''Crime Story'' || Meera || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Naughty Professor]]'' || Herself (cameo in song) || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''Puthumukhangal Thevai'' ||Unknown || Tamil || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Banking Hours 10 to 4]]'' || Pooja || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Proprietors: Kammath & Kammath]]'' || Thirumeni's daughter || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Lisammayude Veedu]]'' || Cameo in song || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2013 || ''Police Mamman'' || Anjana || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[God's Own Country (2014 film)|God's Own Country]]'' || Lekha || Malayalam || \n|-\n| 2016|| ''[[Kadhantharam]]'' || Sivani || Malayalam ||\n|-\n| 2019|| ''Chila New Gen Naattu Visheshangal'' || Gayathri || Malayalam ||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[V1 (film)|V1]]'' || Luna || Tamil ||\n|}\n\n== Television ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n! Year !! Program !!   Channel  !!Role !! Notes\n|-\n|2008||Vodafone Thakadhimi ||Asianet|| Contestant||\n|-\n| 2012||Super Dancer Junior||Amrita TV||Celebrity Judge ||\n|-\n| 2012||Star Lights||Rosebowl||Guest ||\n|-\n| 2012||Entertainment News||Asianet News||Guest ||\n|-\n| 2012||Yes I Am||Yes Indiavision TV||Guest ||\n|-\n|2014|| Aarppo Eerro || Kairali TV||  Judge ||replacing [[Shamna Kasim]]\n|-\n|2015||Star Challenge || Flowers TV