 [[United States dollar|US$]]3.1&nbsp;billion (April 2020)<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/igor-bukhman/#2844377b2f5c/|title=#648 Dmitry Bukhman|work=Forbes|access-date=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n| height             = <!-- \"X cm\", \"X m\" or \"X ft Y in\" plus optional reference (conversions are automatic) -->\n| television         = \n| title              = Co-founder of Playrix\n| term               = \n| predecessor        = \n| successor          = \n| party              = \n| movement           = \n| opponents          = \n| boards             = \n| criminal_charge    = <!-- Criminality parameters should be supported with citations from reliable sources -->\n| criminal_penalty   = \n| criminal_status    = \n| spouse             = <!-- Use article title or common name -->\n| partner            = <!-- (unmarried long-term partner) -->\n| children           = \n| parents            = <!-- overrides mother and father parameters -->\n| mother             = <!-- may be used (optionally with father parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| father             = <!-- may be used (optionally with mother parameter) in place of parents parameter (displays \"Parent(s)\" as label) -->\n| relatives          = \n| family             = \n| callsign           = \n| awards             = \n| website            = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| module             = \n| module2            = \n| module3            = \n| module4            = \n| module5            = \n| module6            = \n| signature          = \n| signature_size     = \n| signature_alt      = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Dmitry Anatolyevich Bukhman''' ({{lang-ru|\u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043d\u0430\u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0443\u0445\u043c\u0430\u043d|translit=Dmitrij Anatol'evi\u010d Buchman}}; born May\u200c \u200c27,\u200c \u200c1985\u200c) is a Russian entrepreneur and co-founder of [[video game developer]] [[Playrix]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Novinar Novinar |url=https://russiabusinesstoday.com/featured/russian-game-developers-join-club-of-billionaires/ |title=Russian Game Developers Join Club of Billionaires |publisher=Russia Business Today |date=2019-04-18 |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Bloomberg |url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/04/18/russian-billionaire-brothers-crush-it-with-gaming-powerhouse-playrix-a65284 |title=Russian Billionaire Brothers Crush It With Gaming Powerhouse Playrix |publisher=The Moscow Times |date=2019-04-18 |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDmitry Bukhman was born into a Jewish family in Vologda, Russia in 1985. In 2000, while studying applied math at Vologda University, Dmitry together with his brother [[Igor Bukhman|Igor]] started developing [[PC game]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PvZZxXpfmtw|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f \u0411\u0443\u0445\u043c\u0430\u043d\u044b \u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043c\u0438\u043b\u043b\u0438\u0430\u0440\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0438, \u0430 \u043e\u043d\u043b\u0430\u0439\u043d \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0434\u0430 - \u0433\u043b\u043e\u0431\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0439|via=www.youtube.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2004 Dmitry together with his brother founded [[Playrix]].<ref name=\"meduza1\">{{cite web|url=https://meduza.io/en/feature/2019/04/19/our-games-are-at-the-top-of-the-russian-charts-but-almost-nobody-knows-us-as-a-brand |title=\u2018Our games are at the top of the Russian charts, but almost nobody knows us as a brand\u2019 Two Russian brothers started a video game company and got onto Bloomberg's billionaire list. Here\u2019s their first long interview. \u2014 Meduza |publisher=Meduza.io |date=2019-04-19 |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref> Playrix has been working in the market of casual PC games until 2009 and produced about 30 games by then. In 2009 the studio focused on developing free-to-play games for smartphones and tablets.\nIn 2011 the company moved the headquarters from Vologda to [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hbr-russia.ru/management/operatsionnoe-upravlenie/809875 |title=Harvard Business Review|publisher=Hbr-russia.ru |date=2019-09-09 |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.ru/newsroom/tehnologii/388831-razrabotchiki-igr-iz-vologdy-predskazali-popadanie-v-odnu-ligu-s |title=\u0420\u0430\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0431\u043e\u0442\u0447\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u0438\u0433\u0440 \u0438\u0437 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0434\u044b \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u043e\u0434\u043d\u0443 \u043b\u0438\u0433\u0443 \u0441 \u0441\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f\u043c\u0438 Call of Duty \u0438 Warcraft \u043f\u043e \u0434\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0430\u043c &#124; \u0422\u0435\u0445\u043d\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0438 |publisher=Forbes.ru |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref> In 2013 the first mobile game [[Township (video game)|Township]] was released.<ref name=\"Bloomberg\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-17/billionaire-brothers-crushing-it-with-gaming-powerhouse-playrix |title=Playrix Founders Are Billionaires on Games Fishdom, Gardenscapes |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2019-04-17 |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref> As of December 2019 the company operates 5 free-to-play mobile games (Township, [[Fishdom]], [[Gardenscapes]], [[Homescapes]], and [[Wildscapes]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://vc.ru/flood/33117-esli-tempy-rosta-sohranyatsya-postroenie-kompanii-urovnya-activision-blizzard-ili-ea-zaymet-ne-tak-mnogo-vremeni |title=Activision Blizzard |publisher=Vc.ru |date=2018-02-10 |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref> According to AppAnnie analytics, it is one of the Top 5 grossing mobile publishers worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.appannie.com/en/insights/app-annie-news/top-52-app-publishers-2018/ |title=App Annie\u2019s Top 52 Publishers of 2018 &#124; App Annie Blog |publisher=Appannie.com |date= |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref> The company has 1,700 employees and 15 offices.<ref name=\"meduza1\"/><ref name=\"pocketgamer1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/interview/72200/playrixs-stellar-2019/|title=1,700 staff, 20 games in development, 8 acquisitions, 2 billion dollar games: Playrix's stellar 2019|first1=Matthew|last1=Forde|first2=Staff|last2=Writer|website=pocketgamer.biz}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Dmitry together with his brother Igor acquired a stake in video games developer Nexters Global.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/dmitry-bukhman-1/|title=Dmitry Bukhman|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019 eight mobile game developers have already been acquired by Playrix.<ref name=\"pocketgamer1\" /> Among the biggest acquires and investments are: Serbian Eipix,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/news/72127/playrix-buys-eipix-entertainment/|title=Playrix acquires Serbian game studio Eipix Entertainment|first1=Matthew|last1=Forde|first2=Staff|last2=Writer|website=pocketgamer.biz}}</ref> Ukrainian Zagrava <ref>{{cite web|url=https://ain.ua/en/2019/10/29/playrix-acquires-zagrava-games/ |title=Russian Playrix acquires Ukrainian Zagrava Games for an estimated $1M |publisher=AIN.UA |date= |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref> and Belarussian Vizor game studios.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-12-05/playrix-billionaires-battle-activision-by-snapping-up-studios?srnd=technology-vp |title=Playrix Mobile Gaming Billionaires Take On Activision, EA Sports |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2019-12-05 |accessdate=2020-01-05}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.facebook.com/dmitri.bukhman Bukhman Facebook account]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bukhman, Dmitry}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Vologda]]\n[[Category:Russian billionaires]]\n[[Category:21st-century Russian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n", "name_user": "Archimatyka", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar; more up to date link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dmitry_Bukhman"}
{"title_page": "Avi Shlaim", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Avi Shlaim\n| image = Avi_Shlaim.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1945|10|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]]\n| residence = [[United Kingdom]]\n| nationality = [[Israel]]i\n| citizenship = Israeli-[[United Kingdom|British]]\n| work_institutions = {{Plainlist|\n*[[University of Oxford]] \n*[[University of Reading]] <small>(1970\u20131987)</small>\n }}\n| alma_mater = [[Jesus College, Cambridge]]<br>[[London School of Economics]]<br>[[University of Reading]]\n| known_for = One of Israel's \"[[New Historians]]\"\n}}\n\n'''Avraham''' \"'''Avi'''\" '''Shlaim''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|FBA|FRE}} (born 31 October 1945) is an [[Israel]]i [[historian]], [[Emeritus Professor]] of International Relations at the [[University of Oxford]] and fellow of the [[British Academy]]. He is one of Israel's [[New Historians]],<ref>{{cite news |author=Ethan Bronner |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/11/14/reviews/991114.14bronjt.html |title=Israel: The Revised Edition: Two historians offer re-examinations of the Zionist\u2013Arab conflict. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=14 November 1999 |accessdate=23 March 2014}} Review of ''The Iron Wall'' by Avi Shlaim and ''Righteous Victims'' by Benny Morris, with links to the first chapters of each.</ref> a group of Israeli scholars who put forward critical interpretations of the history of [[Zionism]] and Israel.<ref>Morris, Benny. \"[http://www.press.umich.edu/pdf/9780472115419-ch1.pdf The New Historiography]\" in Morris, Benny. (ed) ''Making Israel''. 1987, pp. 11\u201328.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nShlaim was born to wealthy Jewish parents in [[Baghdad]], Iraq. The family lived in a mansion with ten servants. His father was an importer of building materials with ties to the Iraqi leadership, including then-prime minister [[Nuri al-Said]].<ref name=rapaport>{{cite news |title=No peaceful solution|first=Meron |last=Rapaport|newspaper=[[Haaretz]] Friday Supplement|date=11 August 2005|url=http://www.haaretz.com/no-peaceful-solution-1.166621}}</ref>\n\nThe Iraqi Jews' situation became problematic with [[Israel's War of Independence]] in 1948. In 1951 Shlaim's father was one of 100,000 Jews who registered to leave the country and surrender their citizenship. A subsequent law ruled that all those who left forfeited all rights, including property rights. The Shlaim family lost all their property. His father crossed the border illegally on a mule, while Shlaim, his mother and sisters flew to Cyprus, reuniting in Israel.<ref name=rapaport />\n\nShlaim left Israel for England at the age of 16 to study at a Jewish school.<ref name=rapaport/><ref>{{cite news |last=Shlaim |first=Avi |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/07/gaza-israel-palestine |title=How Israel brought Gaza to the brink of humanitarian catastrophe |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 January 2009 |accessdate=23 March 2014}}</ref> He returned to Israel in the mid-1960s to serve in the [[Israel Defense Forces]], then moved back to England in 1966 to read history at [[Jesus College, Cambridge]]. He obtained his BA degree in 1969.<ref name=\"Oxf\">[https://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/emeritus/avi-shlaim.html Profile: Avi Shlaim] ''University of Oxford</ref> He obtained an MSc (Econ.) in International Relations in 1970 from the [[London School of Economics]] and a PhD from the [[University of Reading]].<ref>[http://www.sant.ox.ac.uk/people/fellows.html Governing Body Fellows]</ref> He was a Lecturer and Reader in Politics in the University of Reading from 1970 to 1987.<ref name=Oxford>[http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/about/staff/staff.asp?action=show&person=62 Professor Avi Shlaim] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070527060151/http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/about/staff/staff.asp?action=show&person=62 |date=27 May 2007 }}, University of Oxford.</ref>\n\nHe married the great-granddaughter of [[David Lloyd George]], who was the British prime minister at the time of the [[Balfour Declaration of 1917|Balfour Declaration]]. He has lived in England ever since, and holds dual British and Israeli nationality.<ref>Avi Shlaim: \"And for the last forty years, I have lived in Britain, and I teach at Oxford\" in [http://www.democracynow.org/2007/5/9/it_takes_an_enormous_amount_of \"It Takes an Enormous Amount of Courage to Speak the Truth When No One Else is Out There\"&nbsp;\u2014 World-Renowned Holocaust, Israel Scholars Defend DePaul Professor Norman Finkelstein as He Fights for Tenur]. Shlaim's interview; democracynow.org, 9 May 2007, accessed 23 March 2014.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Avi Shlaim 2.jpg|thumb|right|Shlaim addressing the Oxford Theology Society]]\nShlaim taught International Relations at Reading University, specialising in European issues. His academic interest in the history of Israel began in 1982, when Israeli government archives about the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]] were opened, an interest that deepened when he became a fellow of [[St Antony's College, Oxford]] in 1987.<ref name=rapaport /> He was Alastair Buchan Reader in International Relations at Oxford from 1987 to 1996 and Director of Graduate Studies in that subject in 1993\u20131995 and 1998\u20132001. He held a British Academy Research Readership in 1995\u201397 and a Research Professorship in 2003\u20132006.<ref name=\"Oxford\" />\n\nShlaim served as an outside examiner on the doctoral thesis of [[Ilan Papp\u00e9]], another notable New Historian. Shlaim's approach to the study of history is informed by his belief that, \"[t]he job of the historian is to judge\".<ref name=rapaport/>\n\nHe is a regular contributor to ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper, and signed an open letter to that paper in January 2009 condemning Israel's role in the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/16/gaza-israel-petitions |title=Growing outrage at the killings in Gaza |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 January 2009 |accessdate=23 March 2014}}. Letter to the editor signed by over 300 academics, writers, and others.</ref>\n\nWriting in the [[The Spectator|''Spectator'']], Shlaim dubbed Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] as a \"proponent of the doctrine of permanent conflict,\" describing his policies as an attempt to preclude a peaceful resolution to the conflict with Palestinians. Furthermore, he described Israeli foreign policy as one that supported stability of Arab regimes over nascent democratic movements during the [[Arab Spring]].<ref>Shlaim, Avi. \"An Israeli spring? Rejecting the prospect of greater democracy in the Arab world could put the Jewish state at risk.\" ''Spectator'' 25 Feb. 2012</ref>\n\nShlaim is a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|UK Labour Party]].<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/15/censorship-battle-and-an-antisemitic-charge-cause-anger|title=Censorship battle and an antisemitic charge cause anger|location=|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=15 October 2017|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> In August 2015, he was a signatory to a letter criticising ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]''{{'}}s reporting of [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s association with alleged [[Antisemitism|antisemites]].<ref name=\"thejc\">{{cite news |last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/142553/anti-israel-activists-attack-jc-challenging-jeremy-corbyn|title=Anti-Israel activists attack JC for challenging Jeremy Corbyn|location= |work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=18 August 2015|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nThe Israeli historians [[Joseph Heller (historian)|Joseph Heller]] and [[Yehoshua Porath]] have claimed that Shlaim \"misleads his readers with arguments that Israel had missed the opportunity for peace while the Arabs are strictly peace seekers\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/right-of-reply-the-wonders-of-the-new-history-1.167424 |title=The wonders of the new history |author=Joseph Heller |author2=Yehoshua Porat |date=18 August 2005 |newspaper=Haaretz |accessdate=23 March 2014}}</ref><!-- Is it necessary to repeat previous ref with the Hebrew version of the same article?<ref>{{cite news |date=16 August 2005 |author=Joseph Heller |author2=Yehoshua Porat |url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/misc/1.1037061 |title=\u05e4\u05dc\u05d0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d4\u05d9\u05e1\u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d7\u05d3\u05e9\u05d4 |trans_title=Wonders of the New History |language=Hebrew}}</ref> --><ref>{{cite book |author=Joseph Heller |date=2000 |title=The Birth of Israel, 1945\u20131949: Ben-Gurion and His Critics |publisher= [[University Press of Florida]] |isbn=0813017327 |page=306}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2012 article in the [[academic journal]] ''Shofar'', Shai Afsai criticised Shlaim for repeating a story \"[[The bride is beautiful but she is married to another man]]\", for which Afsai could not trace an original source, in his 2001 book ''The Iron Wall: Israel and the Arab World''.<ref>\"'The bride is beautiful, but she is married to another man': Historical Fabrication and an Anti-Zionist Myth\", Shai Afsai, ''[[Shofar (journal)|Shofar]]'', Vol. 30, No. 3; 2012, pp. 35\u201361</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Yoav Gelber]], Shlaim's claim that there was a deliberate and pre-meditated anti-Palestinian \u201ccollusion\u201d between the [[Jewish Agency]] and King Abdullah, is unequivocally refuted by the documentary evidence on the development of contacts between Israel and Jordan before, during and after the war.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Yoav Gelber|title=The Israeli-Arab War of 1948 : The Collusion That Never Was|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/isdf/text/gelber.html|website=jewishvirtuallibrary.org|date=July 2009|quote=\"Shlaim\u2019s conjecture of a deliberate and pre-meditated anti-Palestinian \u201ccollusion\u201d does not stand up to a critical examination. The documentary evidence on the development of contacts between Israel and Jordan before, during and after the war unequivocally refutes Shlaim\u2019s conclusions. If there was any collusion against the Palestinians in 1948, it was not concocted by Israel and Abdullah but rather, by Britain and Transjordan. The outcomes reveal that the British acquiescence to a Transjordanian takeover of Arab Palestine was merely a choice by default rather than a plot.\"}}</ref> [[Marc Lynch]] however wrote that \"the voluminous evidence in [Gelber's] book does not allow so conclusive a verdict\".<ref>{{cite journal | author = Marc Lynch | title = Israeli-Jordanian Dialogue, 1948-1953: Cooperation, Conspiracy, or Collusion? by Yoav Gelber | journal = [[Middle East Journal]] | volume = 59 | number = 2 | year = 2005 | pages = 329\u2013330 | jstor = 4330143}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2006, Shlaim was elected [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA), the United Kingdom's [[national academy]] for the humanities and social sciences.<ref name=Oxford/><ref name=\"FBA\">{{cite web|title=Professor Avi Shlaim|url=https://www.britac.ac.uk/user/2165|website=The British Academy|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 September 2017, Shlaim was awarded the [[British Academy Medal]] \"for lifetime achievement\".<ref>{{cite web|title=From Wikipedia to Roman coins: British Academy recognises excellence in the humanities and social sciences|url=https://www.britac.ac.uk/news/wikipedia-roman-coins-british-academy-recognises-excellence-humanities-and-social-sciences|website=The British Academy|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n* ''Collusion across the Jordan: King Abdullah, the Zionist Movement and the Partition of Palestine'' (winner of the 1988 Political Studies Association's W. J. M. Mackenzie Prize)\n*''The Politics of Partition'' (1990 and 1998)\n*''War and Peace in the Middle East: A Concise History'' (1995)\n*''The Cold War and the Middle East'' (co-editor, 1997)\n*''The Iron Wall: Israel and the Arab World'' (New York: [[W.W. Norton]], 2001)\n*''Lion of Jordan: The Life of King Hussein in War and Peace'' (London: [[Allen Lane]], 2007)\n*''Israel and Palestine: Reappraisals, Revisions, Refutations'' (London: [[Verso Books]], 2009)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*[[Benny Morris]]\n*[[Ilan Pappe]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061013030137/http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/about/staff/staff.asp?action=show&person=62&special= Oxford home page]\n* [http://www.thenation.com/doc/20040628/attapatu Interview].  ''[[The Nation]]'', 28 June 2004.\n* [http://www.democracynow.org/2009/1/14/leading_israeli_scholar_avi_shlaim_israel 2009 Interview on Israeli-Palestinian conflict inc. video, audio and text transcript.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110815155354/http://www.frontlineclub.com/events/2009/11/avi-shlaim-in-conversation-with-shlomo-sand.html Video of discussion] between Avi Shlaim and [[Shlomo Sand]]. Chaired by [[Jacqueline Rose]] at the [[Frontline Club]], London, 12 November 2009\n* [http://users.ox.ac.uk/~ssfc0005/The%20Balfour%20Declaration%20and%20its%20consequences.html Shlaim, Avi.\"The Balfour Declaration And its Consequences\"]  in Louis, Wm. Roger, ed., ''Yet More Adventures with Britannia: Personalities, Politics and Culture in Britain'', London,  I.B. Tauris, 2005, pp.&nbsp;251\u2013270.\n{{New Historians}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shlaim, Avi}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:British people of Iraqi-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Fellows of St Antony's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Middle East]]\n[[Category:International relations scholars]]\n[[Category:Iraqi emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Jews]]\n[[Category:Israeli historians]]\n[[Category:Jewish historians]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) people]]\n[[Category:New Historians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the British Academy Medal]]\n[[Category:Writers from Baghdad]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Avi Shlaim\n| image = Avi_Shlaim.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1945|10|31|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Baghdad]], [[Iraq]]\n| residence = [[United Kingdom]]\n| nationality = [[Israel]]i\n| citizenship = Israeli-[[United Kingdom|British]]\n| work_institutions = {{Plainlist|\n*[[University of Oxford]] \n*[[University of Reading]] <small>(1970\u20131987)</small>\n }}\n| alma_mater = [[Jesus College, Cambridge]]<br>[[London School of Economics]]<br>[[University of Reading]]\n| known_for = One of Israel's \"[[New Historians]]\"\n}}\n\n'''Avraham''' \"'''Avi'''\" '''Shlaim''' {{postnominals|country=GBR|FBA|FRE}} (born 31 October 1945) is an [[Israel]]i [[historian]], [[Emeritus Professor]] of International Relations at the [[University of Oxford]] and fellow of the [[British Academy]]. He is one of Israel's [[New Historians]],<ref>{{cite news |author=Ethan Bronner |url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/99/11/14/reviews/991114.14bronjt.html |title=Israel: The Revised Edition: Two historians offer re-examinations of the Zionist\u2013Arab conflict. |newspaper=The New York Times |date=14 November 1999 |accessdate=23 March 2014}} Review of ''The Iron Wall'' by Avi Shlaim and ''Righteous Victims'' by Benny Morris, with links to the first chapters of each.</ref> a group of Israeli scholars who put forward critical interpretations of the history of [[Zionism]] and Israel.<ref>Morris, Benny. \"[http://www.press.umich.edu/pdf/9780472115419-ch1.pdf The New Historiography]\" in Morris, Benny. (ed) ''Making Israel''. 1987, pp. 11\u201328.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nShlaim was born to wealthy Jewish parents in [[Baghdad]], Iraq. The family lived in a mansion with ten servants. His father was an importer of building materials with ties to the Iraqi leadership, including then-prime minister [[Nuri al-Said]].<ref name=rapaport>{{cite news |title=No peaceful solution|first=Meron |last=Rapaport|newspaper=[[Haaretz]] Friday Supplement|date=11 August 2005|url=http://www.haaretz.com/no-peaceful-solution-1.166621}}</ref>\n\nThe Iraqi Jews' situation became problematic with [[Israel's War of Independence]] in 1948. In 1951 Shlaim's father was one of 100,000 Jews who registered to leave the country and surrender their citizenship. A subsequent law ruled that all those who left forfeited all rights, including property rights. The Shlaim family lost all their property. His father crossed the border illegally on a mule, while Shlaim, his mother and sisters flew to Cyprus, reuniting in Israel.<ref name=rapaport />\n\nShlaim left Israel for England at the age of 16 to study at a Jewish school.<ref name=rapaport/><ref>{{cite news |last=Shlaim |first=Avi |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/07/gaza-israel-palestine |title=How Israel brought Gaza to the brink of humanitarian catastrophe |newspaper=The Guardian |date=7 January 2009 |accessdate=23 March 2014}}</ref> He returned to Israel in the mid-1960s to serve in the [[Israel Defense Forces]], then moved back to England in 1966 to read history at [[Jesus College, Cambridge]]. He obtained his BA degree in 1969.<ref name=\"Oxf\">[https://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/emeritus/avi-shlaim.html Profile: Avi Shlaim] ''University of Oxford</ref> He obtained an MSc (Econ.) in International Relations in 1970 from the [[London School of Economics]] and a PhD from the [[University of Reading]].<ref>[http://www.sant.ox.ac.uk/people/fellows.html Governing Body Fellows]</ref> He was a Lecturer and Reader in Politics in the University of Reading from 1970 to 1987.<ref name=Oxford>[http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/about/staff/staff.asp?action=show&person=62 Professor Avi Shlaim] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070527060151/http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/about/staff/staff.asp?action=show&person=62 |date=27 May 2007 }}, University of Oxford.</ref>\n\nHe married the great-granddaughter of [[David Lloyd George]], who was the British prime minister at the time of the [[Balfour Declaration of 1917|Balfour Declaration]]. He has lived in England ever since, and holds dual British and Israeli nationality.<ref>Avi Shlaim: \"And for the last forty years, I have lived in Britain, and I teach at Oxford\" in [http://www.democracynow.org/2007/5/9/it_takes_an_enormous_amount_of \"It Takes an Enormous Amount of Courage to Speak the Truth When No One Else is Out There\"&nbsp;\u2014 World-Renowned Holocaust, Israel Scholars Defend DePaul Professor Norman Finkelstein as He Fights for Tenur]. Shlaim's interview; democracynow.org, 9 May 2007, accessed 23 March 2014.</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Avi Shlaim 2.jpg|thumb|right|Shlaim addressing the Oxford Theology Society]]\nShlaim taught International Relations at Reading University, specialising in European issues. His academic interest in the history of Israel began in 1982, when Israeli government archives about the [[1948 Arab\u2013Israeli War]] were opened, an interest that deepened when he became a fellow of [[St Antony's College, Oxford]] in 1987.<ref name=rapaport /> He was Alastair Buchan Reader in International Relations at Oxford from 1987 to 1996 and Director of Graduate Studies in that subject in 1993\u20131995 and 1998\u20132001. He held a British Academy Research Readership in 1995\u201397 and a Research Professorship in 2003\u20132006.<ref name=\"Oxford\" />\n\nShlaim served as an outside examiner on the doctoral thesis of [[Ilan Papp\u00e9]], another notable New Historian. Shlaim's approach to the study of history is informed by his belief that, \"[t]he job of the historian is to judge\".<ref name=rapaport/>\n\nHe is a regular contributor to ''[[The Guardian]]'' newspaper, and signed an open letter to that paper in January 2009 condemning Israel's role in the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/16/gaza-israel-petitions |title=Growing outrage at the killings in Gaza |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=16 January 2009 |accessdate=23 March 2014}}. Letter to the editor signed by over 300 academics, writers, and others.</ref>\n\nWriting in the [[The Spectator|''Spectator'']], Shlaim dubbed Prime Minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] as a \"proponent of the doctrine of permanent conflict,\" describing his policies as an attempt to preclude a peaceful resolution to the conflict with Palestinians. Furthermore, he described Israeli foreign policy as one that supported stability of Arab regimes over nascent democratic movements during the [[Arab Spring]].<ref>Shlaim, Avi. \"An Israeli spring? Rejecting the prospect of greater democracy in the Arab world could put the Jewish state at risk.\" ''Spectator'' 25 Feb. 2012</ref>\n\nShlaim is a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|UK Labour Party]].<ref name=\"theguardian\">{{cite news |last= |first= |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/oct/15/censorship-battle-and-an-antisemitic-charge-cause-anger|title=Censorship battle and an antisemitic charge cause anger|location=|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=15 October 2017|accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref> In August 2015, he was a signatory to a letter criticising ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]''{{'}}s reporting of [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s association with alleged [[Antisemitism|antisemites]].<ref name=\"thejc\">{{cite news |last=Dysch|first=Marcus|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/142553/anti-israel-activists-attack-jc-challenging-jeremy-corbyn|title=Anti-Israel activists attack JC for challenging Jeremy Corbyn|location= |work=[[The Jewish Chronicle]]|date=18 August 2015|accessdate=7 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nThe Israeli historians [[Joseph Heller (historian)|Joseph Heller]] and [[Yehoshua Porath]] have claimed that Shlaim \"misleads his readers with arguments that Israel had missed the opportunity for peace while the Arabs are strictly peace seekers\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/right-of-reply-the-wonders-of-the-new-history-1.167424 |title=The wonders of the new history |author=Joseph Heller |author2=Yehoshua Porat |date=18 August 2005 |newspaper=Haaretz |accessdate=23 March 2014}}</ref><!-- Is it necessary to repeat previous ref with the Hebrew version of the same article?<ref>{{cite news |date=16 August 2005 |author=Joseph Heller |author2=Yehoshua Porat |url=http://www.haaretz.co.il/misc/1.1037061 |title=\u05e4\u05dc\u05d0\u05d9 \u05d4\u05d4\u05d9\u05e1\u05d8\u05d5\u05e8\u05d9\u05d4 \u05d4\u05d7\u05d3\u05e9\u05d4 |trans_title=Wonders of the New History |language=Hebrew}}</ref> --><ref>{{cite book |author=Joseph Heller |date=2000 |title=The Birth of Israel, 1945\u20131949: Ben-Gurion and His Critics |publisher= [[University Press of Florida]] |isbn=0813017327 |page=306}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2012 article in the [[academic journal]] ''Shofar'', Shai Afsai criticised Shlaim for repeating a story \"[[The bride is beautiful but she is married to another man]]\", for which Afsai could not trace an original source, in his 2001 book ''The Iron Wall: Israel and the Arab World''.<ref>\"'The bride is beautiful, but she is married to another man': Historical Fabrication and an Anti-Zionist Myth\", Shai Afsai, ''[[Shofar (journal)|Shofar]]'', Vol. 30, No. 3; 2012, pp. 35\u201361</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Yoav Gelber]], Shlaim's claim that there was a deliberate and pre-meditated anti-Palestinian \u201ccollusion\u201d between the [[Jewish Agency]] and King Abdullah, is unequivocally refuted by the documentary evidence on the development of contacts between Israel and Jordan before, during and after the war.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Yoav Gelber|title=The Israeli-Arab War of 1948 : The Collusion That Never Was|url=https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/isdf/text/gelber.html|website=jewishvirtuallibrary.org|date=July 2009|quote=\"Shlaim\u2019s conjecture of a deliberate and pre-meditated anti-Palestinian \u201ccollusion\u201d does not stand up to a critical examination. The documentary evidence on the development of contacts between Israel and Jordan before, during and after the war unequivocally refutes Shlaim\u2019s conclusions. If there was any collusion against the Palestinians in 1948, it was not concocted by Israel and Abdullah but rather, by Britain and Transjordan. The outcomes reveal that the British acquiescence to a Transjordanian takeover of Arab Palestine was merely a choice by default rather than a plot.\"}}</ref> [[Marc Lynch]] however wrote that \"the voluminous evidence in [Gelber's] book does not allow so conclusive a verdict\".<ref>{{cite journal | author = Marc Lynch | title = Israeli-Jordanian Dialogue, 1948-1953: Cooperation, Conspiracy, or Collusion? by Yoav Gelber | journal = [[Middle East Journal]] | volume = 59 | number = 2 | year = 2005 | pages = 329\u2013330 | jstor = 4330143}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\nIn 2006, Shlaim was elected [[Fellow of the British Academy]] (FBA), the United Kingdom's [[national academy]] for the humanities and social sciences.<ref name=Oxford/><ref name=\"FBA\">{{cite web|title=Professor Avi Shlaim|url=https://www.britac.ac.uk/user/2165|website=The British Academy|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 September 2017, Shlaim was awarded the [[British Academy Medal]] \"for lifetime achievement\".<ref>{{cite web|title=From Wikipedia to Roman coins: British Academy recognises excellence in the humanities and social sciences|url=https://www.britac.ac.uk/news/wikipedia-roman-coins-british-academy-recognises-excellence-humanities-and-social-sciences|website=The British Academy|accessdate=5 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Published works==\n* ''Collusion across the Jordan: King Abdullah, the Zionist Movement and the Partition of Palestine'' (winner of the 1988 Political Studies Association's W. J. M. Mackenzie Prize)\n*''The Politics of Partition'' (1990 and 1998)\n*''War and Peace in the Middle East: A Concise History'' (1995)\n*''The Cold War and the Middle East'' (co-editor, 1997)\n*''The Iron Wall: Israel and the Arab World'' (New York: [[W.W. Norton]], 2001)\n*''Lion of Jordan: The Life of King Hussein in War and Peace'' (London: [[Allen Lane]], 2007)\n*''Israel and Palestine: Reappraisals, Revisions, Refutations'' (London: [[Verso Books]], 2009)\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*[[Benny Morris]]\n*[[Ilan Pappe]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061013030137/http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/about/staff/staff.asp?action=show&person=62&special= Oxford home page]\n* [http://www.thenation.com/doc/20040628/attapatu Interview].  ''[[The Nation]]'', 28 June 2004.\n* [http://www.democracynow.org/2009/1/14/leading_israeli_scholar_avi_shlaim_israel 2009 Interview on Israeli-Palestinian conflict inc. video, audio and text transcript.]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110815155354/http://www.frontlineclub.com/events/2009/11/avi-shlaim-in-conversation-with-shlomo-sand.html Video of discussion] between Avi Shlaim and [[Shlomo Sand]]. Chaired by [[Jacqueline Rose]] at the [[Frontline Club]], London, 12 November 2009\n* [http://users.ox.ac.uk/~ssfc0005/The%20Balfour%20Declaration%20and%20its%20consequences.html Shlaim, Avi.\"The Balfour Declaration And its Consequences\"]  in Louis, Wm. Roger, ed., ''Yet More Adventures with Britannia: Personalities, Politics and Culture in Britain'', London,  I.B. Tauris, 2005, pp.&nbsp;251\u2013270.\n{{New Historians}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shlaim, Avi}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Reading]]\n[[Category:British historians]]\n[[Category:British people of Iraqi-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the British Academy]]\n[[Category:Fellows of St Antony's College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Historians of the Middle East]]\n[[Category:International relations scholars]]\n[[Category:Iraqi emigrants to Israel]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Jews]]\n[[Category:Israeli historians]]\n[[Category:Jewish historians]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) people]]\n[[Category:New Historians]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the British Academy Medal]]\n[[Category:Writers from Baghdad]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Jesus College, Cambridge]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Reordered cats", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avi_Shlaim"}
{"title_page": "John Hamilton, 1st Marquess of Hamilton", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox peer\n| name = John Hamilton\n| title = The 1st Marquess of Hamilton\n| tenure = 1599\u20131604\n| offices = [[Commendator]] of [[Inchaffray Abbey]]<br>[[Abbot of Arbroath|Commendator of Arbroath]]\n| successor = James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton\n| birth_date = 1540\n| death_date = {{death date|1604|4|26|df=y}}\n| nationality = Scottish\n| spouse = Margaret Lyon, Countess of Cassilis\n| issue = Edward Hamilton<br>[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton]]<br>Margaret Maxwell, Lady Maxwell<br>Margaret Colquhoun<br>Sir John Hamilton\n| parents = [[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran]]<br>Margaret Douglas\n}}\n'''John Hamilton, 1st Marquess of Hamilton''' (1540\u20131604), was a Scottish nobleman. He was the founder of the long line of the [[Duke of Hamilton|marquesses and dukes of Hamilton]].\n\n==Birth and origins==\nJohn was born about 1535 in Scotland. He was the third son of [[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran|James Hamilton]] and his wife Margaret Douglas. His father was the 2nd Earl of Arran and [[Duke of Ch\u00e2tellerault]] in France. John's mother was a daughter of [[James Douglas, 3rd Earl of Morton]]. Both parents were Scottish. They had married in September 1532.{{sfn|Cokayne|1910|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo01coka/page/220/ 221, line 31]|ps=: \"He m., shortly before 23 Sep. 1532, Margaret 1st da. of James (DOUGLAS), EARL OF MORTON [S.], by Catherine illeg. da. of James IV.\"}}\n\nHe appears below among his brothers as the second son:\n#[[James Hamilton, 3rd Earl of Arran|James]] (1537\u20131609){{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/368/ 368, line 34]|ps=: \"... who was born in 1537 or in 1538 as he was under twenty-three on 15 April 1560 when Randolph wrote to Cecil recommending his good qualities.\"}}, who became insane in 1562{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/369/ 369, line 4]|ps=: \"... Unhappily, in April 1562, he showed signs of disordered intellect, and was soon after pronounced insane.\"}} but nevertheless succeeded nominally his father as the 3rd Earl of Arran in 1575;{{sfn|Henderson|1890a|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/176/ 176, left column]|ps=: \"On the death of his father in 1575, he came into nominal possession of his estates, which were, however, administrated by his second brother, John ...\"}}\n#'''John''' (1540\u20131604), the subject of this article;\n#Gavin, who died in his youth;{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/369/ 369, line 11]|ps=: \"Gavin, styled second son ... appears to have died before August 1547 in his youth.\"}}\n#David (died 1611);<ref>Chatellherault's will, NAS ECC8/8/4</ref>{{sfn|Burke|1869|p=[https://archive.org/details/genealogicalhera00inburk/page/2/ 2, right column, line 37]|ps=: \"d. unm. 1611\"}} and\n#[[Claud Hamilton, 1st Lord Paisley]] (1546\u20131621), from whom descend the [[Duke of Abercorn|earls, marquesses, and dukes of Abercorn]].{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n21/ 443, line 9]|ps=: \"Claud, ancestor of the marquess of Abercorn ...\"}}\n\nHis sisters were:\n#Barbara, who in 1553 married [[James Fleming, 4th Lord Fleming]];{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, line 32]|ps=: \"Barbara, who married James, fourth lord Fleming, high chamberlain of Scotland.\"}}{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/370/ 370, line 4]|ps=: \"Barbara, the eldest daughter, was first contracted to Alexander, Lord Gordon ... but it is not certain that the marriage took place ... She mas married (contract dated 22 December 1553) to James, Lord Fleming, chamberlain of Scotland.\"}}\n#Jean, who married [[Hugh Montgomerie, 3rd Earl of Eglinton]] in 1555;{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, right column, line 37]|ps=: \"Jane, who married Hugh Montgomery, third earl of Eglintoun.\"}}{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/370/ 370, line 15]|ps=: \"Jean or Jane ... was married (contract dated 13 February 1553-4) to the earl of Eglinton.\"}}\n#[[Anne Hamilton, Countess of Huntly|Anne]] (c. 1535 \u2013 before April 1574), who married [[George Gordon, 5th Earl of Huntly]];{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, right column, line 36]|ps=: \"Anne who married George, fifth Earl of Huntly.\"}} and\n#Margaret, who married Sir Alexander, eldest son of [[George Gordon, 4th Earl of Huntly]].{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, right column, line 34]|ps=: \"Margaret, who married Alexander, lord Gordon, eldest son of George, fourth earl of Huntly;\"}}\n\n<div style=\"float: right; margin: 0 0 0 1em\">\n{{chart top|width=auto|collapsed=no|Family tree}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 31em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=John Hamilton with wife, parents, and other selected relatives.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; padding-bottom: 1em; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart| |JmsR1|y|JntBn|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JmsR1=[[James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Arran|James<br>'''1st Earl''']]<br>{{midsize|c. 1475 \u2013<br>1529}}|boxstyle_JmsR1=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lightcyan;\n |JntBn='''Janet<br>Bethune'''<br>{{midsize|c. 1490 \u2013<br>c. 1522}}}}\n{{chart| | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | | |JmsR2|y| Mgt |boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JmsR2=[[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran|James<br>'''2nd Earl''']]<br>{{midsize|c. 1516 \u2013<br>1575}}|boxstyle_JmsR2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lightcyan;\n |Mgt='''Margaret<br>Douglas'''<br>{{midsize|b. c. 1510}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|v|^|-|-|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|JmsR3| |JhnH1|y|MgtLy| |CldLP|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JmsR3=[[James Hamilton, 3rd Earl of Arran|James<br>'''3rd Earl''']]<br>{{midsize|1537\u20131609}}|boxstyle_JmsR3=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lightcyan;\n |JhnH1=John<br>'''1st Marquess'''<br>{{midsize|1540\u20131604}};|boxstyle_JhnH1=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |MgtLy='''Margaret<br>Lyon'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1625}}\n |CldLP=[[Claud Hamilton, 1st Lord Paisley|Claud<br>'''1st Ld<br>Paisley''']]<br>{{midsize|1546\u20131621}}}}\n{{chart| | | |,|-|-|-|'| | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | |JmsH2|y|AnCun| | | |JmsA1|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JmsH2=[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton|James<br>'''2nd Marquess''']]<br>{{midsize|1589\u20131625}}|boxstyle_JmsH2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |AnCun='''Anne<br>Cuninghame'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1632}}\n |JmsA1=[[James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Abercorn|James<br>'''1st Earl<br>Abercorn''']]<br>{{midsize|1575\u20131618}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|^|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|JsDH1|y|MgtFd| |WmDH2|y|ElzMx|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JsDH1=[[James Hamilton, 1st Duke of Hamilton|James<br>'''1st Duke''']]<br>{{midsize|1606\u20131649}}|boxstyle_JsDH1=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |MgtFd=Margaret<br>'''Feilding'''<br>{{midsize|c. 1590 \u2013<br>1638}}\n |WmDH2=[[William Hamilton, 2nd Duke of Hamilton|William<br>'''2nd Duke''']]<br>{{midsize|1616\u20131651}}|boxstyle_WmDH2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ElzMx='''Elizabeth<br>Maxwell'''<br>{{midsize|c. 1620 \u2013<br>bef. 1659}}}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both;}}\n{{chart|Leg|\n |Leg='''Legend'''|boxstyle_Leg=border: 0 solid white;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart|SbjBx|SbjTx| |Bk1Bx|Bk1Tx| |Bk2Bx|Bk2Tx\n |SbjBx=XXX|boxstyle_SbjBx=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; color: white;\n |SbjTx=John<br>Hamilton|boxstyle_SbjTx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;\n |Bk1Bx=XXX|boxstyle_Bk1Bx=background: lavender; border-radius: 0.5em; border-width: 1px; color: lavender;\n |Bk1Tx=[[Duke of Hamilton|Marquesses &<br>dukes of Hamilton]]|boxstyle_Bk1Tx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;\n |Bk2Bx=XXX|boxstyle_Bk2Bx=background: lightcyan; border-radius: 0.5em; border-width: 1px; color: lightcyan;\n |Bk2Tx=[[Duke of Hamilton#Lords Hamilton and Earls of Arran|Earls of<br>Arran]]|boxstyle_Bk2Tx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 31em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=This family tree is partly derived from the Abercorn pedigree pictured in Cokayne.{{sfn|Cokayne|1910|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo01coka/page/4/ 4]|ps=: \"Tabular pedigree of the Earls of Abercorn\"}} Also see the lists of siblings and children in the text.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart_bottom}}\n</div>\n\n==Early life==\nOn 28 November 1547, John, still a boy, was appointed [[Commendator]] of [[Inchaffray Abbey]],{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/370/ 370, line 30]|ps=: \"At a comparably early age he was provided to the abbacy of Inchaffray, the Consistorial Act in his favour being dated 28 November 1547, when he is said to be aged twelve, but his age is variously stated ...\"}} a position he held until 1551, when he was made [[Abbot of Arbroath|Commendator of Arbroath]] instead.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 4]|ps=: \"... and was on 4 September of that year [1551] provided to the rich and extensive abbacy of Arbroath.\"}} He had the benefit of Arbroath until 1579, although his right was disputed by [[George Douglas (bishop)|George Douglas]] (a natural son of the [[Archibald Douglas, 6th Earl of Angus|Earl of Angus]] who would later become [[Bishop of Moray]]).{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 8]|ps=: \"... though his possession was much disturbed by George Douglas, a natural son of the sixth Earl of Angus who claimed the abbacy as a postulate.\"}}\n\nHis family supported [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], even after her imprisonment at [[Lochleven Castle]], her abdication in favour of her one-year-old son on 24 July 1567, her defeat at [[Battle of Langside|Langside]] in 1568 and her flight to England shortly afterwards. In 1570 [[James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray|Moray]], who was regent during part of the minority of [[King James VI and I|King VI]], was assassinated by [[James Hamilton (assassin)|John Hamilton of Bothwellhaugh]], a supporter of Queen Mary, at [[Linlithgow]].{{sfn|Fraser|1970|p=[https://archive.org/details/maryqueenofscots0000anto/page/498/ 498]|ps=: \"... on 11th January, 1570, the regent Moray fell dead, struck down by the bullets of an assassin in the main street at Lithlingow;\"}} John's father (the Duke of Ch\u00e2tellerault and 2nd Earl of Arran) had been imprisoned by Murray at the time and John himself might have had a hand in the murder.{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/193/ 193, left column, line 11]|ps=: \"... and it was doubtless to revenge this that he [John] and his family furthered the plot for the assassination of the regent Moray ...\"}} His successor, Regent [[Matthew Stewart, 4th Earl of Lennox|Lennox]], died in 1571 from a shot in his back during a skirmish at Stirling with the Queen's party.{{sfn|Marshall|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613741/page/865/ 865, left column, line 36]|ps= \"Mathew Stewart, 13th earl of Lennox, the Hamilton's hereditary enemy, was chosen to be the next regent but the following year he was shot in the back during a skirmish at Stirling castle and died&nbsp;...\"}} Finally, on 23 February 1573, his father gave up his support for Mary and recognised Mary's infant son [[James VI of Scotland|James]] as King of Scotland.{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, right column, line 15]|ps=: \"... till 23 Feb. 1573, when action in union with the Earl of Huntly, heconsented to acknowledge the king's authority and lay down his sword.}}\n\n==Head of the family==\nHis father died at Hamilton on 22 January 1575.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/368/ 368, line 28]|ps=: \"... died at Hamilton on 22 January 1574-75.\"}} His older brother James succeeded as the 3rd Earl of Arran, but because of his insanity, he was placed under John's care{{sfn|Henderson|1890a|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/176/ 176, left column]|ps=: \"On the death of his father in 1575, he came into nominal possession of his estates, which were, however, administrated by his second brother, John ...\"}} making John the de facto Earl and head of the family.{{sfn|Marshall|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613741/page/865/ 865, left column column]|ps=: \"... Lord John became in effect the head of the house of Hamilton and heir to the Scottish throne.\"}}\n\n==Marriage and children==\nOn 30 December 1577 John contracted to marry [[Margaret Lyon]], Countess of Cassilis, the widow of [[Gilbert Kennedy, 4th Earl of Cassilis]], and daughter of [[John Lyon, 7th Lord Glamis]],{{sfn|Groome|1892|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio54stepgoog/page/n429/ 419]|ps=: \"... in 1566 he [Gilbert Kennedy] married Margaret Lyon, only daughter of John, seventh lord Glamis ...\"}} promising to marry her before 10 February 1578.{{sfn|Fraser|1887|p=54|ps=: \"113:Contract of marriage between Lord John Hamilton, Commendator of Arbroath, brother-german and apparent heir of James Earl of Arran, on one part and Dame Margaret Lyon, Countess of Cassillis, and others, on the other part. The parties agree to marry each other before the&nbsp;...\"}}{{sfn|Groome|1892|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio54stepgoog/page/n430/ 420, left column, line 49]|ps=: \"His widow afterwards married John, first marquis of Hamilton.\"}} His wife was an staunch Protestant. She had converted her first husband who had been a Catholic before their marriage.{{sfn|Groome|1892|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio54stepgoog/page/n429/ 419, right column, line 30]|ps=: \"... and by her persuasion he became a protestant and caused to reform his churches in Carrick&nbsp;...\"}}\n\nThey had three children:\n*Edward, who died in infancy;{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/195/ 195, left column, line 5]|ps=: \"... an elder son Edward who died young.\"}}\n*[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton|James]] (1589\u20131625), who succeeded him as the 2nd Marquess of Hamilton;{{sfn|Marshall|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613741/page/865/ 865, right column]|ps=: \"His eldest son, James Hamilton, was born in1589.\"}} and\n*Margaret, who married [[John Maxwell, 9th Lord Maxwell]].{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/195/ 195, left column, line 6]|ps=: \"... and a daughter, Lady Margaret, married to John, eighth lord Maxwell.\"}}\n\nHamilton also had two illegitimate children:\n*Margaret Hamilton, who married Sir Humphrey Colquhoun of Luss;{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/195/ 195, left column, line 10]|ps=: \"... and a natural daughter, Jean, who married Sir Umfra Colquhoun of Luss.\"}} and\n*Sir John Hamilton of Letterick, from whom descended the [[Lord Bargany|Lords Bargany]].{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/195/ 195, left column, line 8]|ps=: \"He had also a natural son, Sir John Hamilton of Lettrick, father of the first lord Bargeny&nbsp;...\"}}\n\n==Forfeiture and English Exile==\nIn 1579 [[James Douglas, 4th Earl of Morton]] accused John and his younger brother Claud to have been implicated in the murders of the regents Moray and Lennox and obtained that John and Claud were included in the Scottish Act of forfeiture of 1579. In consequence John lost his income from the abbey of Arbroath{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 17]|ps=: \"... in the forfeiture of the Hamilton estates in 1579, when his own possessions of Arbroath were affected ...\"}} and had to leave the country. He fled first to England, then to France. He returned to England and there stayed with his brother Claud in the North. While in England he reconciled himself with [[Archibald Douglas, 8th Earl of Angus]]{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 28]|ps=: \"The Hamiltons became reconciled to the Earl of Angus, then also in exile&nbsp;...\"}} who was also in exile there due to his association with the [[Raid of Ruthven]]. King James had by now come under the influence of [[James Stewart, Earl of Arran|James Stewart of Bothwellmuir]], to whom the King had granted Hamilton's brother's earldom of Arran.{{sfn|Henderson|1898|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati54stepuoft/page/308/ 308, right column, line 9]|ps=: \"On 22 April 1581 he obtained grant of the earldom of Arran in Bute, the lands and barony of Hamilton in Lanark ...\"}}\n\n==Back in Scotland==\nJohn, with Angus, the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]], and the [[Thomas Lyon (of Auldbar)|Master of Glamis]] and with the connivance of [[Elizabeth I of England]], raised an army and entered Scotland, reaching [[Stirling]] in October 1585. James Stewart of Bothwellmuir fled and King James capitulated on 4 November, receiving the banished lords into his presence.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 33]|ps=: \"... the banished lords were on 4 November 1585 admitted to the King's presence, who ... welcomed Lord John with special cordiality&nbsp;...\"}}\n\nAt a parliament convened at [[Linlithgow]] on 1 December 1585, King James rescinded Hamilton's forfeiture and restored him and the other lords to their previously held lands. Further Hamilton was raised to the [[Privy Council of Scotland|Privy Council]] and made captain of [[Dumbarton Castle]].<ref>[http://www.rps.ac.uk/ Acts of Parliament 1 December 1585]</ref> In April 1590 he visited [[Dalkeith Palace]] and when the gardener tried to stop him taking a horse, Hamilton's servant shot him.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 274.</ref>\n\nIn 1588 John founded a grammar school that became known as [[Hamilton Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hamilton.s-lanark.sch.uk/head-teacher-appointment/ |title=Head Teacher Appointment |last=Stewart |first=C |date=9 March 2016 |website=Hamilton Grammar School |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630105741/http://www.hamilton.s-lanark.sch.uk/head-teacher-appointment/ |archive-date=30 June 2016}}</ref> In 1972 this school became the [[Hamilton Grammar School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/former-hamilton-academy-pupils-hold-5652789 |title=Former Hamilton Academy pupils hold 60th anniversary reunion}}</ref>\n\n==Marquess==\nHamilton continued to rise in the King's favour, and on 15 April 1599, following the baptism of Princess Margaret at [[Holyroodhouse]], he was created ''Marquess of Hamilton, Earl of Arran and Lord Aven''.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/372/ 372, line 24]|ps=: \"... on 17 April, he and the Earl of Huntly were, with great ceremony, at his Majesty's great chamber at Holyrood installed in their proper places, his title being proclaimed MARQUESS OF HAMILTON, EARL OF ARRAN, and Lord EVAN.\"}} In August 1602 he hosted the French ambassador, the [[Charles Cauchon de Maupas|Baron de Tour]] at Hamilton Palace, who hunted with the king and the [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|Duke of Lennox]] and played a card game called \"mawe\".<ref>J. D. Mackie, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1040.</ref>\n\n==Death and succession==\nThe Marquess died before his elder brother in April 1604.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/372/ 372, line 29]|ps=: \"... dying 6 April 1604, his last act being to recommend his son to the King's favour.\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1892|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerage04cokahrish/page/n138/ 141, line 7]|ps=: \"He died (bfore his elder br. James, Earl of Arran and Lord Hamilton [S.] above mentioned) 12 April 1604, aged about 70.\"}} He was immediately succeeded by his son James as the 2nd Marquess of Hamilton. James also succeeded as the 4th Earl of Arran in 1609 upon James's death.{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n21/ 443, line 18]|ps=: \"JAMES, 2nd Marquess, K.G., who, on the death of his uncle, James, 1609, became also 4th earl of Arran ...\"}}\n\n{| {{Table|hide}}\n!colspan=3|Timeline\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Age!!align=\"left\"|Date!!align=\"left\"|Event\n|-\n|0||1540||Born, probably in [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire|Hamilton]], Lanarkshire, Scotland.\n|-\n|7||1547, 28 Nov||Made [[Commendator]] of [[Inchaffray Abbey]] while still a boy.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage370 370, line 30]\"/>\n|-\n|11||1551, 4 Sep||Made [[Commendator of Arbroath]] instead.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage371 371, line 4]\"/>\n|-\n|18||1568, 13 May||Mary loses the [[Battle of Langside]] and flees to England.\n|-\n|30||1570, 23 Jan||Regent [[James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray|Moray]] assassinated; John and his family might have been involved.\n|-\n|31||1571, 4 Sep||Regent [[Matthew Stewart, 4th Earl of Lennox|Lennox]] killed.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEMarshall2004[httpsarchiveorgdetailsisbn_0198613741page865 865, left column, line 36]\"/>\n|-\n|35||1575, 22 Jan||His father died in Hamilton<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage368 368, line 28]\"/> and his brother succeeded as 3rd Earl of Arran, but as he was insane, John became earl de facto.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEMarshall2004[httpsarchiveorgdetailsisbn_0198613741page865 865, left column column]\"/>\n|-\n|38||1578, Jan or Feb||Marries Margaret Lyon.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEFraser188754\"/>\n|-\n|39||1579||John and Claud included in the Act of forfeiture.\n|-\n|42||1582, Aug||[[Raid of Ruthven]]\n|-\n|45||1585, 4 Nov||The King welcomes him back at [[Stirling]].\n|-\n|47||1587, 8 Feb||Mary, Queen of Scots executed at [[Fotheringhay Castle]], England.\n|-\n|59||1599, 15 Apr||Created Marquess of Hamilton.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage372 372, line 24]\"/>\n|-\n|64||1604, 6 Apr||Died.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage372 372, line 29]\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Burke |first=Bernard |author-link=Bernard Burke |date=1869 |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire |edition=31st |publisher=Harrison |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/genealogicalhera00inburk/}}\n*{{citation|last=Cokayne |first=George Edward |author-link=George Edward Cokayne |editor-last=Gibbs |editor-first=Vicary |editor-link=Vicary Gibbs (St Albans MP) |date=1910 |title=The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant |edition=2nd |volume=1 AB-ADAM to BASING |publisher=St Catherine Press |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo01coka/}} (for Arran)\n*{{citation|last=Cokayne |first=George Edward |author-link=George Edward Cokayne |date=1892 |title=The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant |edition=1st |volume=4 |publisher=George Bell and Sons |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/completepeerage04cokahrish/}} \u2013 G to K (for Hamilton)\n*{{citation|last=Debrett |first=John |author-link=John Debrett |date=1828 |title=Peerage of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |edition=17th |volume=2 |publisher=F. C. and J. Rivington |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/}} - Scotland and Ireland\n*{{citation|last=Dunlop |first=Robert |editor-last=Lee |editor-first=Sidney |editor-link=Sidney Lee |date=1890 |title=HAMILTON, JAMES, second EARL OF ARRAN and DUKE OF CH\u00c2TELHERAULT (d. 1575) |encyclopedia=Dictionary of National Biography |volume=24 |publisher=MacMillan and Co. |publication-place=New York |pages=167\u2013170 |url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/167/}} <!-- The Internet address is numbered 25 but the volume is 24. -->\n*{{citation|last=Fraser |first=Antonia |date=1970 |title=Mary Queen of Scots |publisher=Panther Books |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/maryqueenofscots0000anto/ |url-access=registration}}\n*{{citation|last=Fraser |first=William |date=1887 |title=Historical Manuscript Commission 11th Report Appendix Part 6 Manuscripts of the Duke of Hamilton K.T. |publisher=Eyre & Spottiswoode |publication-place=London |url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=rWw_AQAAMAAJ}}\n*{{citation|last=Groome |first=Francis Hindes |author-link=Francis Hindes Groome |editor-last=Lee |editor-first=Sidney |editor-link=Sidney Lee |date=1892 |title=KENNEDY, GILBERT, fourth EARL of CASSILLIS |encyclopedia=Dictionary of National Biography |volume=30 |publisher=MacMillan & Co |publication-place=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio54stepgoog/page/n429/ 419\u2013420] |url=https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio54stepgoog/}} (for his wife's first husband)\n*{{citation|last=Henderson |first=Thomas Finlayson |author-link=Thomas Finlayson Henderson |editor-last=Lee |editor-first=Sidney |editor-link=Sidney Lee |date=1890a |title=HAMILTON, JAMES, third EARL OF ARRAN (1530\u20131609) |encyclopedia=Dictionary of National Biography |volume=24 |publisher=MacMillan and Co. |publication-place=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/173/ 173\u2013176] |url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/}} <!-- The Internet address is numbered 25 but the volume is 24. -->\n*{{citation|last=Henderson |first=Thomas Finlayson |author-link=Thomas Finlayson Henderson |editor-last=Lee |editor-first=Sidney |editor-link=Sidney Lee |date=1890b |title=HAMILTON, JOHN, first MARQUIS OF HAMILTON (1532\u20131604) |encyclopedia=Dictionary of National Biography |volume=24 |publisher=MacMillan and Co. |publication-place=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/192/ 192\u2013195] |url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/}} <!-- The Internet address is numbered 25 but the volume is 24. -->\n*{{citation|last=Henderson |first=Thomas Finlayson |author-link=Thomas Finlayson Henderson|editor-last=Lee |editor-first=Sidney |editor-link=Sidney Lee |date=1898 |title=STEWART, JAMES of Bothwellmuir |encyclopedia=Dictionary of National Biography |volume=54 Stanhope\u2013Stovin |publisher=Smith Elder & Co |publication-place=London |pages=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati54stepuoft/page/308/ 308\u2013311] |url=https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati54stepuoft/}}\n*{{citation|last=Marshall |first=Rosalind K. |editor-last=Matthew |editor-first=Colin |editor-link=Colin Matthew |editor2-last=Harrison |editor2-first=Brian |editor2-link=Brian Harrison (historian) |date=2004 |title=Hamilton, John, first marquess of Hamilton (1539/40\u20131604) |encyclopedia=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |volume=24 |publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |publication-place=New York |pages=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613741/page/864/ 864\u2013867] |isbn=978-0198614111 |url=https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613741/ |url-access=registration}}\n*{{citation|last=Paul |first=Sir James Balfour |author-link=James Balfour Paul |date=1907 |title=The Scots Peerage, Founded on Wood's Edition of Sir Robert Douglas's Peerage of Scotland |volume=4 |publisher=David Douglas |publication-place=Edinburgh |url=https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/}} \u2013 Fife to Hyndford (for Hamilton)\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.thepeerage.com/p10939.htm#i109390 Genealogy of John Hamilton, 1st Marquess of Hamilton on The Peerage website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-reg|sct}}\n{{succession box|title=[[Duke of Hamilton|Marquess of Hamilton]] |before=New Creation |after=[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton|James Hamilton]] |years=1599&ndash;1604}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hamilton, John}}\n[[Category:1530s births]]\n[[Category:1604 deaths]]\n[[Category:Marquesses of Hamilton|John]]\n[[Category:House of Hamilton|John]]\n[[Category:16th-century Scottish peers]]\n[[Category:17th-century Scottish peers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n{{Infobox peer\n| name = John Hamilton\n| title = The 1st Marquess of Hamilton\n| tenure = 1599\u20131604\n| offices = [[Commendator]] of [[Inchaffray Abbey]]<br>[[Abbot of Arbroath|Commendator of Arbroath]]\n| successor = James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton\n| birth_date = 1540\n| death_date = {{death date|1604|4|26|df=y}}\n| nationality = Scottish\n| spouse = Margaret Lyon, Countess of Cassilis\n| issue = Edward Hamilton<br>[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton]]<br>Margaret Maxwell, Lady Maxwell<br>Margaret Colquhoun<br>Sir John Hamilton\n| parents = [[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran]]<br>Margaret Douglas\n}}\n'''John Hamilton, 1st Marquess of Hamilton''' (1540\u20131604), was a Scottish nobleman. He was the founder of the long line of the [[Duke of Hamilton|marquesses and dukes of Hamilton]].\n\n==Birth and origins==\nJohn was born about 1535 in Scotland. He was the third son of [[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran|James Hamilton]] and his wife Margaret Douglas. His father was the 2nd Earl of Arran and [[Duke of Ch\u00e2tellerault]] in France. John's mother was a daughter of [[James Douglas, 3rd Earl of Morton]]. Both parents were Scottish. They had married in September 1532.{{sfn|Cokayne|1910|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo01coka/page/220/ 221, line 31]|ps=: \"He m., shortly before 23 Sep. 1532, Margaret 1st da. of James (DOUGLAS), EARL OF MORTON [S.], by Catherine illeg. da. of James IV.\"}}\n\nHe appears below among his brothers as the second son:\n#[[James Hamilton, 3rd Earl of Arran|James]] (1537\u20131609){{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/368/ 368, line 34]|ps=: \"... who was born in 1537 or in 1538 as he was under twenty-three on 15 April 1560 when Randolph wrote to Cecil recommending his good qualities.\"}}, who became insane in 1562{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/369/ 369, line 4]|ps=: \"... Unhappily, in April 1562, he showed signs of disordered intellect, and was soon after pronounced insane.\"}} but nevertheless succeeded nominally his father as the 3rd Earl of Arran in 1575;{{sfn|Henderson|1890a|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/176/ 176, left column]|ps=: \"On the death of his father in 1575, he came into nominal possession of his estates, which were, however, administrated by his second brother, John ...\"}}\n#'''John''' (1540\u20131604), the subject of this article;\n#Gavin, who died in his youth;{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/369/ 369, line 11]|ps=: \"Gavin, styled second son ... appears to have died before August 1547 in his youth.\"}}\n#David (died 1611);<ref>Chatellherault's will, NAS ECC8/8/4</ref>{{sfn|Burke|1869|p=[https://archive.org/details/genealogicalhera00inburk/page/2/ 2, right column, line 37]|ps=: \"d. unm. 1611\"}} and\n#[[Claud Hamilton, 1st Lord Paisley]] (1546\u20131621), from whom descend the [[Duke of Abercorn|earls, marquesses, and dukes of Abercorn]].{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n21/ 443, line 9]|ps=: \"Claud, ancestor of the marquess of Abercorn ...\"}}\n\nHis sisters were:\n#Barbara, who in 1553 married [[James Fleming, 4th Lord Fleming]];{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, line 32]|ps=: \"Barbara, who married James, fourth lord Fleming, high chamberlain of Scotland.\"}}{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/370/ 370, line 4]|ps=: \"Barbara, the eldest daughter, was first contracted to Alexander, Lord Gordon ... but it is not certain that the marriage took place ... She mas married (contract dated 22 December 1553) to James, Lord Fleming, chamberlain of Scotland.\"}}\n#Jean, who married [[Hugh Montgomerie, 3rd Earl of Eglinton]] in 1555;{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, right column, line 37]|ps=: \"Jane, who married Hugh Montgomery, third earl of Eglintoun.\"}}{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/370/ 370, line 15]|ps=: \"Jean or Jane ... was married (contract dated 13 February 1553-4) to the earl of Eglinton.\"}}\n#[[Anne Hamilton, Countess of Huntly|Anne]] (c. 1535 \u2013 before April 1574), who married [[George Gordon, 5th Earl of Huntly]];{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, right column, line 36]|ps=: \"Anne who married George, fifth Earl of Huntly.\"}} and\n#Margaret, who married Sir Alexander, eldest son of [[George Gordon, 4th Earl of Huntly]].{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, right column, line 34]|ps=: \"Margaret, who married Alexander, lord Gordon, eldest son of George, fourth earl of Huntly;\"}}\n\n<div style=\"float: right; margin: 0 0 0 1em\">\n{{chart top|width=auto|collapsed=no|Family tree}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 31em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=John Hamilton with wife, parents, and other selected relatives.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; padding-bottom: 1em; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart| |JmsR1|y|JntBn|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JmsR1=[[James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Arran|James<br>'''1st Earl''']]<br>{{midsize|c. 1475 \u2013<br>1529}}|boxstyle_JmsR1=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lightcyan;\n |JntBn='''Janet<br>Bethune'''<br>{{midsize|c. 1490 \u2013<br>c. 1522}}}}\n{{chart| | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | | |JmsR2|y| Mgt |boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JmsR2=[[James Hamilton, 2nd Earl of Arran|James<br>'''2nd Earl''']]<br>{{midsize|c. 1516 \u2013<br>1575}}|boxstyle_JmsR2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lightcyan;\n |Mgt='''Margaret<br>Douglas'''<br>{{midsize|b. c. 1510}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|v|^|-|-|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|JmsR3| |JhnH1|y|MgtLy| |CldLP|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JmsR3=[[James Hamilton, 3rd Earl of Arran|James<br>'''3rd Earl''']]<br>{{midsize|1537\u20131609}}|boxstyle_JmsR3=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lightcyan;\n |JhnH1=John<br>'''1st Marquess'''<br>{{midsize|1540\u20131604}};|boxstyle_JhnH1=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |MgtLy='''Margaret<br>Lyon'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1625}}\n |CldLP=[[Claud Hamilton, 1st Lord Paisley|Claud<br>'''1st Ld<br>Paisley''']]<br>{{midsize|1546\u20131621}}}}\n{{chart| | | |,|-|-|-|'| | | | |!}}\n{{chart| | |JmsH2|y|AnCun| | | |JmsA1|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JmsH2=[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton|James<br>'''2nd Marquess''']]<br>{{midsize|1589\u20131625}}|boxstyle_JmsH2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |AnCun='''Anne<br>Cuninghame'''<br>{{midsize|d. 1632}}\n |JmsA1=[[James Hamilton, 1st Earl of Abercorn|James<br>'''1st Earl<br>Abercorn''']]<br>{{midsize|1575\u20131618}}}}\n{{chart| |,|-|-|-|^|-|-|-|.}}\n{{chart|JsDH1|y|MgtFd| |WmDH2|y|ElzMx|boxstyle=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em;\n |JsDH1=[[James Hamilton, 1st Duke of Hamilton|James<br>'''1st Duke''']]<br>{{midsize|1606\u20131649}}|boxstyle_JsDH1=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |MgtFd=Margaret<br>'''Feilding'''<br>{{midsize|c. 1590 \u2013<br>1638}}\n |WmDH2=[[William Hamilton, 2nd Duke of Hamilton|William<br>'''2nd Duke''']]<br>{{midsize|1616\u20131651}}|boxstyle_WmDH2=border-width: 1px; border-radius: 0.5em; background: lavender;\n |ElzMx='''Elizabeth<br>Maxwell'''<br>{{midsize|c. 1620 \u2013<br>bef. 1659}}}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both;}}\n{{chart|Leg|\n |Leg='''Legend'''|boxstyle_Leg=border: 0 solid white;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 70%;}}\n{{chart|SbjBx|SbjTx| |Bk1Bx|Bk1Tx| |Bk2Bx|Bk2Tx\n |SbjBx=XXX|boxstyle_SbjBx=border: 2px solid red; border-radius: 0.5em; color: white;\n |SbjTx=John<br>Hamilton|boxstyle_SbjTx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;\n |Bk1Bx=XXX|boxstyle_Bk1Bx=background: lavender; border-radius: 0.5em; border-width: 1px; color: lavender;\n |Bk1Tx=[[Duke of Hamilton|Marquesses &<br>dukes of Hamilton]]|boxstyle_Bk1Tx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;\n |Bk2Bx=XXX|boxstyle_Bk2Bx=background: lightcyan; border-radius: 0.5em; border-width: 1px; color: lightcyan;\n |Bk2Tx=[[Duke of Hamilton#Lords Hamilton and Earls of Arran|Earls of<br>Arran]]|boxstyle_Bk2Tx=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart/start|style=clear: both; font-size: 80%; width: 31em;}}\n{{chart|Txt|Txt=This family tree is partly derived from the Abercorn pedigree pictured in Cokayne.{{sfn|Cokayne|1910|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo01coka/page/4/ 4]|ps=: \"Tabular pedigree of the Earls of Abercorn\"}} Also see the lists of siblings and children in the text.|boxstyle_Txt=border: 0 solid white; text-align: left;}}\n{{chart/end}}\n{{chart_bottom}}\n</div>\n\n==Early life==\nOn 28 November 1547, John, still a boy, was appointed [[Commendator]] of [[Inchaffray Abbey]],{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/370/ 370, line 30]|ps=: \"At a comparably early age he was provided to the abbacy of Inchaffray, the Consistorial Act in his favour being dated 28 November 1547, when he is said to be aged twelve, but his age is variously stated ...\"}} a position he held until 1551, when he was made [[Abbot of Arbroath|Commendator of Arbroath]] instead.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 4]|ps=: \"... and was on 4 September of that year [1551] provided to the rich and extensive abbacy of Arbroath.\"}} He had the benefit of Arbroath until 1579, although his right was disputed by [[George Douglas (bishop)|George Douglas]] (a natural son of the [[Archibald Douglas, 6th Earl of Angus|Earl of Angus]] who would later become [[Bishop of Moray]]).{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 8]|ps=: \"... though his possession was much disturbed by George Douglas, a natural son of the sixth Earl of Angus who claimed the abbacy as a postulate.\"}}\n\nHis family supported [[Mary, Queen of Scots]], even after her imprisonment at [[Lochleven Castle]], her abdication in favour of her one-year-old son on 24 July 1567, her defeat at [[Battle of Langside|Langside]] in 1568 and her flight to England shortly afterwards. In 1570 [[James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray|Moray]], who was regent during part of the minority of [[King James VI and I|King VI]], was assassinated by [[James Hamilton (assassin)|John Hamilton of Bothwellhaugh]], a supporter of Queen Mary, at [[Linlithgow]].{{sfn|Fraser|1970|p=[https://archive.org/details/maryqueenofscots0000anto/page/498/ 498]|ps=: \"... on 11th January, 1570, the regent Moray fell dead, struck down by the bullets of an assassin in the main street at Lithlingow;\"}} John's father (the Duke of Ch\u00e2tellerault and 2nd Earl of Arran) had been imprisoned by Murray at the time and John himself might have had a hand in the murder.{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/193/ 193, left column, line 11]|ps=: \"... and it was doubtless to revenge this that he [John] and his family furthered the plot for the assassination of the regent Moray ...\"}} His successor, Regent [[Matthew Stewart, 4th Earl of Lennox|Lennox]], died in 1571 from a shot in his back during a skirmish at Stirling with the Queen's party.{{sfn|Marshall|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613741/page/865/ 865, left column, line 36]|ps= \"Mathew Stewart, 13th earl of Lennox, the Hamilton's hereditary enemy, was chosen to be the next regent but the following year he was shot in the back during a skirmish at Stirling castle and died&nbsp;...\"}} Finally, on 23 February 1573, his father gave up his support for Mary and recognised Mary's infant son [[James VI of Scotland|James]] as King of Scotland.{{sfn|Dunlop|1890|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/170/ 170, right column, line 15]|ps=: \"... till 23 Feb. 1573, when action in union with the Earl of Huntly, heconsented to acknowledge the king's authority and lay down his sword.}}\n\n==Head of the family==\nHis father died at Hamilton on 22 January 1575.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/368/ 368, line 28]|ps=: \"... died at Hamilton on 22 January 1574-75.\"}} His older brother James succeeded as the 3rd Earl of Arran, but because of his insanity, he was placed under John's care{{sfn|Henderson|1890a|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/176/ 176, left column]|ps=: \"On the death of his father in 1575, he came into nominal possession of his estates, which were, however, administrated by his second brother, John ...\"}} making John the de facto Earl and head of the family.{{sfn|Marshall|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613741/page/865/ 865, left column column]|ps=: \"... Lord John became in effect the head of the house of Hamilton and heir to the Scottish throne.\"}}\n\n==Marriage and children==\nOn 30 December 1577 John contracted to marry Margaret Lyon, Countess of Cassilis, the widow of [[Gilbert Kennedy, 4th Earl of Cassilis]], and daughter of [[John Lyon, 7th Lord Glamis]],{{sfn|Groome|1892|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio54stepgoog/page/n429/ 419]|ps=: \"... in 1566 he [Gilbert Kennedy] married Margaret Lyon, only daughter of John, seventh lord Glamis ...\"}} promising to marry her before 10 February 1578.{{sfn|Fraser|1887|p=54|ps=: \"113:Contract of marriage between Lord John Hamilton, Commendator of Arbroath, brother-german and apparent heir of James Earl of Arran, on one part and Dame Margaret Lyon, Countess of Cassillis, and others, on the other part. The parties agree to marry each other before the&nbsp;...\"}}{{sfn|Groome|1892|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio54stepgoog/page/n430/ 420, left column, line 49]|ps=: \"His widow afterwards married John, first marquis of Hamilton.\"}} His wife was an staunch Protestant. She had converted her first husband who had been a Catholic before their marriage.{{sfn|Groome|1892|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionarynatio54stepgoog/page/n429/ 419, right column, line 30]|ps=: \"... and by her persuasion he became a protestant and caused to reform his churches in Carrick&nbsp;...\"}}\n\nThey had three children:\n*Edward, who died in infancy;{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/195/ 195, left column, line 5]|ps=: \"... an elder son Edward who died young.\"}}\n*[[James Hamilton, 2nd Marquess of Hamilton|James]] (1589\u20131625), who succeeded him as the 2nd Marquess of Hamilton;{{sfn|Marshall|2004|p=[https://archive.org/details/isbn_0198613741/page/865/ 865, right column]|ps=: \"His eldest son, James Hamilton, was born in1589.\"}} and\n*Margaret, who married [[John Maxwell, 9th Lord Maxwell]].{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/195/ 195, left column, line 6]|ps=: \"... and a daughter, Lady Margaret, married to John, eighth lord Maxwell.\"}}\n\nHamilton also had two illegitimate children:\n*Margaret Hamilton, who married Sir Humphrey Colquhoun of Luss;{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/195/ 195, left column, line 10]|ps=: \"... and a natural daughter, Jean, who married Sir Umfra Colquhoun of Luss.\"}} and\n*Sir John Hamilton of Letterick, from whom descended the [[Lord Bargany|Lords Bargany]].{{sfn|Henderson|1890b|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati25stepuoft/page/195/ 195, left column, line 8]|ps=: \"He had also a natural son, Sir John Hamilton of Lettrick, father of the first lord Bargeny&nbsp;...\"}}\n\n==Forfeiture and English Exile==\nIn 1579 [[James Douglas, 4th Earl of Morton]] accused John and his younger brother Claud to have been implicated in the murders of the regents Moray and Lennox and obtained that John and Claud were included in the Scottish Act of forfeiture of 1579. In consequence John lost his income from the abbey of Arbroath{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 17]|ps=: \"... in the forfeiture of the Hamilton estates in 1579, when his own possessions of Arbroath were affected ...\"}} and had to leave the country. He fled first to England, then to France. He returned to England and there stayed with his brother Claud in the North. While in England he reconciled himself with [[Archibald Douglas, 8th Earl of Angus]]{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 28]|ps=: \"The Hamiltons became reconciled to the Earl of Angus, then also in exile&nbsp;...\"}} who was also in exile there due to his association with the [[Raid of Ruthven]]. King James had by now come under the influence of [[James Stewart, Earl of Arran|James Stewart of Bothwellmuir]], to whom the King had granted Hamilton's brother's earldom of Arran.{{sfn|Henderson|1898|p=[https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati54stepuoft/page/308/ 308, right column, line 9]|ps=: \"On 22 April 1581 he obtained grant of the earldom of Arran in Bute, the lands and barony of Hamilton in Lanark ...\"}}\n\n==Back in Scotland==\nJohn, with Angus, the [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|Earl of Mar]], and the [[Thomas Lyon (of Auldbar)|Master of Glamis]] and with the connivance of [[Elizabeth I of England]], raised an army and entered Scotland, reaching [[Stirling]] in October 1585. James Stewart of Bothwellmuir fled and King James capitulated on 4 November, receiving the banished lords into his presence.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/371/ 371, line 33]|ps=: \"... the banished lords were on 4 November 1585 admitted to the King's presence, who ... welcomed Lord John with special cordiality&nbsp;...\"}}\n\nAt a parliament convened at [[Linlithgow]] on 1 December 1585, King James rescinded Hamilton's forfeiture and restored him and the other lords to their previously held lands. Further Hamilton was raised to the [[Privy Council of Scotland|Privy Council]] and made captain of [[Dumbarton Castle]].<ref>[http://www.rps.ac.uk/ Acts of Parliament 1 December 1585]</ref> In April 1590 he visited [[Dalkeith Palace]] and when the gardener tried to stop him taking a horse, Hamilton's servant shot him.<ref>''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 10 (Edinburgh, 1936), p. 274.</ref>\n\nIn 1588 John founded a grammar school that became known as [[Hamilton Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hamilton.s-lanark.sch.uk/head-teacher-appointment/ |title=Head Teacher Appointment |last=Stewart |first=C |date=9 March 2016 |website=Hamilton Grammar School |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630105741/http://www.hamilton.s-lanark.sch.uk/head-teacher-appointment/ |archive-date=30 June 2016}}</ref> In 1972 this school became the [[Hamilton Grammar School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/local-news/former-hamilton-academy-pupils-hold-5652789 |title=Former Hamilton Academy pupils hold 60th anniversary reunion}}</ref>\n\n==Marquess==\nHamilton continued to rise in the King's favour, and on 15 April 1599, following the baptism of Princess Margaret at [[Holyroodhouse]], he was created ''Marquess of Hamilton, Earl of Arran and Lord Aven''.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/372/ 372, line 24]|ps=: \"... on 17 April, he and the Earl of Huntly were, with great ceremony, at his Majesty's great chamber at Holyrood installed in their proper places, his title being proclaimed MARQUESS OF HAMILTON, EARL OF ARRAN, and Lord EVAN.\"}} In August 1602 he hosted the French ambassador, the [[Charles Cauchon de Maupas|Baron de Tour]] at Hamilton Palace, who hunted with the king and the [[Ludovic Stewart, 2nd Duke of Lennox|Duke of Lennox]] and played a card game called \"mawe\".<ref>J. D. Mackie, ''Calendar State Papers Scotland'', vol. 13 (Edinburgh, 1969), p. 1040.</ref>\n\n==Death and succession==\nThe Marquess died before his elder brother in April 1604.{{sfn|Paul|1907|p=[https://archive.org/details/scotspeeragefoun04paul/page/372/ 372, line 29]|ps=: \"... dying 6 April 1604, his last act being to recommend his son to the King's favour.\"}}{{sfn|Cokayne|1892|p=[https://archive.org/details/completepeerage04cokahrish/page/n138/ 141, line 7]|ps=: \"He died (bfore his elder br. James, Earl of Arran and Lord Hamilton [S.] above mentioned) 12 April 1604, aged about 70.\"}} He was immediately succeeded by his son James as the 2nd Marquess of Hamilton. James also succeeded as the 4th Earl of Arran in 1609 upon James's death.{{sfn|Debrett|1828|p=[https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/page/n21/ 443, line 18]|ps=: \"JAMES, 2nd Marquess, K.G., who, on the death of his uncle, James, 1609, became also 4th earl of Arran ...\"}}\n\n{| {{Table|hide}}\n!colspan=3|Timeline\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Age!!align=\"left\"|Date!!align=\"left\"|Event\n|-\n|0||1540||Born, probably in [[Hamilton, South Lanarkshire|Hamilton]], Lanarkshire, Scotland.\n|-\n|7||1547, 28 Nov||Made [[Commendator]] of [[Inchaffray Abbey]] while still a boy.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage370 370, line 30]\"/>\n|-\n|11||1551, 4 Sep||Made [[Commendator of Arbroath]] instead.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage371 371, line 4]\"/>\n|-\n|18||1568, 13 May||Mary loses the [[Battle of Langside]] and flees to England.\n|-\n|30||1570, 23 Jan||Regent [[James Stewart, 1st Earl of Moray|Moray]] assassinated; John and his family might have been involved.\n|-\n|31||1571, 4 Sep||Regent [[Matthew Stewart, 4th Earl of Lennox|Lennox]] killed.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEMarshall2004[httpsarchiveorgdetailsisbn_0198613741page865 865, left column, line 36]\"/>\n|-\n|35||1575, 22 Jan||His father died in Hamilton<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage368 368, line 28]\"/> and his brother succeeded as 3rd Earl of Arran, but as he was insane, John became earl de facto.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEMarshall2004[httpsarchiveorgdetailsisbn_0198613741page865 865, left column column]\"/>\n|-\n|38||1578, Jan or Feb||Marries Margaret Lyon.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEFraser188754\"/>\n|-\n|39||1579||John and Claud included in the Act of forfeiture.\n|-\n|42||1582, Aug||[[Raid of Ruthven]]\n|-\n|45||1585, 4 Nov||The King welcomes him back at [[Stirling]].\n|-\n|47||1587, 8 Feb||Mary, Queen of Scots executed at [[Fotheringhay Castle]], England.\n|-\n|59||1599, 15 Apr||Created Marquess of Hamilton.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage372 372, line 24]\"/>\n|-\n|64||1604, 6 Apr||Died.<ref name=\"FOOTNOTEPaul1907[httpsarchiveorgdetailsscotspeeragefoun04paulpage372 372, line 29]\"/>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n*{{citation|last=Burke |first=Bernard |author-link=Bernard Burke |date=1869 |title=A Genealogical and Heraldic Dictionary of the Peerage and Baronetage of the British Empire |edition=31st |publisher=Harrison |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/genealogicalhera00inburk/}}\n*{{citation|last=Cokayne |first=George Edward |author-link=George Edward Cokayne |editor-last=Gibbs |editor-first=Vicary |editor-link=Vicary Gibbs (St Albans MP) |date=1910 |title=The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant |edition=2nd |volume=1 AB-ADAM to BASING |publisher=St Catherine Press |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/completepeerageo01coka/}} (for Arran)\n*{{citation|last=Cokayne |first=George Edward |author-link=George Edward Cokayne |date=1892 |title=The complete peerage of England, Scotland, Ireland, Great Britain and the United Kingdom, extant, extinct, or dormant |edition=1st |volume=4 |publisher=George Bell and Sons |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/completepeerage04cokahrish/}} \u2013 G to K (for Hamilton)\n*{{citation|last=Debrett |first=John |author-link=John Debrett |date=1828 |title=Peerage of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland |edition=17th |volume=2 |publisher=F. C. and J. Rivington |publication-place=London |url=https://archive.org/details/debrettspeerage01debrgoog/}} - Scotland an